<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, April 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Won't Sell Destroyers to Taiwan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, backed by his senior advisers, decided
Monday against the sale of four Aegis destroyers to Taiwan, but approved a
smaller package including long-range radar designed to detect missile launches,
two senior U.S. officials said. Clinton acted on the recommendation of top
advisers who met earlier in the day at the White House. The Pentagon had
recommended that the administration put off Taiwan's request to buy new weapons,
including the destroyers, submarines and anti-submarine aircraft, in order to
avoid angering China, which views Taiwan as a rebellious province.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
High Court Expands Passengers' Rights
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court ruled Monday that police officers must
get travelers' consent or a court warrant before squeezing their luggage to see
if drugs might be inside. The 7-2 decision in a Texas case said a U.S. Border
Patrol agent who felt a bus passenger's bag violated the Constitution's Fourth
Amendment ban on unreasonable searches. The bag later was found to contain
drugs. The ruling expands public transit passengers' privacy rights, but the
National Association of Police Organizations said it was disappointed by the
ruling.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
IMF Protesters Disrupt Capital
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Demonstrators disrupted the workday in much of the
nation's capital Monday, but they failed to shut down the two days of meetings
of the World Bank and International Monetary Fund. About 600 people were
arrested Monday, bringing the total to more than 1,300 since the protests began.
The protesters accused the bank and IMF of imposing crushing debts on poor
nations, destroying the environment and perpetrating a host of other ills. World
Bank spokeswoman Caroline Ansety said officials in the meetings felt
''bewilderment and surprise at the degree of anger'' outside. She said the
officials were talking about ways to relieve poverty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuban Americans Await Elian's Fate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- On the 39th anniversary of the Bay of Pigs fiasco, Cuban
Americans in Miami stood watch at the home where Elian Gonzalez's relatives
waited for a key ruling in the custody fight. Protesters recalled the deadly
attempt on April 17, 1961, in which CIA-trained exiles failed to invade Cuba.
Their criticism was extended to the Clinton administration, which wants the
6-year-old Cuban boy returned to his Cuban father. The boy's Miami relatives say
he will have a better life here. Both sides were awaiting a ruling from the 11th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta. The government wants the court to lift
an order that bars Elian's removal from the United States and to order Elian's
great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez to release the boy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Leader Confident on Khmer Rouge Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- On the 25th anniversary of the Khmer Rouge
takeover of Cambodia, Prime Minister Hun Sen said Monday an agreement may
finally be at hand to set up a court to prosecute the movement's former leaders
whose reign of terror killed 1.7 million people. Hun Sen said he backed a
U.S.-suggested compromise that appears to resolve the sensitive issue of how to
conduct indictments. The United Nations and Cambodia have been negotiating the
formation of a tribunal for more than a year, but talks have foundered over
which side would control indictments and rulings.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AltaVista Co. Postpones IPO
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- AltaVista Co., the owner of a widely used Internet
search engine and several other popular Web sites, has postponed plans to raise
$281 million in an initial public offering of its stock. The decision,
attributed to ''market conditions,'' came following last week's tech stock
selloff, which was especially hard on Internet companies. For instance, Yahoo
Inc, which runs the world's most popular Internet search engine, dropped 23
percent last week amid a massive selloff on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Tokyo stock market's main index fell Tuesday morning adding
to Monday's big losses, despite a rebound on Wall Street. The Nikkei, which was
up some 300 points early in the session, fell 103.99 points, to 18,904.65 at the
end of the morning session. On Monday, the average closed down a huge 1,426.04
points, or 6.98 percent after a record drop Friday on Wall Street. In New York
on Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 276.74 points to 10,582.51. The
technology-rich Nasdaq composite soared 217.87 points to 3,589.16.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senators 4, Maple Leafs 3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KANATA, Ontario (AP) -- Rob Zamuner's second goal of the game past an angry
Curtis Joseph helped the Ottawa Senators end an eight-game playoff losing streak
with a 4-3 victory Monday night over the Toronto Maple Leafs. The Leafs still
lead 2-1 in the best-of-7 Eastern Conference first-round series. Game 4 is
Wednesday night at the Corel Centre.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief By BRAD FOSS
</SUBHEAD>
