<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grenada Bank Raises Eyebrows  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE FAUL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) -- It sounds like an investor's dream:
profits of 250 percent, tax-free, from a discreet and distant
offshore bank. And First International Bank of Grenada -- a magnet
for hundreds of Americans willing to part with millions of dollars
-- is extraordinary in other ways too.
</P>
<P>
   Grenadian officials say the bank was capitalized in this former
British Caribbean colony on the strength of a jeweler's $20 million
appraisal of one ruby. They confirm its founder once went broke in
Oregon, bought a Grenada passport and changed his name. And its
reported income -- hotly contested -- would rank it among banking
heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders say the bank pays up, and is simply an original-minded
player in a dynamic globalizing economy. Critics suspect pyramid
schemes and money laundering, and see it as a symbol of the dangers
of poorly regulated offshore banking.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, First International Bank has drawn
considerable attention with an unorthodox effort to establish a
sphere of influence in the Congo, whose vast mineral wealth has
drawn forces from five countries into a civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ''First International Bank of Grenada makes a mockery of the
island as a legitimate financial center,'' wrote Offshore Alert, a
leading Miami-based industry newsletter being sued by the bank's
owners for libel.
</P>
<P>
   Grenada's offshore industry regulator, Michael Creft, says he
doesn't know whether the bank's claims of $26 billion in gross
income in its first full year of business last year are true. That
would put it roughly on par with Chicago-based Bank One Corp., the
fifth-largest bank in the United States, with 1999 revenue of $26
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The local government is investigating charges of illicit
practices by First International Bank, which has drawn the notice
of U.S. authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is an ongoing investigation being coordinated with the
FBI through the U.S. Department of Justice,'' said Nancy McGuire,
spokeswoman for Premier Keith Mitchell, who has repeatedly defended
the bank. ''They have already provided us with some information
which has caused us to request information from the bank, and the
investigation is continuing.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and Department of Justice did not respond to repeated
requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Creft said the investigation included the possibility of money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
   The bank, licensed in Grenada in October 1998, is owned by Van
A. Brink, who was called Gilbert Allen Ziegler when he lived in
Oregon and declared bankruptcy in 1994, according to Creft.
</P>
<P>
   Brink and the bank did not respond to repeated requests for an
interview. The bank said Brink was in Uganda -- a player in the
Congo war -- where he has bought a mansion that used to belong to
dictator Idi Amin.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse interview last year with Grenada's government-owned
radio, Brink said: ''I can just tell you that First (International)
Bank is doing legitimate business. It is acting lawfully.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank fired an external auditor last year after a
disagreement over its practices. In a letter made available to The
Associated Press, Lauriston Wilson, the auditor, wrote to the prime
minister saying he had ''suspicions that the bank's assets were
bogus and fictitious.''
</P>
<P>
   Creft said a subsequent, external audit presented by the bank
was conducted by an ''unqualified'' American, who had been ordered
not to practice in some U.S. states.
</P>
<P>
   Creft said he was going to order another audit.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the bank goes about its business.
</P>
<P>
   Every month, First International Bank pays for hundreds of
Americans to come to the island and woos them at upscale beach
resorts with lectures on the evils of U.S. taxation, Creft said.
Prospects are assured their money is insured by the International
Deposit Indemnity Corp. -- a small private operation that was closed
down by regulators in the tiny island of Nevis a year ago, was
again shut down in Dominica and now operates here.
</P>
<P>
   Creft said First International Bank has made good on promises to
pay up to 250 percent interest, but he didn't know how the bank
does it.
</P>
<P>
   If the bank -- one of the first offshore businesses licensed here
-- were registering now, ''there would be much more due diligence
and we would be much more careful,'' Creft said.
</P>
<P>
   Brink now appears ready to spread his influence to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Brink tried to buy a cooperative bank from the Uganda
government, which turned him down, saying he was not a qualified
banker.
</P>
<P>
   In January, First International Bank signed a deal with a group
of tribal chiefs brought over from the Congo. That agreement gives
Prince Willie Mashiki and his coterie $80 million in exchange for
control over the mineral resources in the areas they claim to
control.
</P>
<P>
   Wamba dia Wamba, a Congo rebel leader who signed a deal with the
bank in November, dismissed suspicions against Brink as part of an
assault on offshore banking by developed nations trying to retain
control over capital.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any time you have a fundamental change in the world economy,
in this case a shift from classical banks to offshore banks, there
are sure to be clashes,'' said the former Harvard University
lecturer, who sold the bank exclusive rights to set up a central
bank should he take power, for $16 million.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   First International Bank of Grenada: http://www.firstbank.to
</P>
<P>
   Offshore Alert newsletter: http://offshorebusiness.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
