<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schumer and Spitzer: Count us out of governor's race  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Sen. Charles Schumer and state Attorney
General Eliot Spitzer say they have no interest in running for
governor in two years, even if fellow Democrats state Comptroller
H. Carl McCall and federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo are out
of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   The comments Monday from the New York Democrats came after the
New York Post reported that both McCall and Cuomo could be up for
high-level administration jobs if Vice President Al Gore wins the
White House. That, said the Post, could set up a run for governor
by Schumer and a possible primary challenge from Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   McCall has told some supporters he plans to run for governor
while Cuomo, the eldest son of former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo,
has said he is thinking about the race. McCall and the younger
Cuomo have said they won't make public announcements about their
political plans until after this November's elections.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that Gore might seek to give Cuomo a
leg up on the governor's race by dangling a high-level federal post
in front of McCall. But there has also been speculation that Gore
might want Cuomo as his White House chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   The Post report indicated Gore might want both working in
Washington, leaving the field open for others.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer and Spitzer both began their current jobs in 1998,
unseating, respectively, Republican incumbents Alfonse D'Amato and
Dennis Vacco.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer told Albany's WROW-AM radio that he laughed when he read
the Post report.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just love this job too much,'' the attorney general said.
''This is a job for a lawyer who's dedicated to holding this job
for at least an eight-year period.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said that if McCall and Cuomo were tapped for a Gore
administration and Schumer wanted to run for governor, ''I'll be
all for him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer's press secretary said the senator had no intention
of running for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's happy being senator,'' Cathie Levine said. ''That's all
he's interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer was preparing to run for governor in 1998 before he
changed gears more than a year before the election in the face of
Republican Gov. George Pataki's strong poll numbers and hefty
campaign bank account. Schumer decided D'Amato was more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, who won easy re-election over New York City Council
Speaker Peter Vallone, has said he may want to seek a third term in
2002. Pataki beat the elder Cuomo in 1994 to become governor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 0021 </TRAILER>
