<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate passes bill requiring 'fire-safe' cigarettes  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Gov. George Pataki is not saying what he
will do with a bill sent him by the Legislature requiring that only
so-called fire-safe cigarettes be sold in New York state starting
in April 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll take a look at it when we get it,'' Pataki spokesman
Michael McKeon said Monday, when the state Senate gave final
legislative approval to the bill 60-0.
</P>
<P>
   By mandating self-extinguishing cigarettes, advocates say the
state would save the lives of careless smokers, of the people
living around them and of firefighters responding to the blazes
they set.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill will help end the carnage here in New York state''
and pressure Congress into adopting similar national standards,
Joseph Bruno, majority leader of the state Senate, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The chief Senate sponsor of the bill, Sen. Frank Padavan,
R-Queens, said the legislation is the first of its kind in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno surprised longtime advocates of self-extinguishing
cigarette legislation last week by announcing his
Republican-controlled house would approve the measure. In previous
years, the measure had passed in the Democrat-controlled Assembly
but died in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Richard Dollinger, D-Rochester, said the Legislature
should have acted in the late 1980s, when federal studies indicated
a self-extinguishing cigarette was possible.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fewer people would have died,'' Dollinger said. ''Fewer people
would have been scarred. There would have been fewer property
losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Three tobacco manufacturers -- Brown &AMP; Williamson, Lorillard and
R.J. Reynolds -- released a joint statement Monday calling the New
York measure ''shortsighted and ill-advised.'' They said research
is unclear whether the self-extinguishing cigarettes produce more
nicotine, tar and carbon monoxide than cigarettes do currently or
whether smokers will actually smoke them.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the problems we have is we have consumer lines that
answer customer calls all the time,'' spokesman Mark Smith of Brown
&AMP; Williamson said. ''One out of 10 has to deal with a product that
goes out while somebody is smoking. ... While someone might mandate
a certain kind of cigarette, if consumers don't smoke it, then
what's the point?''
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco companies said programs educating people about the
dangers of careless smoking plus anti-fire programs, such as the
development of flame-retardant furniture and mattresses, have been
successful at curbing smoking-related fire deaths by 50 percent
over the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that cigarette-related fires account for about
1,000 deaths and 3,000 injuries a year nationally. Experts say such
fires -- typically igniting mattresses and upholstered furniture
when smokers fall asleep with lighted cigarettes -- are the leading
cause of fire deaths in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's chief lobbyist in Albany
urged senators to approve the measure Monday, blaming 31 of the 112
fire deaths in the city in 1999 on fires ignited by cigarettes. In
1998, three city firemen were killed while searching for elderly
victims of a cigarette-related fire in a Brooklyn building,
lobbyist Anthony Piscitelli noted.
</P>
<P>
   Under the measure, tobacco companies would be required to make
cigarettes that stop burning if they're not smoked within a certain
time. Standards would also be established about acceptable
fire-starting capabilities of cigarettes when they come into
contact with different fabrics and other materials.
</P>
<P>
   The state Office of Fire Prevention and Control would develop
the self-extinguishing cigarette standards with help from the state
Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   If signed into law, the measure would go into effect April 1,
2001. The industry would be required to stop marketing
non-self-extinguishing cigarettes in New York one year after that
date.
</P>
<P>
   Padavan and other advocates for the legislation in New York
insisted that the technology has arrived for the tobacco industry
to make a self-extinguishing cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   ''For years, cigarette makers have had the ability to market
products that burn cooler, self-extinguish when they're not being
smoked and are less likely to ignite blazes,'' Padavan said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Haven of the New York Public Interest Research Group
said more than 100 patents have been taken out on
self-extinguishing cigarette technology.
</P>
<P>
   Among the techniques to produce a ''cooler'' burn in cigarettes
is to make the paper they are wrapped in less porous or to elongate
the size of the cigarette, Haven said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 0021 </TRAILER>
