<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax-cut package takes shape in new budget  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State leaders have agreed to reduce an
unpopular tax which touches upon the lives of most New Yorkers in
the new budget for fiscal 2000-01.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki and legislative leaders made a deal Monday
night to cut New York's gross receipts tax on energy.
</P>
<P>
   Though the tax is imposed on all electricity and natural gas
users, business interests say it falls most heavily on the
operators of power-hungry manufacturing plants in New York. The
deal among state leaders, as outlined Monday by people close to the
negotiations, provides for the tax to be eliminated for the big
manufacturers, and for those kinds of companies to get refunds of
the gross receipts taxes they've paid since Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki called for such a reduction in his State of the State
address in January, and he and legislative leaders have all been in
favor of some form of gross receipts tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the tax-cut agreement said the new budget will
also include a reduction in the gross receipts tax for
non-manufacturing commercial customers over five years and for a
reduction in the tax charged to residential electric ratepayers of
$75 million immediately and $50 million to be phased in over the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The gross receipts tax is among the most unpopular taxes within
the state's business community, with executives long claiming it
puts New York companies at a disadvantage to those in other states
where there is no such tax.
</P>
<P>
   An elimination of the tax would save industrial-grade power
users $4,600 a year, legislative aides estimated.
</P>
<P>
   An immediate reduction for residential ratepayers of about 25
percent, as the agreement calls for, would save New Yorkers about
$1.25 a month on their power bills. There would also be monthly
savings of a little under one dollar for typical residential
natural gas customers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Legislature and Pataki approved a reduction of the
4-cent-per-$1 tax on electricity bills, which became fully
effective in January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In all, legislative leaders and Pataki agreed the state could
afford to institute $1.2 billion in tax cuts in the 2000-01 budget.
That cost is when the taxes are fully phased in over five years.
The price tag in the first fiscal year is expected to be in the
range of $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   In other tax-related agreements, according to sources Monday
night:
</P>
<P>
   --The state's ''marriage penalty'' will be eliminated by
increasing the standard deduction on state income taxes from
$13,000 to $15,000. That change will save typical married couples
about $140 a year and bring their tax bill into line with what two
unmarried adults living together would pay. Estimated savings when
phased in over five years: $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   --Regardless of income, residents with children in college will
be able to deduct up to $10,000 of their schooling costs, whether
they attend public or private schools, on state income taxes.
Estimated savings when phased in over five years: $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   --The state's Earned Income Tax Credit for working and
lower-middle-class poor will be increased. Estimated savings: $125
million, with almost all of the costs being picked up by the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   --The state's current Enterprise Zone program creating low-tax,
business-friendly enclaves in struggling parts of the state will be
retooled and expanded to tax-free ''Empire Zones.''
</P>
<P>
   If the agreement holds and is enacted in the final budget, there
is something for all the state leaders in the tax package.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno pushed hard for
gross receipts tax reductions. Initially, Assembly Speaker Sheldon
Silver did not want any cuts to the portion of the tax charged to
residential ratepayers, but sources said he ended up championing
inclusion of home and apartment ratepayers during negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno was a strong proponent of the college tuition tax credit
and both he and Silver backed Earned Income Tax Credit
improvements. Senate Minority Leader Martin Connor and Silver had
advocated for elimination of the marriage penalty. Silver wanted to
see the ''Empire Zone'' program instituted.
</P>
<P>
   Connor's counterpart in the state Assembly, Assembly Republican
leader John Faso, had agitated for the gross receipts tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders have also agreed to renew the Power for Jobs
program, which provides lower-cost electricity to manufacturers and
other big users like hospitals and commercial businesses, over the
next three years. The plan calls for 300 megawatts of power to be
provided at a cost of $240 million, sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
