<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oswego's Safe Haven to be a TV miniseries  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OSWEGO, N.Y. (AP) -- One of World War II's best-kept secrets is
about to get some serious exposure.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS television network will air a miniseries next February
about the nearly 1,000 refugees who sought a safe haven at Fort
Ontario in Oswego during the war. The fort was the only place in
America to house Holocaust survivors and other refugees who fled
the war's turmoil and destruction in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really a compelling story,'' said Judy Ranan, president
of Citadel Entertainment, a Los Angeles-based television production
company that is producing the four-hour series.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important to show that Americans learned tolerance and
accepted these people and embraced them,'' Ranan said.
</P>
<P>
   The two-night miniseries is based on ''Haven: The Unknown Story
of 1,000 World War II Refugees.'' It was written by Ruth Gruber, a
government worker who escorted the refugees to the fort.
</P>
<P>
   Gruber, now 88 and living in New York City, planned to return to
Oswego this week to speak at SUNY-Oswego about her experiences and
unveil a documentary about the refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   Academy Award-winning actors Ann Bancroft and Martin Landau will
play Gruber's parents in the miniseries. Gruber, a central
character, will be played by Natasha Richardson, daughter of
Vanessa Redgrave.
</P>
<P>
   ''The screenwriter made our relationship much more physical,''
said Gruber, adding that she didn't mind. ''They changed
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranan explained that the writer ''had to take some liberty to
make it a little more dramatic.'' She added that many of the
refugees in the series are not based on the real people.
</P>
<P>
   ''The characters are compiled,'' Ranan said. ''We don't have a
specific refugee in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Filming will begin in June in Toronto, because, Ranan said,
filming is cheaper there.
</P>
<P>
   A half-century ago, Oswego had factories, carefully-tended
gardens, hemlock sidewalks and brick streets, said Terry Prior,
curator and director of the Oswego County Historical Society. Prior
has been asked to find 40 to 50 photos from the period.
</P>
<P>
   Among the images that producers are interested in: the former
Fitzgibbons Boiler Works, which produced tanks for the Army during
World War II; the inside of the city's old high school, which has
been converted to condominiums; and the streetlights used at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers last month took a tour of the buildings and grounds
at Fort Ontario and looked at World War II-era photographs, said
Paul Lear, the fort's director.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees' wood-frame dormitories and many of the red brick
buildings at the fort were taken down in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Ontario is located on a windblown bluff overlooking Lake
Ontario that's packed with history. The site has had an outpost
since the French and Indian Wars of the mid-1700s.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our coming to Fort Ontario was very crucial in our lives,''
Paul Bokros told the Associated Press in an interview six years ago
commemorating the 50th anniversary of their arrival at the fort.
''I know it changed my life completely.''
</P>
<P>
   The refugees -- opera singers, lawyers and teachers who were
hand-picked by the government -- were transported from Allied-held
southern Italy to the United States aboard an Army troop ship. The
982 refugees from 17 countries had to dodge a Nazi submarine and
were buzzed by German warplanes on their way across the Atlantic
Ocean, Bokros said.
</P>
<P>
   A train carried them on the final leg of their journey -- from
Hoboken, N.J., to Oswego. Fewer than 200 of the former refugees are
alive today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 0022 </TRAILER>
