<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies 9, Diamondbacks 1  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Consecutive bunt singles by Larry Walker and Jeff
Cirillo highlighted a five-run first inning Monday night as the
Colorado Rockies pounded Omar Daal and the Arizona Diamondbacks
9-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies, who scored 14 runs without a homer in Sunday
night's 14-13 marathon victory over St. Louis, didn't get a home
run Monday, either. But they didn't need one to win for the fifth
time in six games.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Helton knocked in three runs with two singles, and six
other Rockies had two hits apiece, including winning pitcher Masato
Yoshii. Terry Shumpert had a triple and double with two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii (1-1) allowed one run and seven hits in seven innings. He
struck out two and walked two.
</P>
<P>
   Daal (0-1), who had strong performances but no decisions in his
first two outings, allowed eight runs -- seven earned -- and 13 hits
in 5 1-3 innings. He struck out two, walked two intentionally and
hit Jeff Cirillo to trigger a bench-clearing incident in the second
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lansing started the first-inning outburst with a one-out
single, then Walker and Cirillo put down perfect bunts in front of
ex-Rockie Lenny Harris at third base to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Helton followed with a two-run single, then Shumpert's RBI
double put Colorado up 3-0. A sacrifice fly by Neifi Perez made it
4-0. Daal intentionally walked Scott Servais to get to Yoshii,
whose RBI single put the Rockies ahead 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the second, Daal hit Cirillo between the
shoulders with a pitch. An angry Cirillo took a couple of steps
toward the mound, then pushed catcher Kelly Stinnett out of the
way. Both dugouts and bullpens emptied, but no punches were thrown.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado scored three more in the sixth. Harris' error on
Cirillo's hard grounder allowed one run to score, then Helton had
an RBI single off Erubiel Durazo's glove at first and Shumpert
drove across a run with a groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Finley's RBI single drove in Jay Bell for Arizona's lone
run in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Arizona optioned OF David Dellucci to Triple-A Tucson and
activated utility player Andy Fox, who had missed the first 12
games of the season with a hairline fracture in his left wrist. ...
Colorado was the only NL West team to have a winning record against
the Diamondbacks last season. ... Rockies OF Jeffrey Hammonds, who
has been out since injuring a hamstring on opening day, was sent to
the team's extended spring training camp in Tucson for
rehabilitation. ... Arizona SS Tony Womack missed the game to
attend his grandmother's funeral.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
