<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Rejects Cardinals Stadium Bill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- The state House rejected a bill Monday night
proposing a new stadium for the Arizona Cardinals, hours after the
Senate approved it.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on the $331 million stadium financing package was
33-25. One reconsideration vote is allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a close vote,'' Cardinals lobbyist Doug Cole said. ''Our
focus right now is to go back and talk with the people we've been
working with and have a reconsideration vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate gave its final approval earlier Monday with a 20-10
reconsideration vote that reversed a decision last week.
</P>
<P>
   Even if approved by the Legislature, the stadium plan still
needed approval by Gov. Jane Hull and Maricopa County voters before
a stadium could be built.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the money in the package would be used to promote
tourism, improve Cactus League spring training baseball stadiums
and build youth sports facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a good plan for Arizona voters,'' said Rep. Laura
Knaperek, R-Tempe. If the team wants to put such a plan on the
ballot, she said, ''I suggest the Cardinals start an initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the Cardinals would pay $85 million and the
Fiesta Bowl $10 million to build a 73,000-seat domed stadium with a
partially retractable roof and a slide-in grass field.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the money would come from increased taxes on rental
cars and hotel rooms plus stadium-related sales taxes and income
taxes on pro football players and Cardinals employees.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the Cardinals would have access to new money-making
opportunities, starting with naming rights to the stadium and other
advertising. The team also would be able to profit from luxury
seating, parking and concessions.
</P>
<P>
   While the Cardinals would still have to negotiate a lease to use
the building, the bill puts the responsibility for maintenance and
operational costs such as utilities and field preparations on the
stadium authority rather than the team.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals say they need a new stadium and the revenue that
comes with it to remain financially competitive in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am absolutely sure if this goes down, and it well may, the
Cardinals will leave,'' said Rep. Richard Kyle, R-Phoenix, who
voted for the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Since moving to Arizona from St. Louis 12 years ago, the
Cardinals have played at Arizona State University's Sun Devil
Stadium. Last season, they were the only NFL team playing home
games in a college stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-18-00 0047 </TRAILER>
