<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Wings 2, Kings 1  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Two costly high-sticking penalties proved
devastating to the Los Angeles Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Fedorov and Tomas Holmstrom scored power-play goals as
the Detroit Red Wings defeated the Kings 2-1 Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   With Scotty Bowman behind the bench for his 99th playoff game as
Detroit coach, the Red Wings took a commanding 3-0 lead in the
best-of-7 Western Conference first-round series. Game 4 is
Wednesday at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Chris Osgood made 21 saves in front of a sellout crowd
of 18,118 that included numerous fans dressed in the Red Wings' red
and white colors on a night when the Kings urged their fans to
dress in black. Stephane Fiset, peppered for five goals in less
than two periods in an 8-5 loss in Game 2, stopped 22 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Since going 0-for-6 on the power play in a 2-0 victory in Game
1, the Red Wings have scored five power-play goals. The Kings
failed on all seven of their power-play opportunities, making them
0-for-15 in the series.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings led 1-0 on Fedorov's 40th career playoff goal and
second of the series at 5:21 of the first period when Detroit
skated with a two-man advantage. Jozef Stumpel was penalized for
roughing, then Rob Blake was sent off for high-sticking on
Holmstrom to set up Fedorov's goal that beat Fiset stick side.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, which has never rebounded from a 3-0 deficit in the
playoffs, failed to capitalize on a double-minor assessed to Darren
McCarty early in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   With McCarty off four minutes for tripping and unsportsmanlike
conduct, the Kings managed just one shot. Ziggy Palffy got ahead of
Nicklas Lidstrom heading to the net, but his shot went straight
into Osgood's pads.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings led 2-0 on Holmstrom's power-play goal at 14:40 of
the second. He redirected a slap shot inside the blue line by
Lidstrom with Bryan Smolinski off for high-sticking. They were
2-for-6 on the power play in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings made it 2-1 when Luc Robitaille scored his 49th career
playoff goal and second of the series, beating Osgood between his
pads at 2:35 of the third.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Chartrand nearly tied it for the Kings 2{ minutes later,
but Osgood collapsed on his left side to stop Chartrand's shot from
close in.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles had another excellent chance to tie with 7:23
remaining, but Craig Johnson, in front of Osgood, tipped a shot
wide by teammate Ian Laperriere. Fiset made consecutive saves on
Steve Yzerman with less than five minutes remaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
