<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lobster conference seeks reasons for dieoff  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Fishing the New York side of Long Island
Sound on Sept. 14, Joe Finke pulled in 244 pounds of lobster. On
Oct. 8, his catch weighed just 44 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Finke was one of about 250 lobstermen, environmentalists and
scientists who gathered in Stamford on Monday for a two-day
''lobster health symposium'' aimed at finding the cause of the high
lobster mortality.
</P>
<P>
   The lobstermen, who came from both the Connecticut and New York
sides of the sound, told stories of financial despair and
frustration. Although estimates on how many lobsters have been
killed vary, Makowsky said he agreed with one that puts the recent
mortality rate at between 90 percent and 96 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Burt, a lobster dealer in East Norwalk, said the recent
increase in mortality has given Long Island Sound lobsters a a bad
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's gotten to the point where I have ... customers who will
not buy Long Island Sound lobsters at any price,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The dieoff has been concentrated in the western part of the
sound. Lobstermen on the eastern end of the sound said they did not
see a similar mortality rate.
</P>
<P>
   University of Connecticut scientists have found a parasite
called a paramoeba that is infecting the lobsters, but are checking
whether other factors, such as pollution or contamination of the
sound, is contributing to the dieoff.
</P>
<P>
   Members of a New York-based fisheries conservation group, FISH
Unlimited Inc., believe it may have been caused by contaminated
dredge material that was dumped into Western Long Island Sound last
fall from Mamaroneck Harbor, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, officials in New York and Connecticut
were spraying pesticides to prevent the spread of the West Nile
encephalitis outbreak. The group believes that heavy rains from
Hurricane Floyd in September may have washed the pesticides into
the sound.
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with five lobstermen's associations, FISH
Unlimited is planning to collect dead lobsters and sediment from
the sound and submit the samples to an independent laboratory for
testing.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers in both New York and Connecticut have lobbied for
money to help the lobstermen.
</P>
<P>
   The Long Island Sound is the No. 3 lobster market behind Maine
and Massachusetts. Connecticut brings in about 3.5 million pounds a
year, while New York brings in about 8.5 million pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Frate Jr., a lobsterman who fishes in Stamford and Darien,
said whatever has been causing the lobsters to die is still present
in the sound.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not see the problem being over,'' he said. ''They're
still dying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 0100 </TRAILER>
