<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge rejects mistrial for man accused in boy witness killing  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- The trial of a man charged in the
murders of an 8-year-old witness and his mother will go on as
scheduled, despite a letter in which the prosecution's star witness
claims she lied.
</P>
<P>
   A judge on Monday rejected a request to grant a mistrial to
Russell Peeler, who is accused of masterminding the killing of
Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and his mother, Karen Clarke. The mother
and son were gunned down in their Bridgeport home on Jan. 7, 1999,
a few months before B.J. was scheduled to testify against Peeler in
the 1998 killing of Clarke's boyfriend, Rudolph Snead Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Josephine Lee, who lived across the street from Clarke,
originally told police she acted as a lookout and watched as
Peeler's brother, Adrian, shot and killed B.J. and his mother. But
in a letter to her lawyer written in December, Lee changed her
story.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything that I have told them is lies,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers, who are being tried separately, each face a
possible death sentence if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's letter was disclosed to the defense last week during the
final phase of jury selection in Russell Peeler's case.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler's lawyers immediately filed a stack of motions, including
a request for a mistrial, immediate adjournment of the trial and a
continuance.
</P>
<P>
   But after hearing arguments Monday, Judge G. Sarsfield Ford
rejected all of the requests and said jury selection would continue
today.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're expected to react (to Lee's letter) and then proceed
without any additional time to prepare, and that's startling to me.
We're trying to save this man's life,'' said John Walkley, one of
Peeler's attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport State's Attorney Jonathan Benedict argued against a
mistrial or delay, characterizing Lee's letter as ''something like
a gift'' for the defense. He said Peeler's lawyers could use it to
attack her credibility during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would submit that a high school student could confront the
witness with that on no more than a day's notice,'' Benedict said.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict said the letter amounted to nothing more than ''cold
feet'' on the part of Lee. He said she has a terminal illness and
was hoping to get a shorter sentence so she doesn't have to die in
prison. In a plea bargain struck with prosecutors, Lee agreed to
testify against the Peeler brothers in exchange for a sentence of
no more than seven years.
</P>
<P>
   In their motions, Peeler's lawyers complained about the late
date of the disclosure of the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict said Lee had inadvertently included the letter to her
lawyer with several other letters she wrote to Bridgeport police
officers in December. He said when a police officer gave him the
letter, he immediately asked a judge to rule on whether it was
exculpatory -- information that could help prove Peeler's innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Ford made the letter available to the defense last week after
Lee agreed to waive her attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also rejected a series of other defense motions based on
Lee's letter, including: a renewed request to obtain Lee's medical
and psychiatric records; a request to withdraw Peeler's earlier
waiver of a probable cause hearing; a renewed request for an
inquiry into Lee's competency; and a request to give the defense
immediate access to Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also denied a request for Lee to be required to give a
new deposition. Lee's deposition was videotaped in November to
prepare for the possibility that she might die before the trial.
Ford denied the request without prejudice, meaning the defense can
renew the request again later.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict said it appears that Lee will be well enough to testify
during the trial, which could start as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   ''Her health is not a concern, and it's my understanding she's
ready to testify -- truthfully,'' Benedict said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford delayed a hearing on a defense request to dismiss the
charges based on Lee's letter until Wednesday because court copies
of the motion were illegible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 0101 </TRAILER>
