<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With BC-CT--ConEd-NU-Open Space  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) -- Northeast Utilities and Consolidated
Edison's merger proposal faces an uphill battle with the state
Department of Public Utility Control.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Glenn Arthur said Monday he could find no immediate
monetary benefit for consumers, unlike other big utility mergers
around the country that resulted in rate cuts and other perks.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur urged ConEd and NU to amend their merger proposal to
offer more to Connecticut customers, saying the current proposal
''is not a dead ringer for approval.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief executives of the companies said the merger will mean
lower rates and better service for customers in the long run, as
the companies find savings and boost efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will pass these savings along to consumers. We will have
benefits for consumers,'' said Michael Morris, chairman and chief
executive of NU.
</P>
<P>
   ConEd chairman Eugene McGrath said the combined company would
invest in the community and its work force. He defended the company
against questions about its handling of worker complaints and
environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our people do make mistakes from time to time. We try to learn
from them and move on,'' McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
   Any job cuts would be accomplished though attrition, McGrath and
Morris said. Each year, about 1,100 employees retire or leave the
company, and ConEd has a training center to help workers learn new
skills, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The DPUC plans 10 days of hearings on the $3.5 billion merger,
which would create the country's largest electric and gas
distribution company with more than 6.4 million customers in New
York and New England. A draft ruling is scheduled for June 2.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders approved the merger Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A key issue is how much the merger would cost and how the
combined company would pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase price is $1.5 billion over the book value of NU's
stock. To pay that premium, the company does not plan a rate
reduction for Connecticut customers until 2006 or later, Attorney
General Richard Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   Any savings should be passed on immediately, or the premium
should be decreased, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Morris noted that Connecticut consumers are enjoying a 10
percent rate reduction already under the state's electric
deregulation law. The rate cut is in effect until the end of 2003,
at which time the DPUC will hold hearings to set new rates.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Michael Wertheimer questioned ConEd's
record on protecting workers' rights and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   A fire in a transformer in September 1998 resulted in a release
of hazardous chemicals around firefighters, who later settled with
the company for $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1989 steam manhole explosion, 700 pounds of asbestos
contaminated the Manhattan neighborhood of Gramercy Park. The
company was convicted in 1995 of having deliberately concealed the
asbestos threat.
</P>
<P>
   ConEd agreed to a court order to maintain an environmental law
compliance program and to hire an ombudsman to investigate
suspected violations. Wertheimer said some company employees feared
retaliation for reporting environmental concerns after the
ombudsman left.
</P>
<P>
   Wertheimer also questioned ConEd's handling of a radiation leak
at the Indian Point II nuclear power plant in February and a
blackout in the Washington Heights section of New York City last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan businesses have sued ConEd for $50 million, accusing
the utility of discrimination and negligence during the blackout,
which left more than 200,000 people without power in the middle of
a heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath said the company had little choice but to shut off power
to the area because a large part of the system was out of service
from excessive heat.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Johnson from the Office of the Consumer Counsel criticized
the $30 million in stock options and bonuses Morris and other top
executives would get if the merger goes through. Morris alone would
be able to cash in $12.7 million in stock options after the merger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 0101 </TRAILER>
