<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teacher Donates Kidney to Student  </HEADLINE>
By RANDALL CHASE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) -- For a science teacher who learned
lessons about giving from her parents, donating one of her kidneys
to a student fits in perfectly with her role as an educator.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think teachers as a whole give so much to their students,''
Jane Smith, 42, said Monday. ''I think any teacher, when a child
walks through their door, wants to give them a better life.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a teacher at R. Max Abbott Middle School, was discharged
from UNC Hospitals on Monday afternoon, three days after surgeons
removed her left kidney and gave it to 15-year-old Michael Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and the surgeons who performed the transplant said at a
hospital news conference that they hope others will be inspired to
become organ donors.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an incredible gift,'' said David Gerber, an assistant
professor of surgery at UNC.
</P>
<P>
   Michael's mother, Deborah Evans, said Smith was an answer to
prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've had to teach Michael about faith,'' she said. ''.... Even
in his bad days, he would say, 'Mommy, I'm still praying.' ... I
think Michael has developed a very special relationship with
Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans said Michael, who endured two surgery postponements
because of infections, is happier than she has ever seen him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel that everyone has a guardian angel. Some know theirs
and some don't. I always felt that Ms. Smith was our guardian
angel.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael will remain in the hospital a few more days and must
take drugs to prevent his body from rejecting his new kidney, but
doctors said he is doing well and could return to school within six
months. He did not attend the news conference because doctors want
to limit the infection risk.
</P>
<P>
   Born with renal dysplasia, Michael began dialysis treatments
last summer after a kidney failed.
</P>
<P>
   Last August on the school playground, Smith suggested to
Michael, a homeroom student she had known just two weeks, that he
hike up his baggy pants so he could run better.
</P>
<P>
   Michael told her that he was undergoing dialysis and that he
wore the pants because they were comfortable. He also said he
needed a kidney transplant.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'I have two, do you want one?''' Smith recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was one of those moments in your life that you know it was
the right thing, and that it was going to happen,'' said Smith, who
sent Michael home with her phone number and asked him to have his
mother call her.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'OK, Michael, yeah, right,''' Evans recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But Evans said her son was insistent, telling her, ''Mom, she
eats fruits and salads every day.... She's the one. God told me.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith did turn out to be the one, thanks partly to new drugs
that make such ''stranger donations'' of organs increasingly
possible, said Mark Johnson, director of UNC's renal transplant
program and the surgeon who removed Smith's kidney. In the past,
virtually all donor organs came from patients' relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ''Matching kidneys is not so important as it was 20 or 30 years
ago,'' said Johnson, who noted that 45,000 Americans are awaiting
kidney donations but only 12,000 transplants are performed each
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only limitation is we don't have enough organs to do all
those transplants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Coalition on Donation: http://www.shareyourlife.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
