<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani paid $3.6 million for direct mail; Clinton video cost$277,000  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Giuliani Senate campaign spent about half
its fund-raising take on direct mail solicitations during the first
three months of this year, while Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign
paid more than a quarter of a million dollars for an 18-minute
biopic on the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign to elect Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to the U.S. Senate
spent about $3.6 million on direct mail between Jan. 1 and March
31, according to documents filed with the Federal Elections
Commission and released Monday. Another $300,000 was spent on
postage, fund-raising consultant fees and telemarketing. Giuliani
raised $7.3 million during the period.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign spent about $1 million on direct mail and
postage and raised $4.7 million during the period.
</P>
<P>
   But the first lady's campaign spent $277,000 for the production
of the ''Hillary'' documentary that was shown at the February event
officially launching her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   The biopic featured interviews with Clinton's mother and various
admirers, in addition to a clip of the first lady making fun of her
own lack of culinary skills by saying, ''I make a mean tossed
salad.''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary was made by Clinton supporter Linda
Bloodworth-Thomason.
</P>
<P>
   About $1 million of Giuliani's direct mail bills came from
American Target, the Virginia-based company run by Richard
Viguerie, whose appeals for money for Giuliani have painted Clinton
as an ultra-left-winger.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides have sent out their own fund-raising letter
condemning Giuliani's association with Viguerie, who is renowned
for his fund-raising on behalf of arch-conservatives like Sen.
Jesse Helms, of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Giuliani spent $1.3 million on direct mail while
Clinton spent $500,000 on it.
</P>
<P>
   Both this period and last year, Giuliani significantly outpaced
Clinton's fund-raising, with the mayor raising nearly $20 million
while the first lady raised nearly $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   The January-through-March expense forms also show that Clinton
paid $230,000 for political consulting and media work to various
firms, including the New York advertising company Devito Verdi and
a company run by Mandy Grunwald, who was a strategist for Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani listed about $60,000 in fees for various consultants
but also made $770,000 in payments for media production and media
placement, most of it apparently for the purchase of television ad
time.
</P>
<P>
   A series of television commercials for Clinton that ran late
last year was paid for by a Democratic party committee.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates paid hefty sums to pollsters in the first
quarter of this year -- Clinton listing a $56,500 payment and
Giuliani listing $34,000 in polling expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton expenses also include $57,000 paid for White House
air travel plus about $20,000 paid for various train and plane
expenses incurred by campaign staffers. Giuliani listed about
$85,000 worth of travel expenses
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has complained that Clinton should reimburse the
government for a greater share of her travel expenses. She has only
been paying for the equivalent cost of one first-class airfare on
her campaign and fund-raising swings around the state and the
country, even though the actual cost to the government is much
higher because she flies on a White House jet.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign has defended the practice, saying it is a
standard reimbursement formula used by first ladies, presidents and
vice presidents when they campaign for themselves or others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 0111 </TRAILER>
