<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Citizen Decision Raises Storm  </HEADLINE>
By GEIR MOULSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EMMEN, Switzerland (AP) -- After 43 years living in Switzerland,
Janos Deak says he has ''long been Swiss in my heart.'' But that
wasn't good enough for his neighbors -- voters in this industrial
Lucerne suburb rejected his application to become a citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel humiliated,'' Deak, a retired Hungarian construction
worker, said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland has traditionally been stingy in granting
citizenship to foreign residents, but the experiment of a large
town putting the decision into the hands of voters has touched off
national soul-searching even among the referendum-happy Swiss.
</P>
<P>
   Many villages in Switzerland's German-speaking heartland have
long held referendums on citizenship applications. But Emmen, with
a population of 27,000, applied the system on a much larger scale.
</P>
<P>
   The burghers of Emmen rejected 86 percent of the applicants in
their March 12 referendum, even though town officials had cited all
of them as good, law-abiding members of the community.
</P>
<P>
   That raised alarm in government circles, stirred debate in the
national media and prompted the Council of Europe to warn that the
system leaves ''room for discriminatory practice.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This vote is symptomatic -- and I think not just for Emmen but
for many, many places in Switzerland where covert racism exists,''
says Arlette Fischer, the left-wing Social Democrats'
representative in Emmen.
</P>
<P>
   Eight Italians received the red-and-white Swiss passport. The 48
losers were from eastern Europe and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   People from the former Yugoslavia, many of whom arrived in the
1980s or earlier and have Swiss-born children, fared badly. Some
right-wing politicians openly suggest Balkan immigrants have
tendencies to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a bad climate here,'' says Stevica Vukojevic, a
37-year-old Serbian employee at the local steelworks, who along
with his Croatian wife and their two Swiss-born children received
support from only 35 percent of voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've given everything I can to become Swiss,'' he adds. ''I've
concentrated my whole life on it, and I've worked in Emmen for 16
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The would-be citizens voted on March 12 were exposed to detailed
scrutiny through a 98-page booklet the town government mailed to
all Emmen households. A page devoted to each family included
photographs and personal details, including income, activities and
work history.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like being treated as a criminal,'' says Deak, 63, who
was backed by 45 percent of voters. ''The only difference is
there's no number on your chest.''
</P>
<P>
   In the uproar following the vote, town officials abandoned the
next citizenship referendum and put 250 applications on hold until
the end of the year to ''somehow improve the whole procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We urgently need to calm things down,'' says Peter
Schnellmann, president of the local council.
</P>
<P>
   But the underlying problems remain -- in particular a belief that
Switzerland, which long welcomed workers from less wealthy parts of
Europe, can no longer afford to extend that welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every fourth person is already a foreigner'' in Emmen, says
Kurt Portmann, who heads the newly revived local section of the
right-wing Swiss People's Party. ''You have to recognize that we
just have too many. Far too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Portmann's party made large gains in national elections last
year after campaigning with the slogan ''Stop Asylum Abuse'' --
reflecting the success of the anti-immigrant Freedom Party in
neighboring Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Disgusted by the Emmen vote, lawmakers in Geneva and other
western French-speaking towns said they would grant citizenship to
those who were rejected -- an offer generally seen as unrealistic
but which reflects new doubt over a cherished tenet of Swiss direct
democracy: The people are always right.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a local court ordered a review of a 1997 decision by
voters in the northwestern town of Pratteln to throw out
citizenship bids by five Turks, which it ruled an ''arbitrary
demonstration of power.''
</P>
<P>
   The process of obtaining a passport varies enormously across
this country of four languages and 7 million people, but typically
the decision is made by a local panel.
</P>
<P>
   Applicants must have lived in Switzerland for 12 years. Beyond
that, individual towns place their own hurdles -- ranging from
''good character'' through respectable family life to ''readiness
to serve society.''
</P>
<P>
   Costs vary from negligible to thousands of dollars, depending on
whether the community charges a percentage of income.
</P>
<P>
   Deak and Vukojevic, both of whom submitted their current bids
three years ago, are reluctant to start again.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's difficult to see right now,'' Vukojevic says. ''I'm so
disappointed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-18-00 0114 </TRAILER>
