<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Ndereba Wins Close Race  </HEADLINE>
By BERT ROSENTHAL, AP Track Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Catherine Ndereba became a marathon runner because
she had admired the accomplishments of her Kenyan compatriot Tegla
Loroupe, the world record-holder.
</P>
<P>
   Ndereba has not yet matched Loroupe's feats, but she has done
something that Loroupe never has: win the Boston Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Ndereba, who trains with a group of Kenyans in
Norristown, Pa., probably earned a berth on the Kenyan women's
Olympic marathon team, alongside Loroupe and Joyce Chepchemba, the
1-3 finishers at Sunday's London Marathon, with her first marathon
victory.
</P>
<P>
   In winning, Ndereba foiled Fatuma Roba's bid to become the first
male or female to win four consecutive titles at Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on adding Ndereba to the team will not be made
until next week, but she is confident.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they will take me,'' she said Monday, after winning at
Boston in 2 hours, 26 minutes, 11 seconds -- 16 seconds ahead of
Irina Bogacheva of Kyrgyzstan and Roba, who had the same time
(2:26:27). ''I ran on a hard course and I won the race.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory over the 1996 Olympic gold medalist, Roba, was
another plus for Ndereba, who before making her marathon debut at
Boston last year was known as ''Catherine The Great,'' for her
achievements in shorter road races.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 1998 and 1999, Ndereba was chosen the women's road
racer of the year and ranked the No. 1 road racer in the world.
Last year, she had the fastest times in the world for 5 kilometers,
12K, 15K and 10 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Her marathon debut was not spectacular, but she showed great
promise, finishing a respectable sixth in 2:28:27. She improved
rapidly, placing second in the New York City Marathon in November
in 2:27:34.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tegla is very famous in our country,'' Ndereba said. ''I just
wanted to see if I could be like her. Even if I am not exactly like
her now, I am in the process of being like her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ndereba admitted she did not think she would win Monday,
especially against an experienced runner like Roba and not after
feeling severe pain in her left ankle. Still, she had hoped to run
2:24.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not easy to beat a thrice champion,'' she said. ''To win
for three years is not a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Ndereba said she began feeling the pain when she was warming up
for the race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought maybe it was tension,'' she said. ''It was hurting a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ndereba said she was in agony throughout the race and in the
worst pain at about the 19-mile mark, where she was going downhill.
She wouldn't stop, though.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a saying in training that if you have pain, you can't
have fear,'' Ndereba said. ''I said, 'I just want to finish the
race.' It's too hard when you run all those miles and you don't see
the finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Ndereba caught the frontrunning Roba near the 21.7-mile point
and exchanged the lead with her several times over the next 3{
miles. Then, Ndereba used the speed sharpened from running the
shorter distances to burst ahead. Roba couldn't match her move.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was not worried, because I always have confidence in my
kick,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As she crossed the finish line, Ndereba was hurting and
emotional.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I finished, I could not walk without pain,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the Kenyan national anthem was played, she broke into
tears.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was surprisied to win in Boston,'' Ndereba said. ''I was
very happy and I was overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a feeling Loroupe often has experienced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
