<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tewell Notches First Senior Tour Win  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LONG, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. (AP) -- Doug Tewell doesn't care that
his first senior tour win -- and his first major -- came at the
rain-shortened PGA Seniors' Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The on-again, off-again event that had seven weather delays and
more than nine inches of rain in four days was the first Seniors'
Championship to be shortened since the tournament expanded to 72
holes in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   ''A win's a win,'' Tewell said.
</P>
<P>
   Tewell, playing in his first Seniors' Championship, shot a
5-under-par 67 Monday and finished seven strokes ahead of four
others. He became the 12th golfer to win his first senior event at
a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-year-old Tewell finished at 15-under 201, making six
birdies and a bogey during the final round. It was his first win
since the 1987 Pensacola Open.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd have to rank this as the biggest victory of my career,''
said Tewell, whose win earned him $324,000. ''It just means a great
deal to win. It just feels good to get in that winner's circle and
know you can complete an event.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana Quigley, who started the day one stroke behind Tewell, shot
1 over and finished in a four-way tie for second at 8 under with
Hale Irwin, Tom Kite and Larry Nelson. Vicente Fernandez and Hubert
Green were 7 under.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even beyond my 'A' game, I don't know if I would have caught
him today,'' Quigley said.
</P>
<P>
   Tewell hit 13 of 14 fairways and 14 of 18 greens in regulation.
He became the seventh wire-to-wire winner at this event since 1958
and first since Jack Nicklaus in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   A former club pro at Pinetop Country Club in Arizona who spent
three years as a television commentator for The Golf Channel,
Tewell made his debut on the senior tour last fall. He missed the
first five tournaments with a back injury he sustained the day
after his 50th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   He initially feared he had ruptured a disc in his back, but it
turned out to be an acute sciatica attack. The injury came two days
before he was scheduled to leave for his first senior tournament
event, in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Recovering from the injury, Tewell's best finish last year was a
tie for 15th.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wasn't physically prepared. It just hurt to play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he was forced to play, trying for a high position on the
money list and exempt status.
</P>
<P>
   A four-time winner on the PGA Tour, he has much higher
expectations for 2000, especially after his first win.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to be kind of anxious now to see what this amount of
confidence does for me,'' Tewell said. ''I want to see if this will
get me to that level where I feel like I should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believe it will.
</P>
<P>
   ''He plays very well from tee to green,'' Kite said. ''His
bugaboo has been an inconsistent putter. Depending on how well he
can get his putting, he can win a bunch of them.''
</P>
<P>
Divots: Irwin, who won three consecutive Seniors' Championships
(1996-98), finished the tournament despite initially saying he
would not have been able to compete on Monday because of a
commitment to a charity event. ... After a quadruple bogey at the
par-4 No. 11 on Sunday, Quigley carded a 4 at the course's toughest
hole Monday. ... Nicklaus said he will not play another senior
event until the U.S. Senior Open. ... Leonard Thompson, even par as
he approached the par-3 No. 15, hit four shots into the water en
route to an 11, the first double-digit score of the tournament. His
fifth shot stopped on the fringe and he two-putted from there.
Thompson started the day at 4 under, but shot a 13-over 85 in the
final round. Said Kite, one of his playing partners: ''It was
painful to watch.'' ... The tournament, one of four majors on the
tour, was sponsored by Advil.
</P>
</TEXT>
