<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lewis' Lawyers Want Separate Trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- A joint trial for NFL linebacker Ray Lewis and
his co-defendants on murder charges will hinder a ''fair
determination of each defendant's guilt or innocence,'' according
to Lewis' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers filed motions in court Monday arguing that the
Baltimore Ravens' All-Pro should have a separate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is charged along with Reginald Oakley of Baltimore and
Joseph Sweeting of Miami in the Jan. 31 stabbing deaths that
occurred during a post-Super Bowl party in the Buckhead
entertainment district.
</P>
<P>
   Two men from Decatur, Ga., Jacinth Baker, 21, and Richard
Lollar, 24, were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' attorneys also asked that Fulton County prosecutors turn
over any additional witness statements that say the football player
did not have a knife during the melee and did not participate in
the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting's lawyers also filed motions Monday, asking that
prosecutors turn over information of any prior felony convictions
of the state's witnesses and of any internal affairs investigations
of the police officers involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta lawyer Bruce Harvey, who represents Oakley, filed
motions asking Superior Court Judge Alice Bonner to grant immunity
to Kwame King and Carlos Stafford, two occupants of Lewis' rented
stretch limousine who have not been charged in the case. They would
give testimony that clears Oakley of wrongdoing, the motion said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey also asked Bonner to grant Oakley a separate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Severance motions are rarely allowed, but if a severance is
granted, at least one other judge may have to preside over the
other trial. This would be necessary because the defendants have
filed speedy trial demands, which require the case to be tried by
the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is scheduled for May 15, and the motions are to be
argued during hearings scheduled May 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis lawyers also made other requests:
</P>
<P>
   --They want the linebacker's initial statements given to police
on Jan. 31 suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   --They want prior assault charges against Lewis filed by three
separate women not be used against him at trial. The charges were
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   --They want prosecutors to turn over witness statements that may
help explain why Marlin Burros, a friend of the victims who fired
on Lewis' limousine as it sped away, has disposed of his gun.
</P>
<P>
   --They are asking the judge to issue a subpoena demanding Chris
Shinholster of Akron, Ohio, a friend of the victims who was at the
scene, testify at trial. Shinholster told police Lewis did not have
a knife and was not fighting.
</P>
<P>
   --And they want the judge to issue a subpoena requiring Keiva
Walls of Houston, who was an occupant in Lewis' limo, to testify at
trial. Walls has given statements to police saying Lewis yelled for
everyone to get back in the limo and never held a knife that night,
the motion said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
