<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Volleyball Defeats Korean Team  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) -- The United States defeated the
Korean national team 25-22, 23-25, 25-22, 25-20 at the World Arena
on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the hitting of 6-foot-8 George Roumain and 6-5 John Hyden
off sets from USA co-captain Lloy Ball, the Americans overpowered
the smaller Koreans at the net.
</P>
<P>
   After the Koreans won the second game, the U.S. team, which
qualified for the Sydney Olympics by winning the NORCECA
Championships in September, dominated the final two games of the
match.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a nice mix of veterans and kids,'' coach Doug Beal
said. ''I don't think there is any reason we can't be a very strong
medal contender at Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   Beal would know what it takes to succeed at the Olympics -- he
led the Americans' march to the gold medal at the 1984 Los Angeles
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, this what we need most,'' said Ball, who is one of
the six returners from the 1996 Olympic team that finished ninth at
Atlanta. ''We spent four months in the gym, and we're trying to get
our game sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   The match was the third in a four-match tour against the Korean
team that qualified for the 2000 Olympics by winning the Asian Zone
Championships. The U.S. team has a 3-1 advantage with the final
match of the tour scheduled for Wednesday night at Fort Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is an awfully good chance we will see them again in
Sydney,'' Beal said. ''They are a very good team that will also
challenge for a medal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
