<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax procrastinators mob post offices  </HEADLINE>
By MELANIE CARROLL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- As the midnight tax deadline drew closer Monday,
procrastinators crowded into post offices across the country to
file their returns -- or plead for extensions.
</P>
<P>
   Because April 15 fell on a Saturday this year, most Americans
got two extra days to file their taxes. People in Massachusetts,
Connecticut, Maine, New Hampshire, Rhode Island, Vermont and most
of New York outside the New York City area have until midnight
today because of the Patriot's Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City on Monday night, the 1.4 million-square-foot
James A. Farley Post Office in midtown Manhattan was packed with
taxpayers trying to get their tax forms postmarked before the
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Qudsiya Assan, 26, of Brooklyn, couldn't finish her forms on
time, and writing a letter to the Internal Revenue Service for an
extension made her head throb.
</P>
<P>
   ''I caught a headache coming in here today,'' Assan said at the
main post office. ''I pay enough taxes already.''
</P>
<P>
   In north Dallas, some taxpayers faced an unexpected delay in
getting their forms to Uncle Sam: One post office had its doors and
mail slots open but had already made its last pickup.
</P>
<P>
   A postal worker headed for home told the group of about 20
late-filers that the nearest post office still picking up mail was
near downtown Dallas, about 20 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lytle, a 29-year-old software salesman, was headed to the
downtown post office to mail his tax return when he was asked by
two strangers to drop their returns off as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't mind because I have to go down there anyways,'' Lytle
said. ''I just wish I would have gotten here earlier in the day.''
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore, postal worker Jae Kim stood in a steady rain,
greeting last-minute filers as they pulled up to the city's main
post office just before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not as many people as I expected,'' he said, greeting the
occasional patron through the slit of a car window. ''Maybe it's
the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   An unofficial count said about 1,200 people showed up to file
just before the midnight deadline. A local Krispy Kreme doughnut
shop handed out free doughnuts, going through 100 dozen from 10
p.m. to midnight.
</P>
<P>
   A few taxpayers missed the deadline and the doughnuts but went
inside anyway because the main post office is open 24 hours a day
all year long.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Barnett, 24, who spent all day filling out 15 pages of tax
forms, wrote a check to the IRS and stuffed it into an envelope
around 12:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ''I downloaded what I thought were all the forms a couple of
days ago, but I guess I didn't have them all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Terminal Annex post office in downtown Los Angeles, there
were swarms of people filing at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Lines of cars a block long snaked steadily past postal workers
in open-air booths set up to collect tax returns in the parking
lot.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just wanted to see the lovely postal workers,'' was Maureen
Tabor's excuse for waiting until the last minute Monday night.
''And I guess I like procrastinating.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles woman will procrastinate a bit longer, having
filed an extension form, not her return.
</P>
<P>
   In Wisconsin, so many people chose electronic filing that the
usual last-minute rush seemed calmer, one tax preparer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're less swamped than usual,'' said Dan Griffiths, district
manager for H&AMP;R Block's 11 offices in south central Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   But in Chicago, pen and paper ruled supreme.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second year in a row that Isaiah Heard, 28, found
himself trying to beat the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't mind waiting to the last day. It's almost like
tradition now,'' he said at the downtown post office, which was
open until midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Heard said he had planned to file electronically before he was
informed of the additional charges. So he spent Monday morning
completing the forms.
</P>
<P>
   Eric O'Quinn, another last-minute Chicago filer, said he waited
on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew I owed money,'' he explained. ''I figured it didn't
make sense to send it in earlier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 0241 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000418.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 murders of livery drivers have industry concerned  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Livery cab driver Juan Marical slows down to
check out a would-be passenger hailing him in Brooklyn. He knows
he's only supposed to pick up fares called in from his dispatcher,
but like scores of other drivers, he trolls for street fares to
make more money.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent spate of livery cab driver murders has Marical and
many others among the city's more than 41,000 livery drivers
scared. This year, seven livery cab drivers have been murdered --
two in the past week. Last year, 11 were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you look suspicious, forget it,'' Marical said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The police have made solving the murders a top priority, but
there's been an arrest in only one case. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has
expressed his outrage and has pledged $5 million in a grant program
to help equip livery cars with bulletproof partitions or digital
security cameras.
</P>
<P>
   At a City Council hearing Monday to address the safety concerns
of livery drivers, police Chief of Patrol John Scanlon said six of
the seven murders resulted from street hails, and he urged drivers
to avoid such passengers. Only yellow cab drivers can pick up
street fares, and although by law they must take passengers in all
five boroughs, they stick to the relatively safe streets of
Manhattan, making the need for livery drivers all the more pressing
in the outer boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of the conditions of the job itself -- cash-oriented,
solo-operated, evening hours -- (livery) drivers are especially
vulnerable to criminals who would prey on them,'' Scanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Maria Estrella agreed. Her husband, Luis Francisco Perez,
was the sixth cab driver killed this year. He was found in his cab
last Friday with a gunshot wound to his head, two days shy of his
30th birthday. On Saturday, the seventh driver, Jean Scutt, was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'It's dangerous for you,''' Estrella said as she held
her 16-month-old son, Liully. '''I'm waiting every night for you.'
But he would never think that anything would happen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani announced Monday that the city will set up a fund to
help the families of the slain drivers. In addition, the police
department has created a special task force, assigning 300 officers
to protect livery drivers. Some cops will act as decoy drivers, and
there will be designated safe zones where drivers in trouble can go
if they need help.
</P>
<P>
   But Scanlon stressed the best protection for the drivers is the
bulletproof partition. Taxi and Limousine Commission rules require
all yellow cabs and livery cars operated and owned by more than one
driver to have the partitions.
</P>
<P>
   Police stress that no yellow cab drivers have been killed since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   But cars owned and operated by individual drivers -- which make
up 90 percent of all livery cars -- can have either the partitions
or tiny surveillance cameras installed behind the driver's rearview
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   However, many livery drivers say it's too expensive to equip
their cars with partitions, which cost between $250 to $300, or the
cameras, costing from $600 to $800.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the security devices, the job is still pretty
dangerous, said Jose Vinoria, a driver for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been attacked three times -- once, someone put a gun to
the back of my head,'' Vinoria said.
</P>
<P>
   So why do people become livery drivers?
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not because it's a very good job,'' Vinoria said. ''You
have a time when you have to pay your bills. And in this job, you
can be your own boss. You can work as much overtime as you need.''
</P>
<P>
   The dangers of cab driving are not new. Scanlon said the police
department has been battling violence against cab drivers for
years. Fernando Mateo, president of the New York State Federation
of Taxi Drivers, said at least a dozen cab drivers are attacked
each day.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the most dangerous industry in the city,'' Mateo said.
</P>
<P>
   Driving a cab was listed as one of the most dangerous jobs
nationwide in a 1996 survey by the National Institute for
Occupational Safety &AMP; Health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 0247 </TRAILER>
