<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rhode Island man arrested in Internet sting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCKY HILL, Conn. (AP) -- Authorities conducting an Internet
sting have arrested a child welfare worker from Rhode Island
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Kogut, 31, of Central Falls, is accused of seeking
sexual contact with ''a 13-year-old Rocky Hill girl,'' who actually
was a town police detective.
</P>
<P>
   Kogut is the assistant director of the Professional Parent
Program in Rhode Island. He job involves assessing foster care
applicants to determine if they would make suitable parents,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Kogut was arrested on Friday outside an apartment complex where
he had arraigned to meet the ''girl,'' police said.
</P>
<P>
   Kogut was arraigned Monday in New Britain Superior Court on
charges of criminal attempt to commit sexual assault and injury or
risk of injury to a minor and three counts of criminal attempt to
use a computer to entice a minor to engage in sexual activity.
</P>
<P>
   Kogut had supervised male adolescents at a Rhode Island group
home before being promoted to assistant director of the
Professional Parent Program. The program, contracted by the state
of Rhode Island to run specialized foster care services, placed
Kogut on paid administrative leave, pending the outcome of the
investigation, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island's Child Protective Services also is investigating
whether any allegations have been made against Kogut in the
programs he was involved with, state agency officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Kogut was released on $150,000 bail and was ordered to have no
contact with anyone younger than 16. He is due back in court May 8.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Det. Henry Dodenhoff, who posed online as the
13-year-old, said he was contacted in a chat room by Kogut, who
said he was 21, from Rhode Island and interested in sex.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation continued over several days, with Kogut, who
went by the screen name RavnosFirst, always bringing up sex, police
said. He told the ''girl'' he would be gentle and not hurt her,
according to the arrest warrant.
</P>
<P>
   'I'll teach you everything you want to know and I'll be gentle.
... Just tell me you're 18 and we'll be all set,'' the warrant
quotes him as writing.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Kogut mentioned several times that he would be in
''big trouble'' if anyone found out that he and the 13-year-old
were planning to meet to have sex. At one point, Kogut asked the
''girl'' if she could pretend to be sick and stay home from school
one day. If she could, he would do the same and drive to Rocky Hill
to meet her, the warrant says.
</P>
<P>
   Kogut was arrested about 7:30 p.m. Friday outside Stepney Place,
an apartment complex where he was to meet with the ''girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers recognized Kogut from pictures he had e-mailed. They
also knew his green Chevrolet Blazer because he had described it in
detail. He had asked online for directions and followed them to
where police were waiting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
