<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 94; Dow Up 64  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened higher today, extending Monday's
sharp rally as investors once again flocked to blue-chip issues and
sought bargains in the battered technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 64.61 at 10,647.12.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 94.83 at 3,633.99, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 12.04 at 1,413.48.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks extended a rally that picked up steam in the final hour
of trading on Monday, leaving the Dow with a gain of 276.74 points
and the Nasdaq with a 217.87-point advance, its biggest single-day
point gain ever.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was a dramatic turnaround from crushing losses last
week. Still, most analysts are saying it's too soon to declare a
full recovery from the carnage last week, when the U.S. stock
market lost nearly $2 trillion in value.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not out of the woods entirely,'' said Russell Jones,
chief Asia economist for the investment bank Lehman Brothers in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings reports provided a catalyst for buying today. Dow
component Johnson &AMP; Johnson rose 2{ to 80\ after reporting
first-quarter profits that beat analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the government delivered a report that eased some
revived fears about inflation. The Commerce Department said hat
housing construction plummeted 11.2 percent in March, the biggest
plunge in six years, suggesting that rising mortgage rates are
cutting into demand.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to slow the economy to a sustainable pace, the
Federal Reserve has raised interest rates five times since last
June. The slowdown in housing starts offered some hope that the
rate increases are working, reducing the odds of steep increases
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The market's breadth improved, with more stocks joining in the
effort to rally. Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 128.49
million shares, compared with 152.50 million at the same time
Monday. On the Nasdaq, advancers led by a 2-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 6.65 to 465.91.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.2 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.4 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.5 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
