<HEADLINE> PAX To Rebroadcast NBC News Program  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC plans to rebroadcast its early evening news
program on the PAX network owned by Paxson Communications, the
family-friendly broadcaster in which NBC recently bought a 32
percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   The monthlong rebroadcast test in May of ''NBC Nightly News with
Tom Brokaw'' is likely to further strain relations between NBC and
its affiliated stations by providing a competing outlet for a
popular network show.
</P>
<P>
   The PAX network is carried on smaller stations and cable systems
throughout the country, reaching 77 percent of U.S. households,
often in areas already reached by major TV stations affiliated with
NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The PAX network will broadcast Brokaw's news program at 7:30
p.m. nationwide, one hour after airing on network-affiliated
stations. After the one-month test, the rebroadcast is expected to
become a regular part of Pax TV's schedule in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal announced today, PAX will also rebroadcast
some NBC coverage of U.S. Olympic trials beginning in June.
</P>
<P>
   The carriage of NBC programming on PAX was part of an
understanding reached last September when NBC, a unit of General
Electric Co., agreed to acquire a 32 percent stake in the company
for $415 million.
</P>
<P>
   For PAX, which is based in West Palm Beach, Fla., the deal was a
way to bolster its roster of programming, which depends heavily on
wholesome programs like ''Chicken Soup for the Soul.'' PAX already
rebroadcasts NBC's game show ''Twenty One'' on Saturday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Like CBS and ABC, NBC's rapport with its affiliates has been on
the decline as the networks seek to revise decades-old agreements
requiring them to pay station owners to carry their programming.
Fox doesn't pay its affiliates to carry its programming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
