<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More deals reached, but lawmakers struggle to conclude budget  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State legislators have agreed to increase
spending on New York public schools by a record $1.2 billion to
about $13.2 billion, the highest in state history.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement came as the legislative conference
committee on education became the last of the nine committees
negotiating policy areas of the 2000-01 budget to end its
deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, details of a $1.2 billion tax-cut plan over five
years were being released Monday night, but legislative leaders and
Gov. George Pataki could not reach a final deal on the budget.
</P>
<P>
   State Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver and Senate Majority Leader
Joseph Bruno both said this morning that the absence of a final
agreement would prevent the Legislature from adopting a budget by
sundown Wednesday. They had set that time, the start of Jewish
Passover holiday, as a deadline for putting a new budget in place.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders said they would sent their members home starting
Wednesday for the previously scheduled Easter-Passover holiday and
pick up the budget process on Monday, May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Silver confirmed reports by sources Monday night close to the
budget talks that Pataki's Budget Division had raised objections to
the longer-term implications of some spending programs favored by
the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ''The numbers that came out were different from different
perspectives,'' Silver said this morning on WROW-AM in Albany.
''Right now, the Budget Division doesn't seem to agree with
legislative (fiscal committee) secretaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said talks among the leaders would continue this week and
staffers would work on the budget while lawmakers were on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators have been trying to reach an agreement on the state
fiscal year which begun April 1. This is the 16th straight year
budget adoption has been late in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Still awaiting final agreement was the release of details of
specific projects to be funded in a new, ambitious five-year
program for transportation and mass transit.
</P>
<P>
   The tax-cut plan included the immediate elimination of the
gross-receipts tax on energy for manufacturers to apply
retroactively to Jan. 1. The new budget will also include a
reduction in gross receipts tax for non-manufacturing commercial
customers over five years and for a reduction in the tax charged to
residential taxpayers of $75 million immediately and $50 million
over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kuhl Jr. and Assemblyman Steven Sanders, co-chairmen
of the committee on education, said the school aid spending would
be at a record level for the fourth straight year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, funding for the pet program of the state
Assembly called ''LADDER'' was increased by $259 million. Included
in this plan is $225 million for universal pre-kindergarten
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Allocations for districts that are unable to spend the money
next school year will be kept for the district until they can be
used. That settles a dispute between the Legislature and Pataki,
who has proposed returning unspent funds to the state each year.
</P>
<P>
   Funding for LADDER programs will also include increases of $67
million for class-size reduction and $50 million for minor
maintenance and repair.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also agreed to:
</P>
<P>
   --Increase by $370 million on unrestricted operating aid for
public school districts. Included in that would be a new, $35
million spending plan for summer school aid.
</P>
<P>
   --Spend $30 million on fighting school violence.
</P>
<P>
   --Increase school-building aid by $228 million.
</P>
<P>
   --Provide $67.5 million for Teacher Support Aid.
</P>
<P>
   --Increase state support for instructional materials by $33.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   --Increase by $3 million spending for the Limited English
Proficiency program.
</P>
<P>
   --Provide $11 million for bilingual education aid.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said the committee did not take into consideration
capital improvement issues such as school construction projects. He
said those issues would be decided by the Legislature's top
leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
