<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seventh-grade girls accused of plotting to torch school  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BERGENFIELD, N.J. (AP) -- Two seventh-grade girls hauling
flammable liquids in their shoulder bags told police they planned
to burn down their school, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were pretty forthcoming about what was going on: They
said they didn't like school,'' Deputy Police Chief Ed Carroll told
The Record of Hackensack in today's editions. ''That was their
motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls were arrested Saturday after a gift shop manager
accused the girls, age 12 and 13, of stealing calculators, police
said. They were carrying a 32-ounce bottle of charcoal lighter
fluid, a 5-ounce bottle of butane lighter fluid, a 16-ounce bottle
of rubbing alcohol, as well as a can of household disinfectant, a
hammer, matches and a cigarette lighter, Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Police also found a handwritten list of the items found in the
shoulder bag, Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Police called the girls' parents to police headquarters and
began questioning the students, who had served detention earlier at
Roy W. Brown Middle School before they went to the store.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the girls said they planned to set the blaze
Saturday night in the nurse's office or the gymnasium, both of
which are hidden from street view. The girls had brought the hammer
just in case they had to break a window, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The girls were charged as juveniles with conspiracy to commit
arson, possession of a weapon for unlawful purpose and shoplifting,
authorities said. Besides the calculators, police said they also
found stolen arts and crafts supplies, watches and sunglasses in
the bag.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said the girls were not in school Monday and
did not say whether the girls would be disciplined. Officials
wouldn't say whether other parents or students had been told of the
incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
