<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 91; Nasdaq Up 99  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today, extending
Monday's sharp rally as investors once again flocked to blue-chip
issues and sought bargains in the battered technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 91.83 at 10,674.34.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 99.67 at 3,638.83, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 12.13 at 1,413.57.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks extended a rally that picked up steam in the final hour
of trading on Monday, leaving the Dow with a gain of 276.74 points
and the Nasdaq with a 217.87-point advance, its biggest single-day
point gain ever.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was a dramatic turnaround from crushing losses last
week. Still, most analysts are saying it's too soon to declare a
full recovery from the carnage last week, when the U.S. stock
market lost nearly $2 trillion in value.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not out of the woods entirely,'' said Russell Jones,
chief Asia economist for the investment bank Lehman Brothers in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings reports provided a catalyst for buying today. Dow
component Johnson &AMP; Johnson rose 3 1/16 to 80 13/16 after reporting
first-quarter profits that beat analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Intel rose 5 1/16 to 128 1/16. The company, the world's largest
maker of computer chips, was expected to report its first-quarter
earnings after the 4 p.m. close of trading. Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter raised its rating on Intel stock to ''strong buy'' from
''outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, investors were favoring large-capitalization,
well-known technology names. Sun Microsystems rose 4 1/16 to 88
15/16 and Microsoft rose 2 7/16 to 78 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the government delivered a report that eased some
fears about inflation. The Commerce Department said housing
construction plummeted 11.2 percent in March, the biggest plunge in
six years, suggesting that rising mortgage rates are cutting into
demand.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to slow the economy to a sustainable pace, the
Federal Reserve has raised interest rates five times since last
June. The slowdown in housing starts offered some hope that the
rate increases are working, reducing the odds of steep increases
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are highly sensitive to interest rates
and inflation, benefited from the report. American Express rose 4|
to 138|.
</P>
<P>
   The market's breadth improved, with more stocks joining in the
effort to rally. Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-6
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 313.11
million shares, compared with 364.68 million at the same time
Monday. On the Nasdaq, advancers led by a 2-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 9.38 to 468.64.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
