<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDA OKs New Antibiotic Type  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD, AP Medical Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government approved a vital new weapon in
the battle against drug-resistant bacteria today, a drug called
Zyvox described as the first entirely new type of antibiotic in 35
years.
</P>
<P>
   Zyvox can treat routine pneumonia and skin infections and some
drug-resistant staph infections. But its chief fight will be
against an infamous germ, called ''Enterococcus faecium,'' often
deadly to hospitalized patients and impervious to the antibiotic of
last resort.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, more and more germs are developing resistance to that
longtime ''silver bullet'' antibiotic vancomycin, leaving doctors
watching helplessly as their patients die from once-treatable
infections.
</P>
<P>
   Zyvox, doctors hope, will help. In clinical trials of 145
patients with vancomycin-resistant Enterococcus infections, Zyvox
cured 67 percent, the Food and Drug Administration said today in
approving Pharmacia Corp.'s Zyvox.
</P>
<P>
   Zyvox isn't alone in this battle -- the FDA last fall approved
competitor Aventis' Synercid as the nation's first alternative when
vancomycin fails. Experts say both new drugs are important weapons
that should be used sparingly, against the worst infections,
because bacteria eventually will evolve to evade them, too.
</P>
<P>
   Synercid is a combination of two older but little-used types of
antibiotics that deals bacteria a one-two punch.
</P>
<P>
   Zyvox, in contrast, is a chemical designed from scratch to fight
germs at an entirely different point in their life cycle than other
medicines do -- a true surprise attack. Known chemically as
linezolid, it is the first in a long-awaited new class of
antibiotics called oxazolidinones.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a magic bullet. It can't fight all bacteria, only those
known as ''gram-positive'' germs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, gram-positive bacteria cause more than half of all
serious infections treated in hospitals worldwide, the kind often
caught by patients while they're in the hospital for some other
problem. That notorious Enterococcus faecium, for instance,
commonly invades surgery wounds, as well as causing deadly
infections in the abdomen, urinary tract and heart valves.
</P>
<P>
   In clinical trials of Zyvox against other infections, including
tough-to-treat staph infections, Zyvox proved as effective as
vancomycin.
</P>
<P>
   Primary side effects were nausea and headache in about 5 percent
of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacia said Zyvox would be available within a few weeks, but
refused to disclose the price except to say it was expected to be a
little lower than competitor Synercid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-18-00 1218 </TRAILER>
