<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Trial Courthouse Opened  </HEADLINE>
By PETER DEJONG, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands (AP) -- Builders added finishing touches
to the roof of an old schoolhouse Tuesday, finishing its
transformation into a Scottish court where the Lockerbie trial is
expected to begin May 3.
</P>
<P>
   A royal crest, the symbol for Scottish justice, hung above the
leather chairs and oak-paneled table where judges will hear the
case against two Libyans accused in the 1988 bombing of Pan Am
flight 103.
</P>
<P>
   Television crews and photographers were allowed a glimpse inside
the high-security premises in Camp Zeist, a former U.S. air base 25
miles southeast of Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is set to begin more than 10 years after Pan Am
aircraft was blown apart over Lockerbie, Scotland, on Dec. 21,
1988, killing 270 people -- including 189 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants, former Libyan secret servicemen Abdel Basset Ali
al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, pleaded innocent to murder
after being brought to the Netherlands a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Security vehicles patrolled the area as police posed for
photographs near a 20-foot concrete wall --topped with an electric
fence -- surrounding the bunker-like detention facility.
</P>
<P>
   The court chamber, a renovated schoolhouse, is lined with blue
carpet and about 150 chairs, and fitted with a bulletproof glass
wall which will separate the defendants from the public gallery.
The accused and their attorneys will be seated in the same area as
the judges and the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to hold the trial in the Netherlands was taken
after a compromise was reached with Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi,
whose country had been hit by economic sanctions for nearly a
decade until the suspects were handed over to Dutch justice
officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
