<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Military Kills 16 Rebels  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- The army raided Tamil Tiger hide-outs
in the north and gunned down 16 guerrillas, military officials said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The seven attacks Monday in the Jaffna peninsula were aimed at
driving the rebels back into the jungles, said Defense Ministry
spokesman Major Asiri Idunil.
</P>
<P>
   He did not say if the military suffered any casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas stepped up their attacks in November to take back
their former stronghold, which fell to the military four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fierce fighting has raged since March near the Elephant Pass, a
strategic causeway linking Jaffna with the rest of the mainland to
the south. The rebels have seized small pockets near the pass. The
attacks coincided with the military saying it has consolidated
positions near the area.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers want to carve out Eelam as a homeland for the
nation's 3.2 million Tamils, who are a minority. The rebels say the
Tamils are discriminated against in jobs and education by the
Sinhalese majority. The battle has left more than 62,000 people
dead so far.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, troops have been able to consolidate their positions
after soldiers diverted from other areas reached the pass in recent
days, a senior army official said. The area is 175 miles north of
the capital, Colombo.
</P>
</TEXT>
