<HEADLINE> Tokyo Police Will Probe Music Mogul  </HEADLINE>
By YURI KAGEYAMA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Police will investigate sexual misconduct
allegations against the president of Japan's top talent agency, a
lawmaker said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a parliamentary committee meeting last week, ruling party
legislator Yoshihide Sakaue demanded an inquiry into reported
allegations that talent agent Johnny Kitagawa had sex with several
of the teen-age boys at his talent agency.
</P>
<P>
   Although long rumored, the allegations about Kitagawa -- a
68-year-old music mogul behind dozens of top young male TV stars
over the last 30 years -- had never before surfaced in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Kitagawa and his agency, known as ''Johnny's Jimusho'' --
''Johnny's Office'' -- have repeatedly denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, the Shukan Bunshun, one of Japan's most popular
weekly magazines, ran a series of articles alleging the agent had
sex with some of the boys, sometimes threatening to hamper their
careers unless they agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Kitagawa is suing the magazine for libel.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the boys nor their families have said anything publicly
about the reported allegations. None of the boys cited in the
articles, nor their parents, have filed complaints with police or
the courts. The families also declined requests for interviews,
which were made through the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Sakaue said he will propose this week to devote the next few
committee meetings to the allegations, including summoning Johnny's
officials to Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ''These children idolize these stars, but their dreams are being
broken unless they give in to the president's desires,'' Sakaue
said in an interview at his parliamentary office.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has only recently begun to recognize child abuse as a
serious problem. Teachers, doctors and neighbors have often turned
the other way despite obvious evidence of child abuse. Up to now,
police have remained passive about such complaints, Sakaue said.
</P>
<P>
   Although still relatively rare, courts are convicting more
people on charges of having sex with children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
