<HEADLINE> Reuters Revenues Up 8 Pct. in 1st Q  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- British media and information company Reuters
Group reported an 8 percent increase in first-quarter revenues to
$1.31 billion, led by a strong performance in Instinet, the world's
largest electronic brokerage service.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters said, however, that it hasn't completed plans to sell
Instinet shares to the public, and added that the current
volatility in global stock markets probably will slow its efforts
to list its Internet Greenhouse Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stellar performance by Instinet has been particularly
notable in its non-U.S. business,'' chief executive Peter Job said,
in response to concerns expressed by analysts that Instinet relied
too heavily on trading volumes on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in a conference call with analysts Tuesday, Job
affirmed that Reuters is still considering making an initial public
offering of shares in Instinet. Instinet posted a 58 percent
increase in revenues compared to the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The group's need to respond to the rebounding economies of Asia,
together with the recent launch of Instinet's fixed-income
products, have kept Reuters executives too busy to focus on
preparing for an Instinet IPO, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Job added that growth for the Reuters Technical Solutions unit
fell 3 percent at constant exchange rates, due partly to its slow
recovery from Y2K-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Reuters Information division saw sales grow by 6 percent,
thanks to new orders in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters did not release quarterly earnings figures. Like many
other British companies, Reuters only releases profit reports twice
a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
