Nasdaq Composite Index:       3729.85 + 190.69
Gold(final) -    $281.00    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.
</P>
<P>
   Housing Starts Fall 11.2 Percent
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Housing construction, dampened by an upswing
in mortgage rates, took its biggest dive in six years last month --
down 11.2 percent from the previous month. Economists said the
plunge won't stop the Federal Reserve from pushing interest rates
higher to slow the speeding economy and keep inflation under
control. Builders began work on new homes at a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 1.60 million in March, the Commerce Department said
today. It marked the sharpest one-month drop since January 1994,
when housing starts fell by 17 percent. Housing starts were up 3.6
percent in February.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Ministers Hasten Debt Relief
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Echoing a major cause of demonstrators who
failed to shut them down, finance ministers from around the world
acted at their spring meeting to hasten debt relief for poor
countries. While the thousands of protesters failed to stop the
work of the International Monetary Fund and World Bank, they drew
public attention to their complaints that the two institutions have
failed to alleviate global poverty and should be abolished. For
their part, IMF, the World Bank and Washington police officials
took satisfaction in the avoidance of violent confrontations and
destruction of property such as occurred in Seattle last fall at
the World Trade Organization meeting.
</P>
<P>
   J&AMP;J, Pfizer Top Forecasts
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Johnson &AMP; Johnson and Pfizer Inc., two of the
nation's largest pharmaceutical makers, reported strong earnings
growth in the first quarter, topping analysts' forecasts. J&AMP;J's
profits were up 15.5 percent on earnings of $1.3 billion, or 80
cents a share. Pfizer profit before onetime gains surged 33 percent
in the first quarter. Excluding one-time events, the company had
net income of $1.09 billion, or 28 cents per share, up from $815
million or 21 cents per share a year ago. Pfizer stock was up 1] at
39] this afternoon; J&AMP;J was up 3 15/16 at 81 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar Posts Higher 1Q Earns
</P>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ill. (AP) -- Caterpillar, the world's largest maker of
construction equipment, reported a 12 percent increase in
first-quarter earnings today as higher sales and a cost-cutting
program continued to pay off. Caterpillar earned $258 million, or
73 cents a share, in the first three months of the year, up from
$205 million, or 57 cents a share, for the same period in 1999.
Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had expected
earnings of 58 cents per share. Revenue was $4.92 billion for the
quarter, up from $4.87 billion. Caterpillar said it expects overall
sales and profit in 2000 to be higher than last year.
</P>
<P>
   Paine Webber Beats 1Q Expectations
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Paine Webber Group Inc., the fourth-largest U.S.
brokerage firm, reported a 9.8 percent increase in profit for the
first quarter, beating Wall Street estimates. Earnings were $176.3
million, or $1.16 a share, for the January-March period compared
with $160.6 million, or $1.01 a share in the same period a year
ago. Analysts had expected earnings of $1.09 this ear. First
quarter revenues after interest expenses were $1.6 billion, up from
$1.3 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   McGraw-Hill Earnings Nearly Double
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- First-quarter earnings at The McGraw-Hill Cos.
nearly doubled on increased advertising in Business Week magazine
and higher revenues from its Standard &AMP; Poor's financial services
division. Not counting a one-time gain from the sale of a business,
McGraw-Hill earned $47.4 million in the first quarter, or 24 cents
a share, easily eclipsing the 14 cents a share forecast by stock
analysts. Revenues rose 12 percent to $802.5 million. McGraw-Hill
stock was up 6 11/16 at 49 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Mellon Reports Increase in Profits
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Mellon Financial Corp. reported profits in the
first quarter rose almost 10 percent driven by a surge in trust and
investment fees as well as lower costs. The bank also announced an
increase in its dividend. Net income totaled $253 million, or 50
cents a share, topping Wall Street's estimate by a penny. Mellon
earned $231 million, or 43 cents a share, in the first quarter of
1999. Trust and investment fee revenue rose 17 percent from the
first quarter of last year, the company said. Mellon also said it
would raise its dividend by 10 percent to 22 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Weyerhaeuser Earnings Jump in 1st Q
</P>
<P>
   FEDERAL WAY, Wash. (AP) -- Weyerhaeuser, the major paper and
forest products maker, reported sharply higher earnings of $244
million in the first quarter as better market conditions boosted
sales. The earnings equal to $1.04 a share were substantially more
than analysts' predictions of 93 cents. Revenues jumped nearly 50
percent to $3.91 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One Profits Sink 40 Percent
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Bank One Corp. saw first-quarter earnings plummet
by 40 percent as fallout from serious problems with its credit-card
unit continued to erode profits at the nation's fourth-largest
bank. The poor showing, however, met Wall Street's latest lowered
expectations and Bank One shares rose on the New York Stock
Exchange. Net profits for the first three months of 2000 were $689
million, or 60 cents a share, down from $1.151 billion, or 96 cents
a share, for the same period a year ago. many analysts, in their
fourth lowered estimate since August, had forecast 60-cents
per-share earnings following the bank company's warning last month
of a weak quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann Unit Sold to Siemens
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Electronics maker Siemens AG and
Robert Bosch GmbH emerged as the winning bidders for Mannesmann
AG's engineering and auto business with a sweetened offer of $9.2
billion. Mannesmann decided to sell the Atecs division to the pair
yesterday after German steelmaker ThyssenKrupp AG failed to raise
its offer of $8.3 billion. But analysts have questioned the logic
of the bid, especially since Siemens managers have been trying to
slim down the massive electronics and engineering conglomerate
ahead of a planned listing on the New York Stock Exchange next
year.
