<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian, Ukraine Presidents Meet  </HEADLINE>
By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- The presidents of Ukraine and Russia
pledged Tuesday to deepen cooperation in arms production and
building nuclear reactors, but left other pressing problems between
their neighboring nations unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin arrived in Ukraine late Monday
on the last leg of his first foreign trip since he was elected last
month, a journey that also took him to Britain and Belarus. He was
accompanied by Russia's foreign and defense ministers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will consider everything that has been created so far as a
good base for developing Ukrainian-Russian relations,'' Putin said
after meeting with Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchma said he was ''deeply satisfied'' with the talks, adding
that Putin's visit had a highly symbolic meaning for Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   ''Despite a series of problems in Russian-Ukrainian relations
... we found a way today to solve them in the future,'' Kuchma
said.
</P>
<P>
   The talks at the ornate Mariyinsky Palace in downtown Kiev
touched on cooperation in arms production. Russia and Ukraine were
major arms producers in the Soviet era and now often compete for
export contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Putin also said Russia was willing to help Ukraine complete two
new nuclear reactors meant to compensate for the planned closure of
the Chernobyl power plant, site of the world's worst nuclear
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is Ukraine's main trade partner, but volume has dropped
17 percent since Russia's 1998 financial crisis to about $10.4
billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Ukraine and Russia have been troubled since
the 1991 Soviet collapse. A key rift has been over the ex-Soviet
Black Sea Fleet and the mainly ethnic Russian Crimean peninsula.
Many Russian politicians say Sevastopol, the fleet's Crimean home
base, should belong to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Agreements were reached on dividing the fleet in 1997, but
tensions remain.
</P>
<P>
   Putin avoided politically charged remarks and said the city was
a ''sacred place'' for both nations.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine's huge debt for Russian natural gas supplies featured
prominently in Tuesday's talks.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine says the debts total at least $1.4 billion, but Russian
gas officials say the figure stands at $2.1 billion. Russia also
accuses Ukraine of stealing gas from export pipelines headed
through Ukraine to European markets.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchma blamed gas companies for the thefts.
</P>
<P>
   Ukrainian officials expect Putin to take a tough stance toward
gas thefts and debt repayment.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchma said joint commissions will look into Russian energy
supplies and issue recommendations in May.
</P>
<P>
   Putin said Ukrainian Prime Minister Viktor Yushchenko on Tuesday
offered a ''constructive'' plan of debt repayment, but did not
elaborate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-18-00 1510 </TRAILER>
