<DOCNO> APW20000418.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 204;Dow Up 129  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks continued their dramatic
recovery from last week's selloff today, driving the Nasdaq
composite index more than 200 points higher. Blue-chip stocks also
advanced sharply.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the
Nasdaq composite index was up 204.74 at 3,743.90, while the Dow
Jones industrial average rose 129.37 to 10,711.88.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 28.83 at 1,430.27.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks extended a rally that gained momentum in the final hour
of trading on Monday, leaving the Dow with a gain of 276.74 points
and the Nasdaq with a 217.87-point advance, its biggest single-day
point gain ever.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was a dramatic turnaround from crushing losses last
week. Still, most analysts are saying it's too soon to declare a
full recovery from the carnage last week, when the U.S. stock
market lost nearly $2 trillion in value.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not out of the woods entirely,'' said Russell Jones,
chief Asia economist for the investment bank Lehman Brothers in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Investors kept their focus on companies with proven track
records, shunning newer issues and stocks in the more speculative
Internet sector. But in a sign that some investors were dropping
their guard, biotechnology company Amgen returned to life, rising
4{ to 57~.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings reports provided a catalyst for buying today. Dow
component Johnson &AMP; Johnson rose 3 13/16 to 81 9/16 after reporting
first-quarter profits that beat analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Intel rose 4} to 127}. The company, the world's largest maker of
computer chips, was expected to report its first-quarter earnings
after the 4 p.m. close of trading. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
raised its rating on Intel stock to ''strong buy'' from
''outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, investors were favoring large-capitalization,
well-known technology names. Sun Microsystems rose 6| to 91{ and
Microsoft rose 4 5/16 to 80 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the government delivered a report that eased some
fears about inflation. The Commerce Department said housing
construction plummeted 11.2 percent in March, the biggest plunge in
six years, suggesting that rising mortgage rates are cutting into
demand.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to slow the economy to a sustainable pace, the
Federal Reserve has raised interest rates five times since last
June. The slowdown in housing starts offered some hope that the
rate increases are working, reducing the odds of steep increases
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   But most analysts continue to expect a series of modest
increases.
</P>
<P>
   ''Higher interest rates are clearly having an impact,'' said
Mark Vitner, economist at First Union Securities. ''But that
probably is not enough of a slowing to keep the Fed from pushing
interest rates higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are highly sensitive to interest rates
and inflation, benefited from the report. American Express rose 5]
to 139] and J.P. Morgan rose 5[ to 130[.
</P>
<P>
   The market's breadth improved, with more stocks joining in the
effort to rally. Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 863.59
million shares, compared with 915.95 million at the same time
Monday. On the Nasdaq, advancers led by a 3-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 21.79 to 480.55.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
