<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Reaches Angola Violations Deal  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council reached agreement
Tuesday on a resolution warning it may take action against
countries that have violated sanctions against Angola's UNITA
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The council was expected to adopt the resolution at the
conclusion of an open debate Tuesday during which countries
implicated in a blunt report on the embargo violations were
expected to again defend their records.
</P>
<P>
   The groundbreaking report, issued last month, enumerated the
widespread violations of the U.N. fuel and arms embargo, and a ban
on rebel diamond exports, which enabled UNITA to restart a
20-year-old war with the government in December 1998, shattering a
U.N.-brokered cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   It recommended a host of measures to tighten the grip of
sanctions around UNITA, including a three-year arms embargo on
named countries that violated the weapons ban, followed by a
three-year probation.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution being considered Tuesday wouldn't impose any
immediate punishment on sanctions-busters. But the chairman of the
sanctions committee on Angola, Ambassador Robert Fowler of Canada,
said those implicated shouldn't take that omission as any
indication of the council's lack of resolve.
</P>
<P>
   The report by an independent panel alleged two sitting African
presidents, Blaise Compaore of Burkina Faso and Gnassingbe Eyadema
of Togo, helped UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi with arms and fuel
shipments in exchange for diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   And it accused Belgium of having such lax standards at its
Antwerp diamond market that rogue dealers were able to trade UNITA
gems with virtually no obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   The countries implicated have denied the allegations, defended
their records and challenged the report's evidence, noting that it
relied heavily on information provided by rebel defectors.
</P>
<P>
   The draft resolution would authorize a five-person monitoring
group to continue to gather information about alleged violations
and allow implicated countries to report back on ways they are
upholding the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The council this fall would then consider ''appropriate action''
against nations that violation U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Canada and Namibia, which is battling UNITA forces in Congo, had
wanted a stronger resolution that initially included a call for
countries to issue arrest warrants for people known to be helping
violate sanctions. That element was dropped from the final draft.
</P>
<P>
   But France sought to weaken the call for sanctions on the
sanctions violators, concerned about its former colonies and the
precedent that so-called secondary sanctions would make.
</P>
<P>
   French Ambassador Jean-David Levitte noted that several of the
implicated countries had already taken measures to correct any past
violations.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not by multiplying the pariah states that we will give
incentives to these to return to the straight and narrow,'' Levitte
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-18-00 1536 </TRAILER>
