<DOCNO> APW20000418.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Probing Ill. Gov. Scandal  </HEADLINE>
By JAMES WEBB, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Federal prosecutors investigating a
licenses-for-sale scandal that began when Gov. George Ryan was
secretary of state are now also looking into whether Ryan's aides
interfered with a state police probe of his 1998 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1998, state police looked into whether Ryan employees
were improperly campaigning for him on state time. The Ryan
campaign was cleared of wrongdoing about a month before the
election. But during the probe, officials from the secretary of
state's inspector general's office were allowed to sit in on the
state police interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors now want to know whether Ryan aides
interfered with the probe, according to sources who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   At least five current or former members of the state police
internal investigation division, which conducted the 1998 campaign
probe, have been subpoenaed to testify before a federal grand jury,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're looking for interference,'' said a source familiar
with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest offshoot of an investigation into a scandal in
which truckers paid bribes to obtain commercial driver's licenses
from the secretary of state's office, which oversees the motor
vehicle bureau.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 31 people have been charged, ranging from low-level
government employees to driving school operators, and 25 have
pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The head of Ryan's anti-corruption office at that time, former
Inspector General Dean Bauer, was indicted in February on charges
he covered up wrongdoing in the secretary of state's office to save
Ryan from embarrassment. Bauer has pleaded innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan has not been charged with any wrongdoing. He has said he
knew nothing about the payoffs, even though officials say $170,000
in bribe money ended up in his campaign fund.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Culloton, a spokesman for Ryan, had no immediate comment
on the latest development.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's involvement in the campaign probe posed
a potential problem because it could have suggested to employees
being questioned that their statements would be relayed to their
superiors in the secretary of state's office. It also provided an
avenue for alerting potential wrongdoers to where the state police
investigation was going.
</P>
<P>
   Police ''felt their investigation was being compromised and I
think that was an accurate feeling,'' said Allan F. Lolie Jr., a
special prosecutor on the case.
</P>
<P>
   The key contact in the inspector general's office during the
state police investigation, Ernest Neumann, said the agreement that
allowed officials from the inspector's general office to be present
was aimed at limiting the probe so the matter could be settled
before the election.
</P>
<P>
   ''I sure wasn't going to do anything to hinder'' the
investigation, Neumann said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
