<HEADLINE> Grains Mixed; Soybeans Up a Bit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean prices nosed higher Tuesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade in a mild rally underpinned by the surge in
U.S. and international stock markets. Grains were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   The wet outlook in the Midwest sent prices lower early in the
session, but they bounced back with the equities rise and on
forecasts calling for drier weather next week.
</P>
<P>
   Corn climbed up slightly amid skepticism that showers in growing
areas would amount to enough to change the overall picture of
drier-than-normal soil conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat, meanwhile, settled lower. A storm system expected to
bring substantial precipitation to wheat-growing regions in the
central and south-central United States pressured the market.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery fell 1\ cent to $2.64\ a bushel; May
corn rose { cent to $2.24{ a bushel; July oats rose \ cent to
$1.19} a bushel; July soybeans rose 3 cents to $5.47 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures advanced in trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle rose .30 cent to 69.27 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle rose .20 cent to 84.47 cents a pound; June lean hogs
rose 1.30 cent to 75.65 cents a pound; May pork bellies rose the
limit 3 cents to 97.95 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
