<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hirshhorn Shows Dali's Serious Side  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Salvador Dali, whom many remember as that clownish
self-promoter with the upturned mustachios, is getting a highly
serious exhibit at the Hirshhorn Museum beginning Wednesday for his
work on art as optical illusion.
</P>
<P>
   Dali's surrealistic signature--soft, floppy pocket watches,
draped over a tree branch--are not to be seen. But there's a floppy
cello, and flexible piano keyboards like ocean waves.
</P>
<P>
   Just as surrealistic is a big, dripping eye, one of five
paintings Dali made for the dream sequences in Alfred Hitchcock's
film ''Spellbound.''
</P>
<P>
   The painter reported in his one-man newspaper, the Dali News,
that his Hollywood agent told him:
</P>
<P>
   ''They adore all that you are doing at the Selznick studios, but
I want to caution you, for the moment they want to use you only in
small drops.''
</P>
<P>
   Egoism and clownishness find a place too, complete with
mustachios, in a picture called ''The Sun and Dali.''
</P>
<P>
   Art as optical illusion, the point of the exhibit, comes across
in such work as ''Skull of Zurbaran,'' a human skull that Dali
makes up with cubes and other geometric forms. Francisco de
Zurbaran was a Spanish painter of the 1600s.
</P>
<P>
   A whole room in the show illustrates Dali's experiments with an
early form of three-dimensional illusion. Two identical pictures,
done from slightly different angles, can be viewed to give a 3-D
effect. In the 1900s a favorite parlor pastime was to experience a
primitive kind of virtual reality by viewing pairs of travel
photos, shot from slightly different angles, through a hand-held
stereoscope.
</P>
<P>
   The Hirshhorn has arranged ingenious sets of mirrors for viewing
stereoscopic pairs that Dali painted, including a harbor scene with
a huge female nude.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Zilczer, the Hirshhorn's curator of painting, called him
one of the great painters of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's probably true that because of the antics that he pulled
during his career and because of some of the incidents later in his
life, his reputation has somewhat declined,'' she said. ''And it is
our hope that an exhibition such as this will force a reappraisal
of the artist and his contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Dali had interests in politics and history, too. A powerful
evocation of the Spanish Civil War bears a typical Dali title:
''Soft Construction with Boiled Beans,'' but shows parts of a human
body, strangling itself.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the United States when World War II broke out and
created a sculpture he called ''Nieuw Amsterdam,'' the name of New
York when it was a Dutch colony. It's a bronze bust, by another
artist, of White Eagle who resisted the confinement of Indians to
reservations. In his eyes Dali put tiny portraits of Dutch
burghers. They are apparently toasting the purchase of Manhattan
from a bottle of Coca Cola painted on the nose.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''Dali's Optical Illusions'' will be at the Hirshhorn through
June 18. Admission is free, no tickets are required and the museum
has set aside a special entrance in anticipation of large crowds.
It recommends calling (202) 786-2122 for recorded information and
updates.
</P>
<P>
   The show travels to the Scottish National Gallery of Modern Art
in Edinburgh, July 23-Oct. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-18-00 1608 </TRAILER>
