<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-Russian Militia Leader Resigns  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- A pro-Russian Chechen militia leader said
Tuesday he was resigning, while the Kremlin said contacts with the
rebel republic's president were continuing but played down the
possibility of direct talks.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, meanwhile, sent new troops into the southern mountains
where Chechen rebels are concentrated, even as a top military
official said the major military actions of the 8-month-long war
are over.
</P>
<P>
   Bislan Gantamirov, a Chechen tapped by the Kremlin last fall to
lead a pro-Russian police force, said on RTR television that he
resigned because his force had been sidelined by Russian
paramilitary police.
</P>
<P>
   The paramilitary police have conducted operations that human
rights groups have said are often accompanied by looting, beatings
and arbitrary arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Gantamirov is detested by the rebels as a traitor, and his
resignation could remove one of the many issues between the
insurgents and the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, Gantamirov has played a chameleon role in
Chechnya's chaotic politics. A onetime ally of the late Chechen
separatist leader, Dzhokhar Dudayev, Gantamirov switched to
supporting Russia and formed a paramilitary force in the 1994-96
war.
</P>
<P>
   He became deputy prime minister in the Moscow-backed Chechen
government, but in 1996 was imprisoned for embezzling millions of
dollars Moscow provided for rebuilding Chechnya. Gantamirov was
released from prison in November and a week later, the Kremlin
appointed him head of the pro-Moscow Chechen State Council.
</P>
<P>
   He formed a militia, recruited in part from rebel defectors, and
it fought alongside Russian units in storming Grozny, the Chechen
capital.
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin's spokesman on Chechnya, Sergei
Yastrzhembsky, said Tuesday that Moscow is continuing to talk with
Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov through intermediaries in
exploring political solutions to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Russian leadership understands perfectly that exclusive
military means will not solve the Chechen problem,'' Yastrzhembsky
said. ''But without the military phase, it's impossible to use
political means.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Russia wants to see Maskhadov demonstrate goodwill by
handing over suspected terrorists and surrendering weapons before
talks begin -- conditions that could prove impossible for Maskhadov
because of his weak control over the many rebel bands.
</P>
<P>
   A Maskhadov aide, Felim Bezhayev, said the rebels are ready for
direct talks immediately, because it would accelerate ''the process
of settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   The fierce battles of winter have subsided in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   The ITAR-Tass news agency, citing the military press center in
Khankala near Grozny, said more than 3,000 paratroopers landed in
the Shatoi region on Tuesday. The area, deep in the southern
mountains, saw intense fighting this winter.
</P>
<P>
   The first deputy chief of the Russian general staff, Col. Gen.
Valery Manilov, denied that thousands of paratroopers were sent in,
but he told the Interfax news agency that troops in the region were
reinforced.
</P>
<P>
   ''The talk is now that the war has finished -- large-scale
actions, the military part of the operation have been finished,''
he said at a news conference. Russia has claimed frequently that
the rebels are on the verge of defeat, but the fighters keep
mounting ambushes and attacks.
</P>
<P>
   After moving into Chechnya in September, Russian troops seized
about two-thirds of the republic in steady advances across the
northern flatlands. The Russians bogged down in the southern
mountains, the last major area still under rebel control.
</P>
<P>
   Russia sent ground troops into Chechnya after weeks of
airstrikes, following an invasion of neighboring Dagestan by
Chechnya-based rebels. The rebels are also blamed for the apartment
bombings in Russia in September that killed about 300 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
