<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fed: Foreign Banks Treated Fairly  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve, responding to complaints
from the European Union, said foreign banks are treated fairly
under new U.S. rules that permit banks to expand their services.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the Europeans have raised concerns about
rules governing capital requirements for foreign banks that want to
expand beyond their core banking business to sell securities,
insurance and other services in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems to be that this is a fair and flexible process, given
the number and wide variety of foreign banks that operate in the
United States,'' Fed Governor Laurence Meyer said in a letter to
John Mogg, director general for financial services with the
European Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, dated Monday, was released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The principle of national treatment requires that foreign
banks operating in the United States meet standards that are at
least comparable to those we apply to our own banks,'' the letter
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
