<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mostly Up; Gold Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar rose against most other major
currencies in European trading today. Gold fell.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was quoted at 94.81 cents in late European trading,
down from 95.56 cents Monday. Later, in midday trading in New York,
the euro traded at 94.90 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday,
included 104.46 Japanese yen, up from 104.13; 1.6582 Swiss francs,
up from 1.6424; 1.4830 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4862.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound was quoted at $1.5767, down from $1.5862.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 104.68 yen, and
the pound was worth $1.5772.
</P>
<P>
   Based on euro rates, the dollar is worth 2.0627 German marks, up
from 2.0463; 6.9171 French francs, up from 6.8600; 2.3231 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.3047; 2,042.05 Italian lire, up from 2,024.96.
</P>
<P>
   Gold closed in London at $281.20 bid per troy ounce, down from
$281.30 on Monday. In Zurich the bid price was $280.75 up from
$280.65. In Hong Kong, gold closed at $281.25 an ounce, down $3.00
from Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Silver closed in London at $5.11 bid per troy ounce, unchanged
from Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
