<HEADLINE> Texas Sheriff Bans Black Gloves  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARGO, Fla. (AP) -- The sheriff has barred his deputies from
wearing black gloves after people complained that they make the law
officers look like thugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expect my deputies to be aggressive against criminals,''
Sheriff Everett Rice said. ''But I don't want them walking around
looking like the Gestapo.''
</P>
<P>
   The black gloves are not part of the standard green and white
uniform. Deputies said they wear them only to protect their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said the ban will continue until someone can come up with a
non-threatening color.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Cal Dennie, a sheriff's spokesman, said he has two black
pairs that he bought himself and wears them when he is going into a
volatile situation where he might scrape his knuckles.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're for my own protection,'' Dennie said. ''You know how
it is today, not everybody is as clean as they should be. You have
to be concerned about body fluids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
