<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Has Record Gain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks drove the Nasdaq composite
index to its biggest point gain ever today as investors flocked
back to the names that were devastated by last week's rout.
Blue-chip stocks also advanced sharply.
</P>
<P>
   According to preliminary calculations, the Nasdaq composite
index rose 254.08 to close at 3,743.24, while the Dow Jones
industrial average rose 179.94 to 10,762.45.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp rally served as an exclamation point to big gains on
Monday, when stocks began recovering from last week's devastating
collapse. In just two sessions, the Nasdaq has regained 471.95
points, or more than one-third, of last week's losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq remains 25 percent below the peak it reached on March
10, but has narrowed its losses for the year to 6.8 percent. At its
low point last week, the Nasdaq had dropped more than 18 percent
from the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq stalwarts like Sun Microsystems, Microsoft and Cisco
Systems all rose sharply, fueling the rally. Yet analysts were
heartened by investors' willingness to branch out from the biggest
technology names and buy shares of smaller companies and stocks in
the more volatile Internet and biotechnology sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! and online brokerage ETrade bounded higher; biotechnology
company Amgen also returned to life.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's behavior is much more impressive than yesterday,''
said Barry Hyman, senior equity analyst at Ehrenkrantz King
Nussbaum. ''This is the way the market must trade if this rally is
to be maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies, which was nearly as
ravaged as the Nasdaq by last week's selloff, rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most analysts are saying it's too soon to declare a full
recovery from the carnage last week, when the U.S. stock market
lost nearly $2 trillion in value.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not out of the woods entirely,'' said Russell Jones,
chief Asia economist for the investment bank Lehman Brothers in
Tokyo. Volatility remained high, and stock market indexes pulled
back sharply in late afternoon before making one final push in the
last half-hour of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings reports provided a catalyst for buying today. Dow
component Johnson &AMP; Johnson rose after reporting first-quarter
profits that beat analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Intel rose. The company, the world's largest maker of computer
chips, was expected to report its first-quarter earnings after the
4 p.m. close of trading. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised its
rating on Intel stock to ''strong buy'' from ''outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the government delivered a report that eased some
fears about inflation. The Commerce Department said housing
construction plummeted 11.2 percent in March, the biggest plunge in
six years, suggesting that rising mortgage rates are cutting into
demand.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to slow the economy to a sustainable pace, the
Federal Reserve has raised interest rates five times since last
June. The slowdown in housing starts offered some hope that the
rate increases are working, reducing the odds of steep increases
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   But most analysts continue to expect a series of modest
increases.
</P>
<P>
   ''Higher interest rates are clearly having an impact,'' said
Mark Vitner, economist at First Union Securities. ''But that
probably is not enough of a slowing to keep the Fed from pushing
interest rates higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are highly sensitive to interest rates
and inflation, benefited from the report. American Express and J.P.
Morgan rose.
</P>
<P>
   The market's breadth improved, with more stocks joining in the
effort to rally. Yet Hyman said many of the smaller and mid-sized
technology stocks that rose today may never return to the highs
reached prior to last week's washout.
</P>
<P>
   ''I that we don't forget the lessons learned last week,'' he
said. ''Earnings and valuations are important, and when they're
ignored, catastrophic drops can occur.''
</P>
<P>
   According to preliminary calculations, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
rose 40.17 to 1,441.61.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by nearly a 2-to-1 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,990 up, 1,016 down and 442
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 1.09 billion shares as of 4 p.m., vs. 1.29
billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 23.03 to
482.29.
</P>
<P>
