<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBC To Rebroadcast News on PAX  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC's purchase of a stake in the Pax television
network is paying dividends for Tom Brokaw: the family-friendly
broadcaster has agreed to rerun his evening news broadcast each
night.
</P>
<P>
   Pax TV stations will package ''NBC Nightly News'' with a
rebroadcast of the NBC affiliate's local news for that market in an
hourlong news block that will run from 7 to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement will start in May as a one-month test and,
unless something goes wrong, will begin regularly in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Pax TV is carried on smaller stations and cable systems
throughout the country, reaching 77 percent of U.S. households,
often in areas already reached by major TV stations affiliated with
NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The nightly news rerun is the latest example of TV repurposing,
an idea that makes major network affiliates nervous. Some
executives at local stations are worried that if viewers can see a
program on another network at another time, it will cut into their
viewership.
</P>
<P>
   ABC last year began allowing weekly episodes of its ''Once and
Again'' drama to run on the Lifetime network. NBC's cable partner,
MSNBC, briefly rebroadcast NBC's ''Today'' show in the afternoons,
but stopped because the ratings were low.
</P>
<P>
   Since NBC owns 13 local stations, the network wouldn't be doing
anything it believed could be harmful to these stations, said NBC
President Randy Falco.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have more to lose than they do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Nightly News'' has a better chance of succeeding on Pax TV
because it will be shown only an hour after its original broadcast,
Falco said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal announced Tuesday, Pax will also rebroadcast
some NBC coverage of U.S. Olympic trials beginning in June.
</P>
<P>
   The carriage of NBC programming on Pax was part of an
understanding reached last September when NBC, a unit of General
Electric Co., agreed to acquire a 32 percent stake in the company
for $415 million.
</P>
<P>
   For Pax, which is based in West Palm Beach, Fla., the deal was a
way to bolster its roster of programming, which depends heavily on
wholesome programs like ''Chicken Soup for the Soul.'' Pax already
rebroadcasts NBC's game show ''Twenty One'' on Saturday nights.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see too many opportunities in the short-term for us to
do more of that,'' Falco said, noting that NBC is restricted from
repurposing entertainment programs that it does not own.
</P>
<P>
   Like CBS and ABC, NBC's rapport with its affiliates has been on
the decline as the networks seek to revise decades-old agreements
requiring them to pay station owners to carry their programming.
Fox doesn't pay its affiliates to carry its programming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-18-00 1658 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
