<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Tuesday, April 18, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nasdaq Gains Record 254; Dow Up 179
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks drove the Nasdaq composite
index to its biggest point gain ever today as investors flocked
back to the names that were devastated by last week's rout.
Blue-chip stocks also advanced sharply. The Nasdaq composite index
rose 254.08 to close at 3,743.24, while the Dow Jones industrial
average rose 179.94 to 10,762.45. Broader stock indicators were
also higher and advancing issues outnumbered decliners. The sharp
rally served as an exclamation point to big gains yesterday, when
stocks began recovering from last week's devastating collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:
Dow Industrials:        10762.45 + 179.94
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1983  Declines 1011  Unchgd  444
NYSE Volume:       1,093,172,830
Most Active NYSE issue:         America Online60{   + 2 1/16 
S&AMP;P 500:         1439.87 + 38.43
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          877.36 + 28.39
Nasdaq Composite Index        3743.24 + 254.08
Gold(final) -    $281.00    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.
</P>
<P>
   European Stocks Close Higher
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Gains in European technology, media and telecom
stocks late today reversed early losses. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index
of shares in European companies rose 4.66 points, or 1.3 percent,
to 372.81. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, ended up 5.17 points at
419.84. The Pan-European technology index Easdaq was up 1.6
percent. Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index ended up 0.1 percent to
7,196.49. Allianz rose 0.2 percent and Commerzbank was up 2.8
percent. London's FTSE-100 index closed up 1.4 percent, at 6,074.0.
The Paris CAC-40 Index was up 1.4 percent to 6,147.44, with Canal
Plus, Equant and France Telecom leading gainers. Milan's MIBtel
Index was up 1.0 percent to 29,834 and Amsterdam's AEX Index up 1.3
percent to 646.43.
</P>
<P>
   Housing Starts Fall 11.2 Percent
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Housing construction, dampened by an upswing
in mortgage rates, took its biggest dive in six years last month --
down 11.2 percent from the previous month. Economists said the
plunge won't stop the Federal Reserve from pushing interest rates
higher to slow the speeding economy and keep inflation under
control. Builders began work on new homes at a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 1.60 million in March, the Commerce Department said
today.
</P>
<P>
   Coke Boosts Sales, But Posts 1Q Loss
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- The Coca-Cola Co. posted a loss for the first
quarter but its results before onetime items beat analysts'
expectations. The world's biggest soft drink company lost $58
million, or 2 cents per share, in the January-March period after
writing down $405 million in assets for its operations in India and
a $275 million charge from its ongoing corporate realignment. But
excluding one-time items, Coke earned 22 cents a share, thanks in
part to a 3.5 percent increase in worldwide sales. Many analysts
had expected a 41-cent figure. Coca-Cola shares fell 13/16 today to
47 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Ministers Hasten Debt Relief
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Finance ministers from around the world acted
at their spring meeting to hasten debt relief for poor countries.
The action was in line with one of the points thousands of
protesters had stressed as they tried but failed to stop the work
of the International Monetary Fund and World Bank at their spring
meetings. The protesters said the two institutions have failed to
alleviate global poverty and should be abolished. Police staved off
violent confrontations and destruction of property of the kind that
took place last fall at the Seattle meeting of the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   	   J&AMP;J, Pfizer Top Forecasts
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Johnson &AMP; Johnson and Pfizer Inc., two of the
nation's largest pharmaceutical makers, reported strong earnings
growth in the first quarter, beating analysts' forecasts. J&AMP;J's
profits were up 15.5 percent on earnings of $1.3 billion, or 80
cents a share. Pfizer profit before onetime gains surged 33 percent
in the first quarter. Excluding one-time events, the company had
net income of $1.09 billion, or 28 cents per share, up from $815
million or 21 cents per share a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar Posts Higher 1Q Earns
</P>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ill. (AP) -- Caterpillar, the world's largest maker of
construction equipment, reported a 12 percent increase in
first-quarter earnings today thanks to higher sales and
cost-cutting. Caterpillar earned $258 million, or 73 cents a share,
in the first three months of the year, up from $205 million, or 57
cents a share, for the same period in 1999. Revenue was $4.92
billion for the quarter, up from $4.87 billion. Caterpillar said it
expects overall sales and profit in 2000 to be higher than last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris Earnings Rise in 1Q
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Philip Morris Cos. Inc.'s profit rose more than
12 percent in the first three months of the year as domestic
tobacco shipments surged despite higher prices and results improved
in its food and beer businesses. The results reported today by the
maker of Marlboro cigarettes, Kraft cheese and Miller Lite beer
were in line with Wall Street estimates. But its shares continue to
be weighed down by worries about legal challenges in Florida and by
the U.S. government to its tobacco business. Shares of Philip
Morris fell 9/16 today to 20 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Paine Webber Beats 1Q Expectations
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Paine Webber Group Inc., the fourth-largest U.S.
brokerage firm, reported a 9.8 percent increase in profit for the
first quarter, beating Wall Street estimates. Earnings were $176.3
million, or $1.16 a share, for the January-March period compared
with $160.6 million, or $1.01 a share in the same period a year
ago. Analysts had expected earnings of $1.09 this ear. First
quarter revenues after interest expenses were $1.6 billion, up from
$1.3 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One Profits Sink 40 Percent
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Bank One Corp. saw first-quarter earnings plummet
by 40 percent as fallout from serious problems with its credit-card
unit continued to erode profits at the nation's fourth-largest
bank. The poor showing, however, met Wall Street's latest lowered
expectations and Bank One shares rose on the New York Stock
Exchange. Net profits for the first three months of 2000 were $689
million, or 60 cents a share, down from $1.151 billion, or 96 cents
a share, for the same period a year ago. many analysts, in their
fourth lowered estimate since August, had forecast 60-cents
per-share earnings following the bank company's warning last month
of a weak quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
<P>
   Housing starts: down 11.2 percent
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow: International trade
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: Jobless claims
</P>
