<HEADLINE> White House Predicts China Passage  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Speaker Dennis Hastert pledged Tuesday
that the Republican-controlled House, ''working with the
president,'' will pass legislation for normal trade relations with
China despite the opposition of the Democratic leader, Rep. Dick
Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once again, the House minority leader has chosen partisan
politics over bipartisan progress,'' Hastert, R-Ill., said in a jab
at Gephardt, expected to announce opposition to the legislation
Wednesday in a speech at St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, seconded Hastert's
criticism of Gephardt. ''The would-be speaker of the House is too
tied to big labor and trial lawyers to recognize the needs of the
new economy,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   A vote is expected next month on a measure to grant permanent
normal trade relations with China, rather than continue the current
system of having Congress vote on the issue once a year.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials say Gephardt will declare in his speech
that safeguards in the legislation to protect human rights and
address other concerns in China aren't strong enough to justify
surrendering the leverage that accompanies annual reviews.
</P>
<P>
   As comments from Hastert and Armey suggested, the political
maneuvering is intense on China trade. While divisions exist in
both parties, the split is more pronounced among Democrats, who are
also struggling to gain a House majority in this fall's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor is fighting the trade bill, fearing it will cost
jobs. Business groups, eager to open an enormous new market, are
strongly for it. That sets up a potentially dangerous vote for
Democratic lawmakers from swing districts, who might customarily
rely on support from the AFL-CIO to win difficult re-election
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's decision leaves him at odds with President Clinton
and Vice President Al Gore but in line with other Democratic
leaders in the House and the majority of the party's rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, as Armey's comments suggested, it places
Republicans in position to claim credit if the measure passes but
avoid blame if it fails.
</P>
<P>
   ''Representative Gephardt's announcement makes President
Clinton's job more difficult but not impossible,'' said Armey, one
of numerous Republicans who contend the job of lining up Democratic
votes belongs to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert was more emphatic about the bill's prospects for
passage: ''Working with the president, we will pass PNTR (the China
trade bill) without Mr. Gephardt.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Gephardt's decision ''is based not on sound economic
principles. Rather, it is based on fear, fear of the political
power of Big Labor, fear of the implications of the new economy,
fear of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's imminent decision to oppose the bill was welcomed by
the Democratic whip, Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., whose spokesman
called it a ''positive development.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials say Gephardt is not expected to lobby
against the bill.
</P>
<P>
   His strategy of opposing the measure, but not too strenuously,
appears part of an effort to minimize antagonizing business groups
being wooed to support Democrats in the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, joined his colleagues in criticizing Gephardt, using
official trade figures to say defeat of the bill would cost the
majority leader's home state, Missouri, money and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   While a majority of Democrats seem ready to vote against the
bill, Rep. Bob Matsui, D-Calif., a supporter, has said as many as
70 or so Democrats could wind up in favor of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have a 222-211 majority in the House, with two
independents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
