<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State lists elementary schools for racial imbalance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP)-- Elementary schools in Hamden and Greenwich
are racially imbalanced and may be in violation of state law, the
state Department of Education has found.
</P>
<P>
   The finding that there are not enough minority students at the
schools is the first such determination in the state in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, a single school's minority population must be
within 25 percentage points of the minority population of the
entire school district.
</P>
<P>
   The law is intended to foster racial diversity and prevent a
school district from putting all or most of its minority students
in the same school.
</P>
<P>
   Unaudited figures from schools led the Department of Education
to put four school districts on notice, said Tom Murphy, spokesman
for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   In Hamden, the average elementary school minority population is
40 percent. To stay within the law, no school in Hamden can have
fewer than 15 percent or more than 65 percent of its pupils from
minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   According to enrollment figures, only 44 children, or 14.1
percent of the 311 students at Bear Path Elementary School, are
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   In Greenwich, the district average is 20.7 percent minority.
Hamilton Avenue School was listed because its minority student
population is 52.6 percent, Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   The state found that racial balance also was off at an
alternative school in Norwalk and a magnet school in West Hartford,
but these schools are exempt from the state law because they serve
special populations.
</P>
<P>
   The schools in Greenwich and Hamden must report plans to correct
their imbalance to the Department of Education within the next 120
days.
</P>
<P>
   ''They need to take corrective action, but it appears quite
achievable,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamden Superintendent of Schools Alida Begina the Board of
Education will decide whether the town should redistrict, add
classrooms or an all-day kindergarten to Bear Path Elementary
School or take other steps to address the racial imbalance.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwich school Superintendent Roger Lulow said school leaders
had been discussing whether to make the Hamilton Avenue School an
interdistrict magnet school, before the racial imbalance issue was
brought up.
</P>
<P>
   Lulow said the school is small, and ''four our five kids either
way changes our whole balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The state law that covers racial imbalance in schools was not
enforced for two years, under a directive from the General
Assembly, to give the state time to review how to make the
regulations more fair and to review how imbalance is measured,
Murphy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
