<HEADLINE> Sprint Gains 14 Percent in 1Q  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Sprint Corp. topped Wall Street
forecasts Tuesday with a 14 percent gain in first-quarter operating
profits by the company's regular phone and data business and a
small-than-expected loss by the fast-growing wireless operation.
</P>
<P>
   The company's FON Group, which provides communications services
through traditional wireline connections to customers, earned $907
million or 65 cents a share in the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint, which has agreed to be acquired by MCI WorldCom, said
its net profit totaled $1.12 billion or $1.28 per share due to
one-time factors, especially a gain of $675 million from the sale
of the company's investment in the Global One international
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period in 1999, the wireline operation posted an
operating profit of $795 million or 55 cents a share, and a net
profit of $406 million or 47 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprint PCS division posted a net loss of $513 million or 54
cents a share for the first quarter as the company continued to
invest heavily in expanding and upgrading its wireless network,
with $693 million in capital expenditures for the period. In the
first quarter of 1999, Sprint PCS lost $626 million or 71 cents a
share in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   The PCS group also reported a net gain of 831,000 customers in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ''On both sides of the business -- wireline and wireless -- Sprint
continues to demonstrate its leadership in the marketplace,'' said
William Esrey, Sprint chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's stock trading, Sprint FON shares rose $1 to $57.75,
while Sprint PCS shares rose $6.62{ to $53.37{.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
