<HEADLINE> Accused Treasurer Returns To Work  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Three months after her extortion conviction was
thrown out, Miriam Santos reclaimed her job as Chicago city
treasurer and picked up a fat check covering back pay and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Santos spent four months in federal prison after she was found
guilty last May of trying to extort a $10,000 campaign contribution
from a securities firm and forcing her staff to do campaign work on
city time.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court overturned the conviction in January,
saying the judge had committed ''a veritable avalanche of errors.''
But prosecutors said they are prepared to retry the case and
perhaps add new charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not bitter or angry. You can forget about that stuff,''
Santos, 44, said Monday as she returned to City Hall and collected
her back-pay check, expected to exceed $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, Santos is entitled to return to her elective
office, a $118,650-a-year job, with back pay and pension benefits.
Mayor Richard M. Daley, who appointed a successor after her
conviction, acknowledged last month that she has a right to reclaim
her job.
</P>
<P>
   Santos, who was the Democratic candidate for Illinois attorney
general in 1998, had been accused of threatening to cut off Fuji
Securities from lucrative city business unless it made a $10,000
contribution to the Democratic Party of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   She said that she is ready to get back to business and that
other than cutting back on her use of foul language, she will not
change much about her style, which she described as aimed at
getting things done fast.
</P>
<P>
   Interim Treasurer Barbara Lumpkin, Daley's appointee, said she
will cooperate fully in the transition. She is expected to get a
new job in city government.
</P>
<P>
   ''We saw two classy ladies participate in a transfer of power.
It's been a long time since I've seen that at City Hall,'' said
Santos spokesman Alton Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Three staff members testified against Santos at the trial. Two
of them are leaving for other jobs soon, Lumpkin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
