<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Surges; Copper Rebounds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crude oil futures surged Tuesday on the New York Mercantile
Exchange after a refinery shutdown in Louisiana heightened concerns
about tight U.S. supplies.
</P>
<P>
   In other commodity markets, copper rebounded after falling to an
eight-month low and pork bellies soared.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices were slumping until late in the session when Citgo
closed its 350,000-barrel-a-day refinery in Lake Charles, La.,
following a power outage due to a boiler malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   The refinery, operated by the U.S. refining arm of Venezuela's
state oil company, processes crude into gasoline as well as
distillate and other fuels.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was not believed to be serious but it was enough to
jangle nerves in a market with little cushion against supply
disruptions. Also underpinning the price rise was the strong
showing of equity markets for a second straight day.
</P>
<P>
   West Texas Intermediate crude for May delivery, a contract which
expires Wednesday, settled up 22 cents at $26.11 a barrel -- a
two-week high.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rally really shows that any little refinery problem is
going to magnify the tight supply situation we have,'' said Phil
Flynn, energy analyst for Alaron Trading Corp. in Chicago. ''We're
counting on those refineries to produce at a big clip, and if they
don't shortages could develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring unforeseen supply news, the market now may be headed
toward the upper end of the trading range -- $28 to $29 a barrel --
he suggested. ''Probably the bulls are going to be in charge for
the next couple of days,'' Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Before word of the outage, falling crude had been dragging other
energy commodities lower.
</P>
<P>
   May heating oil settled up 1.31 cent at 70.78 cents a gallon;
May unleaded gasoline rose .88 cent to 82.86 cents a gallon; May
natural gas fell 6 cents to $3.098 per 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   In London, June Brent crude from the North Sea rose 31 cents to
$23.05 a barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   After markets closed, weekly data from the American Petroleum
Institute showed that U.S. refineries operated at 92 percent
capacity last week, up slightly from 91.5 percent the week before.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil stocks rose 6.575 million barrels from the previous
week, according to the API. But gasoline and distillate fuel stocks
both were down -- gasoline by 2.842 million barrels and distillate
by 2.676 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   On the Comex division of the New York Merc, rebounding stock
markets also helped copper prices rally after they dipped to an
eight-month low.
</P>
<P>
   A second day of impressive equity gains helped calm fears that
the U.S. economy might be slowing, which would be a hammer blow to
the construction industry that copper depends on heavily.
</P>
<P>
   May copper settled up 2.1 cents, or 3 percent, at 76.45 cents a
pound after sinking as low as 74.10 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
   The surge reflected bargain-hunting as copper investors ignored
new housing data showing that U.S. housing starts declined by 11
percent in March, a worse fall than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen pork bellies bounced back from an early session slide on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange and hit new contract highs. The
buying surge was attributed to ideas that a shortened slaughter
week would combine with strong post-Easter holiday demand to boost
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Lean hog futures jumped higher on similar notions.
</P>
<P>
   May pork bellies rose the limit 3 cents to 97.95 cents a pound,
while June lean hogs rose 1.30 cent to 75.65 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
