<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Refund Lost? Don't Panic  </HEADLINE>
By MARIA CODER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What do I do if my federal tax refund check is lost or
stolen?
</P>
<P>
   A: Don't panic. If your check is lost or stolen, the money is
still rightfully yours.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you should do is call the IRS' automated TeleTax
number, (800) 829-4477, to check the status of your check. You will
be asked for your Social Security number and the amount of the
refund.
</P>
<P>
   If TeleTax doesn't answer your questions, the next step is to
call (800) TAX-1040, where you can explain your situation to a
person.
</P>
<P>
   According to the IRS, sometimes a refund is delayed by past-due
federal debts, such as delinquent student loans or child support.
You can find out if one of those situations applies to you by
calling (800) TAX-1040.
</P>
<P>
   But if your refund hasn't been held up by such a debt, and you
still haven't been able to find out what happened to your check,
there is another alternative, the national taxpayer advocate
hotline at (877) 777-4778.
</P>
<P>
   As far as tracking down lost or stolen state tax returns, you'll
have to check with your local tax department since procedures vary
from state to state.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that you'll find in the course of your research
that your federal refund check was cashed by somebody else. If so,
the IRS will trace the check and get a photocopy of it, which will
be sent to you so you can verify that the signature endorsing the
check was not your own.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also get IRS Form 3911 -- the Taxpayer Statement Regarding
Refund. If you're married and filing jointly both spouses will be
required to sign the form, which asks you to explain the
circumstances regarding your refund.
</P>
<P>
   It will take about two to three weeks to get the paperwork in
the mail after you've claimed your refund was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ''We try to do this in as speedy a manner as possible but on the
other hand we have to be careful someone is not attempting to
defraud the system,'' said Terry Lemons, an IRS spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS says tens of thousands of refund checks are returned as
undeliverable each year for several reasons -- such as failure to
provide a forwarding address when relocating, or the expiration of
a forwarding address. If you believe your check wasn't delivered
for one of these reasons, first call the TeleTax number, (800)
829-4477. If that doesn't help, try (800) TAX-1040.
</P>
<P>
   In November, IRS district offices ask local newspapers to print
lists of people with uncollected refunds. If you'd like to find if
you're on the list, call 1-800-TAX-1040.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
