<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks Digital Divide Close  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT, AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- President Clinton, at a showcase of high
technology, challenged industry leaders Tuesday to share ''this
astonishing new era of enterprise'' by ensuring that all Americans
have access to computers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm asking you to do this because you can,'' Clinton said.
''I'm asking you to do this because it's right. And I'm asking you
to do this because America needs it to have a continually growing
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came to the Comdex trade show at the close of a two-day
''digital divide'' tour intended to dramatize the gap between
computer haves and have-nots. While government surveys have shown
it to be a ''racial ravine'' between whites and minorities,
academics and industry analysts say Internet access is much more
closely tied to income and education than race.
</P>
<P>
   Strolling through an exhibition hall on the shore of Lake
Michigan, Clinton stopped to try out a warm ergonomic pillow
designed to prevent carpal tunnel syndrome. ''This would be good
for me with my crazy lifestyle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another vendor gave the president a user name (Clinton) and
password (Buddy) for a site for online storage of computer files.
Told that he could hide files that would not accessible to anyone
else, Clinton said, ''We've had enough problems'' -- referring to a
controversy over White House e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   The president also was intrigued by a voice-recognition system
for Internet access. ''Pretty neat, huh?'' Clinton remarked.
''You've given me hope with my big, awkward hands.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, he urged high-tech leaders to support his goal of
providing the latest learning tools to every child in every school
and creating ''digital opportunity for every family and every
community.'' More than 400 businesses, schools, community groups
and volunteers have signed up, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He asked them to help ''give our schools computers and
high-speed connections, to design the educational software our
children need to succeed, to make sure our teachers are as
comfortable in front of a computer as in front of a chalkboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he urged them to expand internships, particularly for
women and minorities, who are underrepresented in most information
technology jobs. Saying there is a limit to what the federal
government can do, the president also encouraged more technology
partnerships with schools, local communities and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the technology boom has accounted for about 30
percent of America's economic growth and ''this astonishing new era
of enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think, just on pure ethical grounds, we all sense that the
American values require that everybody be given a fair chance to
participate,'' Clinton said. ''But secondly, I think it's in our
economic interest to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Washington policy-makers spend a lot of time wondering
how to prolong the economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, it's clear to me that if we want it to continue, we have
to do more to find new markets,'' he said. ''New markets mean
creating new businesses and new employees, as well as new
customers. And if you do both, it means you can have growth without
inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   On his way out of town, Clinton stopped at a restaurant to help
Chicago Mayor Richard Daley celebrate his 58th birthday. The
president lamented that Daley is ''four years older than me and he
looks younger.'' Clinton turns 54 in August.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Washington after five days on the road, the
president heads out again Wednesday to help dedicate a memorial in
Oklahoma City to the 168 people killed five years ago in the
bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
