<HEADLINE> Philip Morris Earnings Rise in 1Q  </HEADLINE>
By SKIP WOLLENBERG, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Philip Morris Cos. Inc.'s profit rose more than
12 percent in the first three months of the year as domestic
tobacco shipments surged despite higher prices and results improved
in its food and beer businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The results reported Tuesday by the maker of Marlboro
cigarettes, Kraft cheese and Miller Lite beer were in line with
Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But its shares continue to be weighed down by worries about
legal challenges in Florida and by the U.S. government to its
tobacco business. Its shares fell 56\ cents to $20.68} in trading
at 4:30 p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris earned $2.01 billion, or 87 cents a share, in the
three months ended March 31 compared with $1.79 billion, or 73
cents a share, a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Its underlying earnings, which include incremental income
related to the arrival of the year 2000 amounted to 89 cents a
share. That matched what analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson
Financial had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 2.8 percent to $20.04 billion from $19.5 billion a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're off to a good start in 2000,'' said chairman and chief
executive Geoffrey C. Bible. ''Our first-quarter results clearly
demonstrate that our business fundamentals are robust.''
</P>
<P>
   Its domestic tobacco profits rose 6.5 percent to $1.1 billion
due to higher pricing and increased shipments to wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   Its shipments climbed 7.1 percent in the quarter compared with a
4.6 percent increase industrywide. Those increases are the biggest
since tobacco prices were increased sharply in the wake of the
industry's costly settlement with the states in 1998 for their
expenses in treating sick smokers.
</P>
<P>
   But Philip Morris attributed the big hike in shipments mainly to
decisions by wholesalers to rebuild inventories this year after
reducing them in the same period a year ago, and to an extra
working day in this year's first quarter. It estimated shipments
would have been down 2.5 percent industrywide without those
factors.
</P>
<P>
   David Adelman, who follows tobacco companies for Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter, estimated retail sales of cigarettes were down 1.5
percent in the first quarter after falling about 8 percent last
year. ''Consumers have gotten over the shock'' of higher prices, he
said. The sales decline more closely resembles the pattern before
the price hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Burry, who follows tobacco for Brown Brothers Harriman &AMP;
Co., said it will take another quarter of shipment and sales
figures to see if the price hikes of 1998 and 1999 have driven a
significant number of smokers out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris said its share of overall domestic tobacco
shipments rose 1.2 share points to 51.6 percent. It cited retail
sales data that said its share of that market rose 0.4 points to
50.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Its international tobacco business posted a 4.1 increase in
profits despite a 1.1 percent decline in sales volume.
</P>
<P>
   In the food business, profits were up 6.1 percent in North
America due to higher volume, productivity savings and favorable
commodity costs. International food earnings rose 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Profits at Miller Brewing rose 12.5 percent, partially due to an
increase in shipments and higher prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
