<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Gains Record 254; Dow Up 189  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks drove the Nasdaq composite
index to its biggest one-day point gain Tuesday as investors
flocked back to the shares that were devastated by last week's
rout. Blue-chip stocks also advanced sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp rally extended Wall Street's big gains of Monday, when
stocks began recovering from last week's collapse. But the market's
gains were far more widespread on Tuesday, with smaller stocks
joining the rally as investors looked for bargains.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts were encouraged by the broadening of the
market, yet continued to warn investors that the market remains
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq rose 254.41 to close at 3,793.57, while the Dow Jones
industrial average rose 184.91 to 10,767.42.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 rose 40.17 to 1,441.61.
</P>
<P>
   In just two sessions, the Nasdaq has regained 472.28 points, or
more than one-third, of last week's losses, and has wiped out the
355-point drop it suffered on Friday. The Nasdaq remains 25 percent
below the peak it reached on March 10, but has narrowed its losses
for the year to 6.8 percent. At its low point last week, the Nasdaq
had dropped more than 18 percent from the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq stalwarts like Sun Microsystems, Microsoft and Cisco
Systems all rose sharply Tuesday, feeding the rally. Sun rose 7
3/16 to 92 1/16, Microsoft gained 4 11/16 to 80 9/16 and Cisco rose
2} to 69\.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were heartened by investors' willingness to branch out
from the biggest technology names and buy shares of smaller
companies and stocks in the more volatile Internet and
biotechnology sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! rose 12 5/16 to 126 11/16 and online brokerage ETrade
rose 3 5/16 to 21{; biotechnology company Amgen also returned to
life, rising 5 to 58].
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's behavior is much more impressive than yesterday,''
said Barry Hyman, senior equity analyst at Ehrenkrantz King
Nussbaum. ''This is the way the market must trade if this rally is
to be maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies, which was nearly as
ravaged as the Nasdaq by last week's selloff, rose 26.81 to 486.09.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most analysts are saying it's too soon to declare a full
recovery from the carnage last week, when the U.S. stock market
lost nearly $2 trillion in value.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not out of the woods entirely,'' said Russell Jones,
chief Asia economist for the investment bank Lehman Brothers in
Tokyo. Volatility remained high, and stock market indexes did pull
back somewhat in late afternoon before making one final push in the
last half-hour of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings reports provided a catalyst for the buying. Dow
component Johnson &AMP; Johnson rose 4 to 81{ after reporting
first-quarter profits that beat analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Intel rose 6 to 129 in advance of its first-quarter earnings
report. After the 4 p.m. close of regular trading, Intel released
earnings that easily topped analysts' estimates. Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter raised its rating on Intel stock to ''strong buy'' from
''outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the government delivered a report that eased some
fears about inflation. The Commerce Department said housing
construction plummeted 11.2 percent in March, the biggest plunge in
six years, suggesting that rising mortgage rates are cutting into
demand.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to slow the economy to a sustainable pace, the
Federal Reserve has raised interest rates five times since last
June. The slowdown in housing starts offered some hope that the
rate increases are working, reducing the odds of steep increases
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   But most analysts continue to expect a series of modest
increases.
</P>
<P>
   ''Higher interest rates are clearly having an impact,'' said
Mark Vitner, economist at First Union Securities. ''But that
probably is not enough of a slowing to keep the Fed from pushing
interest rates higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are highly sensitive to interest rates
and inflation, benefited from the report. American Express rose 5
15/16 to 139 15/16 and J.P. Morgan rose 5{ to 130{.
</P>
<P>
   The market's breadth improved, with more stocks joining in the
effort to rally. Yet Hyman said many of the smaller and mid-sized
technology stocks that rose Tuesday may never return to the highs
reached prior to last week's washout.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope that we don't forget the lessons learned last week,''
he said. ''Earnings and valuations are important, and when they're
ignored, catastrophic drops can occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by nearly a 2-to-1 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, and by a 3-to-1 margin on the
Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE composite volume totaled 1.33 billion shares, compared with
1.44 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.2 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index edged up 0.1 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
rose 1.3 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
