<HEADLINE> Ex-Officer Guilty in Motorist Death  </HEADLINE>
By JIM SUHR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- A white former police officer was convicted of
involuntary manslaughter Tuesday in his retrial in the 1992 beating
death of a black motorist.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Nevers, whose second-degree murder conviction had been
thrown out, sighed, slumped his head and shook it side to side as
the verdict was read.
</P>
<P>
   Nevers contended he was trying to defend himself while arresting
Malice Green outside a suspected crack house on Nov. 5, 1992.
Defense attorney Neil Fink said cocaine contributed to Green's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Nevers broke the law when he used unreasonable
force and struck Green's head 14 times with a heavy flashlight.
They also accused Nevers of ''concocted'' testimony in which he
claimed the 35-year-old unemployed steelworker had tried to grab
his gun.
</P>
<P>
   Green's sister, Treise Green, 40, said she was satisfied with
the verdict. She said ''that word 'guilty' was important,'' and
that Nevers ''should just go back to prison, even if it's 15
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Involuntary manslaughter is punishable by up to 15 years in
prison. The judge scheduled sentencing for May 16 and allowed
Nevers to remain free on bond. Fink said he would appeal on grounds
that jurors were improperly given the option of convicting Nevers
of involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Nevers and his partner, Walter Budzyn, were convicted
of second-degree murder. Budzyn was sentenced to eight to 18 years,
Nevers to 12 to 25 years. Their convictions were overturned five
months apart in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Budzyn's first conviction was overturned by the Michigan Supreme
Court, which ruled that his jury was unfairly influenced by being
shown ''Malcolm X'' -- a movie containing footage of the beating of
Rodney King by Los Angeles police -- during a break in
deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. District Court judge overturned Nevers' conviction in
late 1997, saying he was denied a fair trial. The judge cited the
''Malcolm X'' screening and the jury's exposure to media
speculation there could be rioting in Detroit if the white officers
were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Budzyn was retried and convicted in 1998 of involuntary
manslaughter and was freed after the judge sentenced him to time
already served.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
