<HEADLINE> Coke Boosts Sales but Posts 1Q Loss  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN BACHMAN, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- The Coca-Cola Co. posted a loss for the first
quarter but its results before onetime items beat analysts'
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The world's biggest soft drink company lost $58 million, or 2
cents per share, in the January-March period after writing down
$405 million in assets for its operations in India and a $275
million charge from its ongoing corporate realignment.
</P>
<P>
   But excluding one-time items, Coke earned 22 cents a share,
thanks in part to a 3.5 percent increase in worldwide sales. The
consensus forecast by analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson
Financial was 21 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Coke also said it took a 10-cent-per-share charge on inventory
reduction by its bottlers, resulting in operating earnings of 32
cents per share, though analysts did not incorporate the charge
into their estimates.
</P>
<P>
   In the same period last year, Coke earned $747 million, or 30
cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the quarter slipped to $4.39 billion from $4.40
billion a year ago but sales volume grew 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Coke's loss for the quarter stems from a number of changes the
company has been implementing.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company expects to cut 5,200 jobs from its
worldwide work force by the end of 2000, and spend $725 million
before taxes to cover costs of the job cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Coke began reducing the amount of concentrate it
ships to its bottlers to bring inventories more in line with
demand. Coke said it expects that process will shave 1 to 3 cents
per share from earnings in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Coke said volume growth of 3.5 percent exceeded its projections
of 3 percent because of strong demand for its products during the
last few weeks of the quarter. Sales volume of its core brands rose
2 percent, while products from Schweppes -- which Coke bought last
year -- added 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst said those numbers were not particularly
encouraging, given the company's ambitious projections for
long-term sales.
</P>
<P>
   ''In our opinion, volume remains light for them and we need to
see some pickup there,'' said Ann Gurkin of Davenport &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the company's new chairman and chief
executive, Douglas Daft, told investors that Coke expects 7 percent
to 8 percent annual growth in worldwide sales volume over the long
term.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have been skeptical that Coke can meet those sales
targets, with most predicting average volume growth of 5 percent or
less per year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think they can touch 7 to 8 percent periodically ... but as
an average of an annual growth number, it's not possible,'' said
Roy Burry, a longtime Coke analyst with Brown Brothers Harriman &AMP;
Co.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the asset writedown in India would be the last
to come from a review of all operations Daft ordered last year. In
January, Coke announced that it would write down $800 million in
assets from its underperforming operations in Russia and the Baltic
states.
</P>
<P>
   In late trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Coke shares were
down 87{ cents at $47.62{. The company released its quarterly
earnings a day before its annual shareholders meeting in
Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Coca-Cola Enterprises, the largest Coke bottler,
reported a loss of $35 million, or 8 cents per share, for the first
quarter. For the same period a year ago, the company reported a
loss of $62 million, or 15 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Coca-Cola Enterprises rose 68} cents to $21.93} on the
NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Coca-Cola, http://www.coke.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
