<HEADLINE> McGraw-Hill Earnings Nearly Double  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- First-quarter earnings at The McGraw-Hill Cos.
nearly doubled on increased advertising in Business Week magazine
and higher revenues from its Standard &AMP; Poor's financial services
division.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting a one-time gain from the sale of a business,
McGraw-Hill earned $47.4 million in the first quarter, or 24 cents
a share, easily eclipsing the 14 cents a share forecast by stock
analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   The news sent McGraw-Hill's stock sharply higher. Company's
shares rose $6.12{, or 14 percent, to $48.87{ in trading at 4:30
p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Including the gain from the sale of Tower Group International,
McGraw-Hill reported net earnings of $57.6 million, or 29 cents per
share.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues rose 12 percent to $802.5 million from $716.5 million
in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported a 32 percent increase in the number of
advertising pages in Business Week magazine, which like other
business publications has been enjoying a surge of new advertising
revenues as young companies spend heavily to establish brand names.
</P>
<P>
   Results at Standard &AMP; Poor's were also strong as the financial
services division expanded in Europe, Asia and Latin America. S&AMP;P,
which is best known in the United States for its bond ratings and
stock indices, has been developing new services overseas such as
rating bank loans and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   McGraw-Hill also reported higher revenues in its third main
business area, educational and professional publishing, but the
division still posted a net loss of $36.8 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
