<HEADLINE> Weyerhaeuser Earnings Jump in 1st Q  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FEDERAL WAY, Wash. (AP) -- Weyerhaeuser, the major paper and
forest products maker, reported sharply higher earnings of $244
million in the first quarter of the year as better market
conditions propelled sales.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings, which were equivalent of $1.04 per share, easily
beat analyst estimates of 92 cents per share as calculated by First
Call/Thompson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues jumped nearly 50 percent to $3.91 billion from $2.67
billion in the same period a year ago, largely due to the company's
acquisitions of MacMillan Bloedel and Trus Joist as well as better
markets for its products.
</P>
<P>
   In the same period a year ago, Weyerhaeuser earned $101 million,
or 51 cents a share, before an extraordinary loss on the sale of
the company's composite products business and an accounting charge
of $149 million.
</P>
<P>
   Including the one-time charges, the company reported a net loss
of $48 million, or 24 cents a share, in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Weyerhaeuser shares fell $1.50 to $53.50 in trading at 4:30 p.m.
Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
