<HEADLINE> Caterpiller Posts Higher 1Q Earns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ill. (AP) -- Caterpillar, the world's largest maker of
construction equipment, reported a 12 percent increase in
first-quarter earnings Tuesday as higher sales and a cost-cutting
program continued to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar earned $258 million, or 73 cents a share, in the
first three months of the year, up from $205 million, or 57 cents a
share, for the same period in 1999. Analysts surveyed by First
Call/Thomson Financial had expected earnings of 58 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue was $4.92 billion for the quarter, up from $4.87
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''They had a great quarter,'' said Joanna Shatney, an analyst
for Goldman, Sachs and Co. ''Great job on controlling costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Peoria-based company said it expects overall sales and
profit in 2000 to be higher than last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're focused on cost management, accelerating the financial
benefits from out acquisitions, reaching new breakthroughs in
product quality and becoming even more responsive,'' said chairman
and chief executive officer Glen Barton.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar is the world's biggest maker of earth-moving
machinery and a leading supplier of agricultural equipment. It has
manufacturing plants in 22 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar shares were priced at $40.25 at 5:15 p.m. EST on the
New York Stock Exchange, down 68} cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
