<HEADLINE> Mellon Reports Increase in Profits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Mellon Financial Corp. reported profits in the
first quarter rose almost 10 percent driven by a surge in trust and
investment fees as well as lower costs. The bank also announced an
increase in its dividend.
</P>
<P>
   Net income totaled $253 million, or 50 cents a share, topping
Wall Street's estimate by a penny. Mellon earned $231 million, or
43 cents a share, in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Trust and investment fee revenue rose 17 percent from the first
quarter of last year, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Mellon also said it would raise its dividend by 10 percent to 22
cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are also pleased to announce that for the first time, our
assets under management have exceeded $500 billion,'' Martin G.
McGuinn, chairman and chief executive officer, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Mellon's shares were priced at $32.50 at 5:15 p.m. EST on the
New York Stock Exchange, up $1.25 or 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fee revenue was $798 million in the first quarter of 2000,
basically flat with the year-ago period because Mellon sold several
businesses, including its credit card, network services and
mortgage banking units. Excluding those divestitures, fee revenue
was up 13 percent in the current quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Net-interest revenue was $351 million in the first quarter, down
5 percent from $371 million in the first quarter of 1999. Excluding
the effect of the divestitures of the credit card and mortgage
businesses, net-interest revenue increased 1 percent compared.
</P>
<P>
   Operating expenses totaled $719 million in the first quarter of
2000, down 6 percent from $760 million. Excluding the effect of
divestitures, expenses grew 9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
