<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maloney, Nielsen rematch drawing big donors  </HEADLINE>
By CAREN BENJAMIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Connecticut's fifth district congressional
race has become a key battleground in the fight for control of the
U.S. House of Representatives where Republicans currently have a
six-seat majority.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Democrat James Maloney beat Republican Mark
Nielsen by about 2,300 votes, the second closest contest in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating another tight race between the two, both national
parties have begun pumping money into this year's rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Election Commission reports available Tuesday show
Maloney with a slightly larger war chest than his opponent, but
political observers say the fundraising has just begun.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's going to be an outpouring of money in the district
like nobody in this part of Connecticut has ever seen before,''
said Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center for
Responsive Politics, which tracks money in campaigns. ''My advice
for everyone who lives there would be, 'buckle your seat belt and
get ready.'''
</P>
<P>
   Maloney now has $526,422 in his war chest compared to Nielsen's
$437,629. He also has substantially less debt.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Rob Simmons, a Republican trying to unseat U.S.
Rep. Sam Gejdenson in the second district, has less than half of
Nielsen's bankroll.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, a five-term state lawmaker running against a 10-term
incumbent, has $154,550 cash on hand. In the period that ended
March 31 he raised $73,919. Gejdenson has about $290,000 on hand,
and raised about $116,000 during the reporting period.
</P>
<P>
   About a quarter of the approximately $227,000 Nielsen raised
between January and March came in the form of donations from
Republican leadership PACs or gifts from the campaigns of
Republican congressmen already in safe seats.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Whip Thomas DeLay, R-Texas, gave Nielsen $5,000 from
his Americans for a Republican Majority PAC and California Reps.
John Doolittle, Buck McKeon and Christopher Cox, each gave Nielsen
$100,000 from their campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the ferocity of the battle for the House, Makinson
said this kind of sharing of the wealth will be strongly encouraged
by parties and can be seen in any number of House races.
</P>
<P>
   ''The national Republican party has made it clear that this is
one of their top targets and we are going to stand ready to help
Congressman Maloney in any way he wishes,'' said Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee spokesman John Del Cecato.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the National Republican Congressional Committee
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   More unusual is the fact that Nielsen, a former state senator,
raised $58,583 this period from business PACs. Among the most
generous was Philip Morris, which gave the $5,000 limit.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 10 percent of business PAC money in a given election
year goes to challengers, Makinson said. ''Businesses are not
really in the business of electing members of Congress. They are in
the business of lobbying. They like sure bets.''
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen campaign manager Fergus Cullen suggested business had a
clear reason for breaking the mold.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jim Maloney received more money for labor unions than any
other East Coast member and the business community has noticed
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney raised $121,665 this period from PACs including unions,
issue-oriented groups and the campaign funds of fellow Democrats
including Connecticut Sen. Christopher Dodd.
</P>
<P>
   Unions contributed heavily to Maloney in 1998 in large part
because his was one of the few competitive races in the northeast
that year, said campaign manager Jason Linde.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 1825 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000418.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smoking study shows preteens, teens still lighting up  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- About a quarter of New Jersey high-school
students smoke, while 10 percent of middle-school students are
lighting up, according to a study released Tuesday by the state
Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   That's progress.
</P>
<P>
   A state study released last year showed that 13 percent of
middle school students had used cigarettes in the month prior to
the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Another state study reported that about two-thirds of high
school students in 1998 said they smoke cigarettes. Half of those
reported only ''occasional use.''
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that some stores still sell tobacco to
minors, despite state laws outlawing it. More than one-third of
young smokers said they bought their cigarettes at convenience
stores or gas stations, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Most student smokers -- 37 percent -- bought their cigarettes in
convenience stores, while 25 percent bought them in gas stations.
The rest bummed them from someone else or had someone else buy
them, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Health Commissioner Christine Grant, appearing before the state
Assembly budget committee Tuesday, outlined a $30 million proposed
program to prevent kids from smoking and help smokers -- young and
old -- kick the habit.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've already funded programs that are reaching more than
20,000 New Jersey students in middle school, and the tobacco
settlement funds that Governor Whitman's providing will allow us to
expand this program dramatically across the state,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which is included in the proposed state budget,
includes an anti-smoking media campaign aimed at kids and teens,
smoking treatment programs for young people and adults and other
local efforts to reduce smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The money will also pay for an evaluation to see how well the
programs work, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The $30 million is part of the first installment of New Jersey's
$7.6 billion share of a multibillion dollar national settlement
with tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   The study on smokers was conducted by the University of Medicine
and Dentistry's School of Public Health. Researchers surveyed
16,000 students in 164 New Jersey middle and high schools.
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed that nearly 19 percent of students in
seventh and eighth grades and 39 percent of high schoolers use some
type of tobacco -- including cigarettes, cigars and chewing tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Black high school students were the least likely to use tobacco
at 34 percent, while white students had the highest rate of tobacco
use -- 43 percent. More than 35 percent of Hispanic high school
students used tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Students whose families or friends are smokers were twice as
likely to use cigarettes, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the young smokers said they'd like to quit,
but 43 percent of those wanting to quit said they didn't think they
could.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 1825 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000418.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diallo Parents Sue NYC for $81M  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The parents of Amadou Diallo on Tuesday sued the
city and the four policemen involved in their son's shooting death
for $81 million -- including $1 million for each of the 41 bullets
fired.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $40 million sought is for pain and suffering
endured since the Feb. 4, 1999 killing of their son. Nineteen of
the 41 shots struck the unarmed Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed by Diallo's mother, Kadiatou, and his father,
Saikou.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo, a West African immigrant, was shot as he stood in the
vestibule of his Bronx apartment building. The four white officers
in the Street Crime Unit testified at their jury trial they mistook
the wallet Diallo pulled out of his pocket for a gun.
</P>
<P>
   All four officers were acquitted of murder charges in February.
</P>
<P>
   The suit said that the four ''intentionally, wantonly,
recklessly and maliciously'' opened fired.
</P>
<P>
   It also claimed the shooting resulted from aggressive racial
profiling practices sanctioned by police.
</P>
<P>
   The city's lawyers did not immediately return calls for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
