<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Seeks Peace Accord Rescue  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Prime Minister Tony Blair met
with Northern Ireland political leaders and the Irish prime
minister on Tuesday in a new effort to salvage the province's
faltering peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not expect any breakthroughs in the complex
issues, but hoped to work out a plan that would lead to restoration
of powers to the Protestant-Catholic Cabinet suspended in February
because of a deadlock over Irish Republican Army weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there are possibilities, but I think it is important
that we don't raise people's expectations too highly before we know
what those expectations may be,'' Blair said after a series of
meetings in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there is a good will to see this thing through,'' he
said. ''There was an attitude by the parties in favor of the (1998
Good Friday peace) agreement that this is the only serious way
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The power-sharing Cabinet -- which included the largest
Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists, and members of the IRA's
political ally, Sinn Fein -- was the centerpiece of the accord and
was only 11 weeks old when its powers were lifted. The British
government decided on a suspension to prevent the complete collapse
of the administration should the Ulster Unionists carry out their
threat to withdraw over the IRA's failure to commit to disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   ''What the British and Irish governments now have to seriously
consider is what pressure can they bring to bear and how can they
do it,'' Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble said after his
meeting with Blair. ''They really do have to rethink their approach
to this and the business of always offering the republicans carrot
after carrot is in itself not going to work.
</P>
<P>
   John Hume, leader of Northern Ireland's main nationalist party,
the Social Democratic and Labor Party, said he put forward a plan
to break the impasse and that his meeting with Blair was ''very
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair met with Gerry Adams and Martin McGuinness, leaders of the
IRA-allied Sinn Fein party. Party chairman Mitchel McLaughlin said
his party sought a guarantee that, once the Catholic-Protestant
Cabinet was revived, Britain's top official in the province,
Northern Ireland Secretary Peter Mandelson, would have no power to
suspend it again.
</P>
<P>
   Blair later went to Dublin to brief Irish Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern on his meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Before Blair's arrival, Ahern said there were no differences of
opinion between the British and the Irish governments on
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not a question of what we would agree on, but whether we
can get it implemented. The two governments have a clear view, but
it is not much use if we cannot carry everybody else with us. We
are now seeing if we can get agreement from all the other
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair's London office later said he had had ''useful and
positive'' talks lasting more than two hours with Ahern and with
Irish government ministers and officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
