<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DreamWorks Takes Fund-Raising Break  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE DeARMOND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The surprising news that Hollywood's most
prominent Democratic fund-raisers plan a break from hosting the
glitzy affairs after November's election may be a sign the industry
is reaching its donor saturation point, political analysts said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Donors are getting tired of it. These are true-blue Democratic
donors. You just cannot keep saying 'yes' forever,'' said Larry
Makinson, director of the watchdog group the Center for Responsive
Politics. ''I think they may be the first, but they're not going to
be the last.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of the decision by Steven Spielberg, David Geffen and
Jeffrey Katzenberg, founders of DreamWorks SKG and three of the
Democrats' most reliable donors and party hosts, came as the trio
hosted a $2.8 million benefit for the Democratic National Committee
during the weekend visit of President Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Spahn, a spokesman for DreamWorks, downplayed the trio's
decision, saying the group also took a fund-raising break in 1997
after helping Clinton and other Democrats in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   He denied the decision was a sign the group has less support for
Gore than Clinton, pointing to the weekend fund-raiser as proof of
their commitment. Instead, he said the DreamWorks executives are
simply tired of fund-raising, but won't halt their efforts until
after Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every political candidate in the country from city council on
up to White House aspirants is likely to call us, write us, ask for
a meeting looking for support, looking for help,'' he said. ''It is
nonstop, it is year-round every year. It is a system run amok.''
</P>
<P>
   Spahn declined to say how long the break might last and whether
the executives will resume their current level of fund-raising. The
DreamWorks trio has helped raise about $15 million for Democratic
committees and candidates during the Clinton-Gore administration,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hollywood money race, Gore, the presumptive Democratic
presidential nominee, has outpaced GOP rival George W. Bush. In the
first nine months of last year, Hollywood donors gave Gore $642,865
compared to $488,327 for Bush, who's doing better than previous GOP
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts say donor fatigue started to set in for
Hollywood's contributors as campaigns set record fund-raising
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political analyst and senior
associate with the School of Politics and Economics, Claremont
Graduate University, said candidates, in the end, will get the
money they want.
</P>
<P>
   She predicted other donors will fill the void -- perhaps from
Silicon Valley. Gore, not as comfortable at star-studded Hollywood
events as Clinton, raised some $2.6 million from the high-tech
industry on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like nature, political money abhors a vacuum. Someone, some
group will step in,'' Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   The news comes at a time when Democrats have become financially
competitive with Republicans. During the first three months of
2000, the Democratic National Committee reported raising $26
million while the Republican National Committee said it raised $24
million. Both parties reported having around $18 million in the
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, House Democrats reported having more money in the
bank than their GOP counterparts as of March 31. The Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee said it raised $28.6 million on
hand, while the National Republican Congressional Committee said it
had had $18.2 million. During the first three months of the year,
the NRCC reported raising $20 million to $12.3 million for the
DCCC.
</P>
<P>
   Republican donors have indicated that they, too, are suffering
from donor fatigue in some cases, and some corporate executives
have announced their support for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Spahn said the DreamWorks executives don't blame the candidates
for the system that has made heavy fund-raising a necessity for
candidates and noted the trio supports Gore's interest in campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Harshbarger, president of Common Cause, said he'd like to
see celebrities like Geffen, Katzenberg and Spielberg turn their
energies to campaign finance reform instead of taking a break
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are hopeful that this year will -- because of the amounts
involved -- finally will get people to realize the current system is
not good for democracy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
