<HEADLINE> Scott Smith files appeal claiming juror misconduct  </HEADLINE>
sdtvpr
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- New Milford police officer Scott Smith,
convicted of manslaughter for killing an unarmed suspect, on
Tuesday asked a judge to overturn that conviction because of
alleged juror misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   In his motion, Smith's attorney, John Kelly, cited nine
instances of alleged juror misconduct during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, he said some jurors pressed others not to
rehear Smith's testimony and a juror nicknamed ''Rambo'' improperly
displayed a sheriff's badge and pressed for conviction, urging that
the other jurors follow his lead because he was experienced in law
enforcement matters.
</P>
<P>
   Some jurors have also claimed that another member of the panel
cited his military experience in the Marines and discussed court
martials and soldiers who had been charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   A juror also has reportedly admitted driving by the crime scene
and discussing the case with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Litchfield Superior Court Judge Charles D. Gill could grant
Smith a new trial, or rule that the alleged statements were proper
in the context of heated deliberations. Waterbury State's Attorney
John Connelly, who prosecuted Smith, said he was confident the
conviction would stand.
</P>
<P>
   During his trial, Smith claimed self defense, saying he shot
Franklyn Reid because he thought Reid was going for a weapon.
Witnesses said it appeared that Reid had surrendered and was
offering no resistance when he was shot in the back at point-blank
range.
</P>
<P>
   Smith originally was charged with murder following the December
1998 shooting but was convicted of manslaughter. He is scheduled to
be sentenced on May 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
