<HEADLINE> RI Officers Cleared in Cop's Death  </HEADLINE>
By GILLIAN FLYNN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Two white policemen who fatally shot an
off-duty black officer they mistook for a suspect were cleared
Tuesday of criminal wrongdoing by a state grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The January shooting death of 29-year-old Sgt. Cornel Young Jr.
sparked protests, accusations that the Providence police were
racist and led to a federal civil rights inquiry that remains
ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury spent about two months reviewing the conduct of
Officers Michael Solitro and Carlos Saraiva and Young's death.
</P>
<P>
   ''I call on all communities in Rhode Island whatever their
opinions about today's announcements to be calm, to be responsible
and to continue to fight in appropriate channels,'' said Attorney
General Sheldon Whitehouse, criticized by some community leaders
for his handling of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Young's mother, Leisa Young, said she was angry she had to learn
of the ruling from reporters. Bill Fischer, a Whitehouse aide, said
the attorney general had left messages at her home and work but
could not reach her before he held a news conference to announce
the grand jury's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''How much trust am I supposed to put in the fact that they're
going to do anything else?'' Leisa Young said, as she left a
meeting with ministers at the Allen A.M.E. church.
</P>
<P>
   Solitro, 33, and Saraiva, 30, were responding to a fight outside
a Providence restaurant Jan. 28, when Young, in street clothes, saw
the confrontation, drew his gun and rushed outside to help the
officers. Solitro and Saraiva said they repeatedly told Young to
drop the weapon but he did not comply and they shot him.
</P>
<P>
   The police union insisted Young's shooting was a case of a bad
split-second decision, not prejudice. It issued a statement Tuesday
saying members were saddened that some community leaders were using
the tragedy to further their own agendas ''with disregard of the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Joseph Pezza, the attorney for Solitro, who had been on
the patrol for seven nights when he shot Young, said the officer
was relieved and hoped soon to return to work. ''He was very
emotional,'' Pezza said. ''He hoped the truth would come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Joseph F. Penza Jr. said Saraiva was torn over whether
he should return to work.
</P>
<P>
   ''In his own mind, the actions he took were justified,'' Penza
said. ''But only he knows if he can go back and do his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Martin Hames, a police spokesman, said both men had been on
leave from the department and administrators would determine when
they could return to active duty.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights leaders held a series of protests, rallies and
prayer meetings, demanding someone with no ties to Rhode Island
enforcement investigate the case. Whitehouse refused, saying it was
his responsibility as the state's top prosecutor to lead the
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Theodore Wilson, among those pushing for an independent
prosecutor, said he was not surprised by the grand jury decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''From the onset this process was tainted and whatever came out,
wasn't worth the piece of paper it was written on,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., asked the Congressional Black
Caucus to examine the case. Kennedy planned to meet with civil
rights leaders Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehouse said he decided not to pursue a felony murder count
police had filed against Aldrin Diaz, who waved a gun in the
confrontation that ended in Young's death. The state grand jury on
Tuesday indicted Diaz on weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz's lawyers said their client was a scapegoat for police
misconduct.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
