<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyers say van driver admits possible error before troopers openedfire  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The driver of a van carrying four
minorities admitted he may have stepped on the accelerator,
prompting two state troopers to open fire in a case that set off a
firestorm over racial profiling in New Jersey, a defense lawyer
contends.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Robert Galantucci maintains that instead of attempted
murder, the gunshots fired that night on the New Jersey Turnpike
were a justifiable police shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our law doesn't expect people to be perfect. It expects them
to be reasonable,'' Galantucci said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And Trooper John Hogan, 29, of Florence, was reasonable when he
and Trooper James Kenna fired on the van, wounding three of the
four young men inside. The troopers acted in self defense, thinking
that the van was backing up to hit them, Galantucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Public outcry after the shooting led to widespread allegations
of racial profiling by state troopers and a severely critical
report by the Attorney General's Office detailing the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ''The key point in this case is the perception of the state
troopers, not the perception of those young men,'' Galantucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Galantucci asked a state Superior Court judge on Monday to
dismiss the attempted murder indictments in part because the
prosecutor acted improperly, he maintains. Jack Arsenault, the
lawyer for Kenna, 28, of Hamilton Square, plans to file a similar
motion.
</P>
<P>
   In his grand jury testimony, driver Keshon Moore, 24, of New
York, admitted that he felt like he started the incident, according
to a lengthy legal brief filed by Galantucci.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't blame anybody but myself. It was a mistake,'' Moore
told the grand jury, according to Galantucci's brief.
</P>
<P>
   Moore also told the panel that he was driving with a suspended
license and he ''probably hit the accelerator'' as he jumped into
the back seat. The driver possibly became nervous as he tried to
hand the wheel over to a passenger, Danny Reyes, the motion
alleges.
</P>
<P>
   The troopers pulled the van over on the turnpike the night of
April 23, 1998. Moore's three passengers were wounded when Hogan
and Kenna fired 11 shots into the van. Moore was not injured.
</P>
<P>
   The troopers have said they fired in self-defense because the
van began backing up toward them as they approached it on foot
after stopping it for speeding.
</P>
<P>
   The troopers are white; Moore and his passengers are minorities.
Hogan and Kenna, who have pleaded innocent in the shooting, have
been suspended without pay, pending the outcome of their case. They
are charged with attempted murder and aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Lennon, president of the State Troopers Fraternal Association
of New Jersey, says the information contained in the court papers
vindicates what troopers have been saying since the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a series of mistakes that day and the first one was
made by the driver,'' Lennon said.
</P>
<P>
   If the van headed backward at the troopers, that is a criminal
act and the troopers are required to take action, not shrink away,
Lennon said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that at last it shows the troopers were acting in self
defense and in my opinion it basically exonerates them,'' Lennon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Galantucci said this motion was filed first because it requires
the judge to analyze ''thousands of pages'' of grand jury
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Special Prosecutor James J. Gerrow is scheduled to file a
response next month and arguments are planned for June 27 before
state Superior Court Judge Andrew J. Smithson. Gerrow said Tuesday
''it would be inappropriate to comment'' and would respond to all
issues in his motion.
</P>
<P>
   In his motion Galantucci alleges that grand jurors were
influenced by reports of racial profiling by police when they
should have considered only the law regarding proper use of deadly
force by law enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the nine-month investigation, grand jurors had
been ''primed to find'' evidence that the shooting was racially
motivated, Galantucci alleges. And grand jurors were not admonished
that racial profiling, the practice of police targeting minorities,
was not a case issue before them.
</P>
<P>
   Also tainting the grand jury was an indictment alleging that
Kenna and Hogan falsified their traffic logs -- a tactic officials
maintain was an attempt to disguise the race of motorists they
stopped, the motion says. That should have remained sealed until
after the grand jury completed its work on the turnpike shooting,
he contends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
