<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Challenges Finance Leaders  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan challenged
world financial leaders Tuesday to listen to demonstrators who
protested in Washington against world poverty and the exclusion of
many poor nations from the benefits of new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Annan's audience included many finance ministers fresh from the
tumultuous meetings of the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund, which protesters tried to disrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to turn this unease, this ferment, this
confrontational energy, into something constructive -- into
something that benefits all the people and which all the people can
support,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Annan's remarks were made at a joint meeting of the U.N.
Economic and Social Council and the two global financial
institutions that met in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In a report earlier this month on the challenges facing the
world in the 21st century, Annan called for an all-out effort to
lift more than 1 billion people out of extreme poverty by 2015, an
appeal he reiterated Tuesday to the controllers of government purse
strings.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when some people have reaped enormous benefits from
new technology, Annan said, it is ''shameful and unacceptable that
another part -- and by most reckonings the larger part -- remains
excluded ... subjected to a life of grinding poverty often
accompanied by malnutrition and disease.''
</P>
<P>
   With minimal investment in basic education, Annan argued,
billions of poor people can leapfrog into the world of instant
communications and become part of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   At the Washington meetings, ministers and bankers renewed
pledges to hasten debt relief for the poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   The international community has launched the Highly Indebted
Poor Countries (HIPC) initiative to reduce the debt burden of
countries that are pursuing reasonable economic policies as well as
managing their future debt. But Cuba complained that only four of
the 33 poorest countries were going through the process.
</P>
<P>
   World Bank Managing Director Sven Sandstrom said $2.4 billion
has so far been pledged to the HIPC trust fund but ''this is only a
fraction of what is going to be needed in the years ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   IMF Acting Managing Director Stanley Fischer noted that the IMF
has not received permission to sell gold to help finance the fund,
that regional development banks don't have money to contribute, and
that many pledges have not been paid.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria's Finance Minister Jubril Martin Kuye said many
middle-income countries were becoming increasingly indebted and
suggested that the international community should consider
extending debt relief to them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
