<HEADLINE> Gore To Unveil Water Heater Measure  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore is proposing a
requirement for more energy-efficient water heaters -- the latest in
a string of environmental miniannouncements from Gore's office
aimed getting a jump on Earth Day this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After announcing a plan to protect drinking water earlier in the
week, Gore will propose efficiency standards Wednesday for
residential water heaters with an aim toward ameliorating
atmospheric climate change.
</P>
<P>
   The final water heater standard, if finished this year, would go
into effect in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ''These new standards will help save consumers money on energy
bills and reduce greenhouse gases and other pollution,'' Gore says
in a draft announcement obtained Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Timing of the announcement took by surprise some people at the
Energy Department, where the standards are being developed. The
standards, which will apply to all new residential water heaters,
are not scheduled for publication in the Federal Register until
April 28.
</P>
<P>
   Gore says the more efficient water heaters will reduce
greenhouse gas emissions over the next 20 years by 36 million
metric tons, equivalent to taking 28 million cars off the road, and
help curtail the prospects of global warming.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president notes that Americans spend $20 billion a year
to heat water, which accounts for 14 percent of household energy
requirements. Over the typical 12-year life of a water heater, the
average consumer would save about $100 with the more efficient
model, the vice president's office estimates.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gore announced the Environmental Protection Agency
was proposing new requirements on 157,000 water systems that get
water from public wells so as to reduce risks from bacteria and
parasites.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's corner on the environmental market was challenged last
week by his Republican presidential rival George W. Bush, who
revealed a plan to expedite cleanup of abandoned industrial sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency, under Carol Browner, a
close Gore confidant, also has put high priority on cleaning up
so-called ''brownfield'' industrial areas that are contaminated by
past pollution but with modest cleanup could be returned safely to
limited commercial uses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
