<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Works on Consistency Strategy  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sounding almost like a Democrat, Republican
George W. Bush unveils an education agenda one day,
headline-grabbing health care and environmental initiatives the
next, an affordable-housing plan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Where's Al Gore?
</P>
<P>
   It may seem as if the real Democrat in the presidential race is
taking a nap during this springtime lull in the campaign. But after
one splashy misstep in the Elian Gonzalez storm, the vice
president, who put his policy proposals on the table months ago, is
executing a low-watt strategy to gain consistency for his message,
cash for his party, and a homespun shine to his public image.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides know he makes no front pages with the ''School Days''
he's begun conducting in battleground states like Michigan. There,
he talked education policy until midnight over teacher Claudia
Amboyer's chocolate cake before tucking himself into her son's
bedroom and immersing himself the next day in her eight-hour school
routine.
</P>
<P>
   But local communities eat up these vignettes, Gore spokesman
Chris Lehane said. And the campaign sees them as a way -- much like
Gore's exhaustive open meetings in Iowa and New Hampshire -- to undo
perceptions of him as detached and a Washington insider.
</P>
<P>
   ''The lesson from Iowa and New Hampshire, where Al Gore spent a
great deal of time, was that people liked him more the more they
saw him and heard him,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the sense that Gore is running under the radar is his
determination to let the Gonzalez furor pass.
</P>
<P>
   After first insisting that the Cuban boy's custody would be
''settled'' if his father came to the United States to state his
wishes, Gore endorsed legislation to give the family residency -- a
move criticized by Republicans and some outraged Democrats as
pandering to Florida's Cuban-American community.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign finance reform package sparked derisive agreement
by some with his own line about being ''an imperfect messenger''
because of allegations about his 1996 campaign fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, Gore's evolving stands on Elian and campaign
reform resurrected a key vulnerability -- inconsistency. Already,
his record on abortion and gun control as a congressman from
Tennessee has been criticized as filled with flip-flops. More
recently, the issues were gays in the military and investing Social
Security funds in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's generally hard to know what Al Gore believes in on any
given day,'' said Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Gore's Lehane called Bush's initiatives
effort ''the Seinfeld of campaigns -- a campaign about nothing
beyond his irresponsible tax cuts and embracing of Bob Jones
University.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's obviously now trying to find policy Band-Aids to cover up
the fact that he has very little depth on these policy issues,''
Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's schedule these days is dominated by almost daily fund
raising -- with severely restricted press coverage -- for the
Democratic National Committee, which out-raised the Republican
Party by $2 million for the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   In a single stop in California's Silicon Valley last week, Gore
picked up a record $2.6 million. His five-day total the week before
was $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, fund raising for the Republican National Committee
is on Bush's back burner while he tries to replenish the $60
million he's already emptied from his own coffers. He's also
playing catch-up in the policy game.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer rejected the notion that Bush's policy push is
belated.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are going to be scores of issues and we have a
deliberate plan to address them. But if you address everything a
year before the election, what's left?''
</P>
<P>
   Initiatives on the family, government waste and trade are still
to come, Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's nomination battle with Bill Bradley last year forced him
to the table early with health care, education, Medicare, tax,
child care and anti-hunger proposals. On the Republican side, Bush
sketched ideas for charitable institutions and defense spending and
outlined education reforms, but tax cuts made up the core of his
policy agenda before now.
</P>
<P>
   ''They sprinkled around some policy initiatives that they
thought would energize their base, particularly their conservative
base,'' said Republican strategist Greg Mueller, a former adviser
to Steve Forbes, who ran against Bush for the GOP nomination but
has since endorsed him.
</P>
<P>
   After a primary season that saw Bush listing rightward and
courting religious conservatives, Mueller said Bush is ''now coming
back with issues, particularly education and health care, which
play very well with Hispanic and suburban-women swing voters.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Bush has proposed nearly $60 billion in new
spending on signature Democratic issues: childhood literacy, health
care for the poor, low-income housing and environmental cleanup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-18-00 1933 </TRAILER>
