<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Collins asks high court to clarify school construction order  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- In an unusual move, Assembly Speaker Jack
Collins filed a motion Tuesday asking the state Supreme Court to
settle the nagging question of whether the state must pay the full
cost of school construction in poor districts.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins also said that, no matter what the high court does,
his request would not further delay long-awaited legislation to
create the statewide school construction program.
</P>
<P>
   He promised that a bill would be in place by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuver is the latest in the ongoing struggle over how to
fund the program, which is estimated to cost between $11 billion
and $13 billion and would make building funds available to all New
Jersey districts.
</P>
<P>
   In question is a 1998 state Supreme Court decision that most --
including the governor and Senate president -- interpret as ordering
the state to fully fund construction costs in 30 of New Jersey's
poorest districts.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins, R-Salem, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   He said the constitution -- and previous court decisions -- give
the Legislature the right to decide how to fund education needs.
That funding formula, the speaker argues, can include requiring
local districts to ante up their share.
</P>
<P>
   Collins wants to know whether the court decision prohibits the
state from compelling these poor districts to pay what they can
afford, as long as the state fully funds all ''constitutionally
necessary construction.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins has proposed fully funding emergency repairs and new
classroom space to relieve overcrowding. State money for ''extras''
such as cafeterias and media rooms would be provided on a sliding
scale, depending on a district's ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Debate on the school construction legislation has dragged on for
months, with major differences separating competing versions backed
by Collins and Senate President Donald DiFrancesco.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman and DiFrancesco say the court's 1998
landmark Abbott vs. Burke ruling compels the state to pay the full
fare for repairing and replacing crumbling buildings in the special
needs districts.
</P>
<P>
   The court set a spring deadline for that construction to begin.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is scheduled to meet May 18 to consider the school
construction bill. The Assembly plans to meet on May 22 and 25 and
could consider the bill during those sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Collins has no right to ask for court intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court's language is crystal clear that the state would
fully fund facilities improvement in the Abbott districts because
of their dire fiscal circumstances,'' said David Sciarra, director
of the Education Law Center, which represents poor children in the
30-year-old school funding fight.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is entirely inappropriate for the speaker to ask for the
court's advice on how he should deal with pending legislation,
especially when the court has issued an unequivocal mandate,''
Sciarra added.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Askin, a Rutgers law professor, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know where the Assembly speaker has any authority at
all to seek that kind of clarification,'' said Askin. ''He's not a
party to the case. It's a political statement of some kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins plans to run for governor next year and some say he is
using the school construction issue to distinguish himself from
DiFrancesco, the other likely Republican candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Collins scoffs at that suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   He says it's his right -- and duty -- to question whether state
taxpayers should be forced to pay for construction in these 30
districts, especially since some of the districts are now in better
fiscal shape than some ''non-Abbott'' districts.
</P>
<P>
   Hoboken, for example, has become richer in the years that the
lawsuit has winded through the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Collins is specifically asking for clarification of the
following clause in the Supreme Court's 1998 ruling:
</P>
<P>
   ''We conclude that any funding formula that does not fund the
complete cost of remediating the infrastructure and life cycle
deficiencies that have been identified in the Abbott districts or
that does not fully fund the construction of any new classrooms
needed to correct capacity deficiencies will not comport with the
State's constitutional mandate to provide facilities adequate to
ensure a thorough and efficient education.''
</P>
<P>
   Winnie Comfort, spokeswoman for the state Judiciary, said the
state and Education Law Center have 10 days to respond and then the
high court will consider the matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
