<HEADLINE> Chicago Janitors Go on Strike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Hundreds of janitors at suburban office buildings
went on strike Tuesday, hours after their striking counterparts
downtown reached a settlement agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In separate talks Tuesday, negotiators for the Service Employees
International Union and the Suburban Contractors Association met
with a federal mediator to discuss contracts for the suburban
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are still extremely far apart,'' said Barry White, a
negotiator for the contractors. He said plans were in place to
provide the necessary services in the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Union spokesman Ken Munz said about 500 of the union's 4,500
suburban janitors went on strike. Others were to report for work as
usual, but would gradually be asked to strike if no settlement was
reached, he said.
</P>
<P>
   No new negotiations were scheduled. The janitors' contract
expired April 9.
</P>
<P>
   The contract for downtown janitors was reached Monday night
after 5,500 SEIU members spent the day picketing outside downtown
offices. Their agreement with the Building Owners and Managers
Association calls for a pay increase of 45 cents in the first year
to $11.85 an hour, with increases of 35 cents and 30 cents in
subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a very good settlement,'' Munz said. ''It's the best we
have seen in a decade.''
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, thousands of commercial building janitors are on
strike, seeking wage increases and benefits. Union officials say
similar labor unrest could soon occur in other cities, including
New York, Cleveland, Detroit and Philadelphia, where union
contracts are due to expire this year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: SEIU: http://www.seiu.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
