<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Japan Banks Near Merger Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd. and Mitsubishi
Trust and Banking Corp. have agreed to set up a joint holding
company in April of next year, published reports said.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance would create the world's fifth-largest financial
group, with $837 billion in deposits and other assets, the Nihon
Keizai financial newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   The two banks were to officially announce their planned alliance
Wednesday, according to reports by the Nihon Keizai and the
nationally circulated Asahi, Yomiuri and Mainichi newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the two banks were not available for comment early
Wednesday. On Tuesday, both banks refused to discuss the reported
alliance, saying only that talks were in progress and nothing had
been decided.
</P>
<P>
   The Nihon Keizai said the two banks would integrate their
operations under a joint holding company to be established next
April. The firm would manage $433 billion in pension and other
trusts.
</P>
<P>
   The firm would be a publicly-traded company, with shares listed
on both the Tokyo Stock Exchange and the New York Stock Exchange,
the Nihon Keizai report said.
</P>
<P>
   Trust operations will be integrated by merging two
BOT-Mitsubishi subsidiaries -- Nippon Trust Bank and Tokyo Trust
Bank -- with Mitsubishi Trust.
</P>
<P>
   The merger of three trust banks will be completed by October,
2001, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   The banks involved hope the move will enable them to compete
against other planned megagroups in the financial industry, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese banks have been consolidating their operations to
recover from billions of dollars in bad loans made in the
speculative lending boom of the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest of these mergers is the Mizuho Financial Group,
which announced in August that it was creating an institution with
$1.3 trillion in assets by merging Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, Fuji Bank,
and the Industrial Bank of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Sanwa Bank, Tokai Bank and Asahi Bank also plan to
merge, creating the country's second-largest bank with $1 trillion
in assets.
</P>
<P>
   BOT-Mitsubishi and Mitsubishi Trust will initially continue
current operations under the joint holding company.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they will merge overlapping operations and
concentrate on their individual strengths, the Nikkei said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-18-00 2017 </TRAILER>
