<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tuesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
Taber Students Honor School Shooting
</P>
<P>
   TABER, Alberta (AP) -- Hundreds of students at W.R. Myers high
school packed into their gymnasium Tuesday to mark the coming
anniversary of a fatal shooting of one of their own a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   For many, it was a tribute to Jason Lang, a 17-year-old
basketball and soccer player who was shot dead in the school hall.
For others it was a day to contemplate how their lives were
dramatically changed when a teen-ager walked into the school and
opened fire, killing Lang and wounding another student.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting happened April 28, eight days after two youths at a
high school in Littleton, Colo., shot and killed 13 people, then
turned the guns on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of the accused boy in Taber has said he was harassed
and bullied at school and became obsessed with the Colorado
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   With a theme of ''Hope, Remember and Challenge,'' Myers
students, teachers and parents gathered to sing songs, pray and
listen to a speech by Rev. Dale Lang, Jason's father. The service
was held 10 days early because the anniversary falls during the
school's Easter break.
</P>
<P>
   The accused youth, now 15, is awaiting trial on first-degree
murder and two charges of attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Coroner: Towns Ill-Equipped for Disasters
</P>
<P>
   KANGIQSUALUJJUAQ, Quebec (AP) -- Northern Quebec communities are
ill-equipped to deal with disasters a year after an avalanche
killed nine Inuit, a coroner said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Four adults and five children -- the youngest 15 months old --
were killed when the avalanche struck the town's school gym on Jan.
1, 1999. Twenty-five people were injured.
</P>
<P>
   ''When the municipality of Kangiqsualujjuaq sent out a call for
help, no one in (nearby) Kuujjuaq had an emergency plan,'' Jacques
Berube noted in his report.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hospital had an emergency plan designed to deal with
airplane crashes. I noted that a number of senior officials working
at the hospital did not know that this plan existed and did not
know how to implement it.''
</P>
<P>
   Disaster plans, along with more fire trucks, emergency phone
lines, increased training for medical and emergency response teams,
more medical equipment are among his suggestions for the provincial
government.
</P>
<P>
   The avalanche was caused by weather conditions, Berube's report
stated. A ledge overloaded with snow gave way, sending powdery
death cascading down the hill.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Bernardo's Lawyer: Homolka Lied
</P>
<P>
   ST. CATHARINES, Ontario (AP) -- Sex-killer Paul Bernardo's lawyer
was poised in 1994 to snare Karla Homolka in a damning lie that
would scuttle the infamous plea-bargain deal that gave her just 12
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   As friends and family teetered on every word, Ken Murray
described in court Tuesday how he was going to use Homolka's own
statements to drag her back into a case he believed she had
skillfully evaded.
</P>
<P>
   When she made her deal with the Crown in March 1993, Homolka
said nothing about Jane Doe, the anonymous fourth victim of the
notorious couple's lengthy spree of sex and brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before the deal was sealed, the Crown showed Homolka a
snippet of videotape depicting her drugging and performing sexual
acts on an unidentified girl.
</P>
<P>
   Homolka, who was claiming she herself was a victim of her
sexually sadistic husband, suggested the girl was one of three
teen-age victims known to police.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray, having viewed the six videotapes depicting the rape
and torture of teens Leslie Mahaffy, Kristen French, Homolka's
sister Tammy and Jane Doe, knew better.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was Karla with a recumbent Jane Doe,'' said Murray, who is
testifying in his own defense against charges of obstructing
justice for holding on to the tapes for 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The tape) shows her in control,'' he said. ''It shows her
performing sexual activities on her unconscious victim. It shows
her as enjoying it.
</P>
<P>
   ''If she was caught lying about anything, or was found to have
committed other offenses prior to her deal, the deal was off . . .
she wasn't bargaining in good faith.''
</P>
</TEXT>
