<DOCNO> APW20000418.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Rep. Defends Iraq Sanctions  </HEADLINE>
By JASSIM MOHAMMED, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASRA, Iraq (AP) -- A visiting U.S. congressman Tuesday defended
U.N. economic sanctions on Iraq, but said there is no reason why
''innocent people'' suffering under them should not be given
humanitarian help.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Tony Hall, a Democrat from Ohio, is in Iraq on a
four-day visit to investigate the plight of Iraqi people under
sanctions aimed at forcing the government of Iraq to give up its
weapons of mass destruction. The sanctions were imposed after
Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a very difficult country and we had difficult times in
the past 10 years. I think there is no question ... there is a
major health problem here,'' Hall told The Associated Press
Television News.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq blames the sanctions for the deaths of 1.2 million people,
including 750,000 children under the age of five, because of
scarcity of food and medicine. But the United States says President
Saddam Hussein's government must shoulder the blame for not
allowing U.N. weapons inspectors to finish their job of eliminating
illegal weapons that would lead to the lifting of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sanctions ... sometimes can hit the most innocent people,''
Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   But ''you must remember why sanctions were put on this country
and why U.N. (was) very concerned about weapons of mass destruction
being exported and that is the main reason for the sanctions,''
Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But having said that, it does not mean that the innocent
people here, the children, women and old people, cannot be helped
in humanitarian sense and that's what I am hoping that we can do,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall visited a water sanitation project in Basra, 281 miles
south of the Iraqi capital, Baghdad. He also visited hospitals in
three other southern cities, Babylon, Samawah and Nasiriyah, on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At Babylon's Maternity and Children Hospital, which had no
electricity, many beds were shared by two children because of
overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   Hall went up to Fatima Ali, standing next to her 2-year-old
daughter's bed. ''My daughter is dying,'' she said in Arabic. Hall
did not understand the words but replied: ''I will help.''
</P>
<P>
   In another bed, Mohammed Farhan, less than two months old, was
being treated for malnutrition and diarrhea. Hospital chief, Dr.
Ahmed Diab, said the infant needs 12 boxes of milk every month but
the hospital can give him only eight.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have seen a number of malnourished children and they need a
lot of care. There is a lot of humanitarian goods that could come
here and they are not coming through for some reasons. Maybe I can
help on that,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall also visited the city of Ur, believed to be the birthplace
of the biblical patriarch, Abraham.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
