<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal investigators release findings of autism cluster probe  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRICK, N.J. (AP) -- A federal investigation of a possible autism
cluster here found the worried parents who pushed for the study
were right: The neurodevelopmental disorder is far more common -- at
least here -- than once thought.
</P>
<P>
   The parents did get some good news, though. A second arm of the
study could find no contamination in the water that Brick residents
have been swimming in and drinking that could be linked to the
autism cases here.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very satisfied,'' said Brick resident Bob Lanzieri, whose
6 1/2-year-old son J.T. is autistic. ''I appreciate the study
immensely for (showing) that we have a higher rate of autistic
people than we thought ... and we need to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the most intensive federal study of autism prevalence ever
conducted, researchers said Tuesday that they found a rate of 4 in
1,000 children with autism and another 2.7 in 1,000 with similar,
but less severe autism-like disorders.
</P>
<P>
   The 6.7-in-1,000 rate is several times higher than past
estimates, although the true rate of autism is controversial
because there has never been a nationwide study.
</P>
<P>
   ''The major question for me is whether it's just more prevalent
(than previously thought) or it's on the rise,'' as some parents
and doctors suspect, said Dr. Eric London, vice president of
medical affairs at the National Alliance for Autism Research in
Princeton and a consultant for the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A poorly understood disorder, autism is thought to occur early
in pregnancy. In moderate to severe cases, autism makes it
difficult to communicate or relate to the outside world, and drives
some to obsessively repeat certain motions, even hurt themselves or
others; in mild cases, it triggers behavioral problems.
</P>
<P>
   Until the early 1990s, autism was thought to afflict 1 in 2,000
children, but some recent studies in foreign countries found rates
of 3-6 in 1,000. Preliminary data from a federal study of children
in Atlanta show a rate of 2-3 in 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, data from California, South Florida and other areas
show a sharp increase in recent years in children getting special
educational services for autism, and parents in Staten Island,
N.Y., and other communities have complained of possible autism
clusters. None has been documented so far, even here.
</P>
<P>
   A group of worried Brick parents conducted a survey in late 1997
that found a high enough level of autism in this coastal town about
60 miles north of Atlantic City that state health officials and
politicians won federal funding for a comprehensive investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1999, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
and the Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry began
related investigations, with the CDC team focusing on autism
incidence and the ATSDR team looking at whether the disorder could
be caused by environmental toxins suspected by the parents.
</P>
<P>
   After an exhaustive search for possible autism cases, the CDC
team studied 75 children ages 3 to 10. Of those, 36 children were
determined to have autism and another 24 had autism-related
disorders, said Jacquelyn Bertrand, a developmental psychologist at
the CDC. Twice as many boys as girls were autistic, 63 percent of
the 60 children also were mentally retarded, and seven families had
two children with autism.
</P>
<P>
   She said this study will be a model for new CDC studies on the
incidence of autism in other communities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this (study) is going to bring more and more attention
to autism and the fact that it's not a rare disorder, that we need
more attention to diagnosis,'' so affected children can get
treatment earlier and reach a higher level of function, said Dr.
Audrey Mars, an assistant pediatrics professor at the University of
Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey who examined many of the
children.
</P>
<P>
   The ATSDR team combed data on chemicals in the municipal water
supply dating to 1987, focusing on three chemicals found at high
enough levels to cause concern, said Robert Knowles, an
environmental scientist with the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Two of them, TCE and PCE, were found in two now-closed municipal
wells. Both were either undetectable or at levels considered safe
by the time that water, highly diluted with water from the
Metedeconk River running through Brick, reached homes or
businesses. A third group of chemicals that are a byproduct of
water chlorination, trihalomethanes, occasionally exceeded safe
levels, but never when coinciding with pregnancies resulting in
autistic children.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles said the researchers also determined that swimming in
the river was safe, and that while the Brick Township Landfill, a
Superfund site closed in 1979, is leaking contaminants into
groundwater, none of it reaches the drinking supply. About 70
percent of Brick's drinking water comes from the river.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a father who led the fight for the study said he's not
convinced that there's no environmental cause for the autism cases
here or the apparent increase around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm slightly disappointed that (the federal experts) aren't
staying in town long enough to answer the questions in the
community this is going to provoke,'' added Billy Gallagher, a
commercial fisherman with two autistic children, Alanna, 9, and
Austin, 7.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Smith, R-Robbinsville, praised the thoroughness
of the study. He expects a vote in early May on his bill to provide
$37 million for research of autism and other developmental
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ''Brick becomes the springboard for a nationwide effort,'' Smith
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   London agreed, and noted that his group has increased its
funding for research on autism's prevalence, cause and possible
cures. Meanwhile, the state is receiving $1.5 million from the CDC
to study autism and develop programs to teach medical personnel how
to identify the complex disorder.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: CDC investigation report,
http://www.cdc.gov/nceh/programs/cddh/dd/brick.htm
</P>
<P>
   National Alliance for Autism Research: http://www.naar.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 2122 </TRAILER>
