<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Welcomes Israel's Pullout  </HEADLINE>
By HUSSEIN DAKROUB, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Lebanon signaled Tuesday its possible
acceptance of Israel's planned withdrawal from southern Lebanon,
after weeks of expressing suspicion over Israeli intentions to end
its 18-year occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss declared the planned
withdrawal ''a resounding victory for Lebanon and its heroic
resistance'' and a ''crushing defeat'' of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the first time in the history of the Arab-Israeli
conflict, Israel is forced to withdraw from an Arab territory,''
Hoss said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But in a departure from previous statements, Hoss did not
criticize Israeli intentions or mention conditions for a withdrawal
-- a sign that Lebanon may be willing to accept the pullback as an
inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon frequently called for an unconditional and full Israeli
withdrawal from the occupied border zone. But it has viewed with
outright suspicion Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's pledge in
recent months to pull out by July. Many Lebanese officials saw
Barak's words as a bluff and a maneuvering tactic.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon and Syria -- the main power broker in Lebanon -- had also
added a new demand in recent months that the pullout be part of an
overall Mideast peace accord, which has appeared unlikely soon with
the Israel-Syria talks deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
   Beirut and Damascus' refusal to welcome the withdrawal had
frustrated Israeli officials, concerned about possible guerrilla
attacks into north Israel. U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright this month called it ''strange'' that Israel was being
criticized ''for wanting to withdraw from another country.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel has said Syria is pushing Lebanon to oppose the
withdrawal, since the unilateral pullback could deprive Damascus of
a bargaining chip in future talks -- in the form of pressure on
Israel from Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Israel officially notified the United Nations of its plans
Monday, saying it would pull troops back to the internationally
recognized border by July 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council drafted a presidential statement Tuesday
welcoming the Israeli move and asking Secretary-General Kofi Annan
to start preparations, particularly concerning defining the border
and security. The council is expected to approve the statement
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hoss' statement did not mention misgivings shared by Lebanon and
Syria over the pullback. It said only that the content of the
Israeli notification is ''the subject of study and consultation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoss also did not repeat his government's earlier warning that
it won't be responsible for reining in guerrillas battling Israeli
troops, or armed Palestinians living in refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, which has about 30,000 troops in Lebanon, however,
remained suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ''Israel is undoubtedly insincere in telling the United Nations
and the U.N. Security Council permanent members that it wants to
withdraw from Lebanon by July,'' said an editorial by the
English-language Syria Times, which like other Damascus papers
reflects the government's thinking.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Hezbollah guerrillas attacked an Israeli outpost,
wounding one soldier. Israeli retaliatory fire killed a Syrian
worker and wounded four other people, Lebanese security officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah responded by firing across the border into northern
Israel. Witnesses and military sources reported said six shells
fell, causing no injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Later, two Israeli jets fired missiles at suspected guerrilla
targets in a central section of the occupied zone from which the
shells were believed to have come.
</P>
<P>
   Israel moved into Lebanon in 1982 and created an occupation
security zone in the south in 1985 to protect its northern towns
from guerrilla attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-18-00 2133 </TRAILER>
