<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Panel Orders Cab Safety Moves  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Alarmed by the recent killings of livery cab
drivers, the city's Taxi and Limousine Commission voted unanimously
Tuesday to require all drivers to install either bulletproof
partitions or digital security cameras in their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has pledged $5 million in a grant program
to help pay for the security devices.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's what the federation asked the mayor to do, and the mayor
has granted us our wish,'' said New York State Federation of Taxi
Drivers President Fernando Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Seven drivers have been killed this year, and 11 were killed in
1999, according to police statistics. None of the drivers killed
this year had a partition, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said another driver was wounded Tuesday when a passenger
attacked him with a machete.
</P>
<P>
   Commission chairwoman Diane McGrath McKechnie said the grant
will pay for drivers to buy partitions, which cost between $250 and
$350, but will pay only up to $350 for cameras, which start at
$600. She estimated that about half of the city's 41,000 livery
drivers have neither security device.
</P>
<P>
   The only exception to the new rule will be for livery cars owned
by companies that cater to corporate clients and take only vouchers
or credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also stressed to livery drivers that they must
stop picking up street fares, something only yellow cabs are
allowed to do so. Livery drivers must be dispatched to passengers,
but many flout the rule to make extra money. Of the seven drivers
killed this year, police say six were killed by passengers they
picked up on the street.
</P>
<P>
   The commission adopted the rule on an emergency basis for the
next 60 days. Before the temporary measure expires, the commission
will hold public hearings to make it permanent. Drivers have 30
days to comply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
