<HEADLINE> Storm, Wind Rip Los Angeles  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL CHAVEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A powerful storm raked Southern California
early Tuesday with pounding rain and fierce winds that tore up
mobile homes and businesses and left thousands without power.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters said another storm was expected to hit Thursday but
predicted it would not pack the fury of the one that began early
Monday and unleashed a destructive ''microburst'' windstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit was the city of Paramount in southeastern Los
Angeles County, where high winds severely damaged 71 mobile homes
and at least a dozen businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The landscape resembled tornado-type damage more associated with
Oklahoma or Kansas than Southern California: hundreds of uprooted
trees, crumpled mobile homes knocked off their foundations, twisted
metal and awnings dangling from power lines.
</P>
<P>
   ''Earthquakes are a dream compared to this,'' said mobile home
resident Diane Sullivan, who described the gale as a moaning sound
that grew louder and louder. ''We never had any damage from an
earthquake. I don't know how people can live in the Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of serious injuries, said Assistant City
Manager Linda Benedetti. City officials declared an emergency,
making Paramount eligible for state aid.
</P>
<P>
   Storm damage was spread throughout the Los Angeles basin. In
Diamond Bar, winds collapsed the roof of a fitness center and
lightning zapped a home in Altadena.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service studied debris patterns and fallen
trees and determined it was a so-called microburst rather than a
tornado, said meteorologist Clint Simpson. The windspeeds were
estimated at 75 mph to 90 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The wind, rain and lightning were part of a storm that rolled
into the region Monday morning, contributing to hundreds of traffic
accidents on Los Angeles County freeways. Four people died during
highway crashes Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At least 45,000 Southern California Edison customers were
without power or had service briefly interrupted during the two-day
period, company spokesman Steven Conroy said. Service to nearly all
customers was expected to be restored by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Communities from Los Angeles to San Luis Obispo counties
recorded 1 inches to 4 inches of rain from early Monday morning
through 10 a.m. Tuesday, the National Weather Service said.
Monday's storm totals set records for the date in many areas,
including downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not unusual to get a storm in April. It is unusual to get
this amount of rain in April,'' Mike Wofford said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-18-00 2153 </TRAILER>
