<HEADLINE> Court says Florio can't use county committee label  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A state Superior Court judge in Union
County on Tuesday barred Jim Florio from using a ballot slogan that
was nearly identical to the name of the county committee.
</P>
<P>
   Florio had planned to call himself and his slate of candidates
the ''Union County Democratic Committee, Inc.'' on the June primary
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Edward W. Beglin, Jr. said that name infringed on the
existing Union County Democratic Committee, a group entitled to
''protect its name and goodwill associated with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio does not have the backing of the Union County democratic
organization and its leaders. Instead they endorsed investment
banker Jon Corzine over the former governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Were any other organization to use its name, particularly as a
slogan for certain candidates used to designate their affiliation
on the primary ballot, only public confusion and misunderstanding
would result,'' Beglin said.
</P>
<P>
   Florio now plans to use the word ''Democrat'' as his label,
campaign spokesman Jim Lanard said. Florio's lawyers have made that
offer to the Union County organization, as well as groups in
Mercer, Middlesex and Essex counties, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
