<HEADLINE> Hutchinson Tech Eliminating 950 Jobs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUTCHINSON, Minn. (AP) -- Hutchinson Technology is eliminating
950 jobs in Wisconsin, South Dakota and Minnesota because of weak
demand for its computer components, the company announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs come on top of 600 jobs eliminated during the first
six months of the fiscal year at Hutchinson, the world's leading
supplier of suspension assemblies for computer disk drives, which
supports the mechanism that allows users to read from and write to
the hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it will immediately suspend photoetching in Eau
Claire, Wis., and consolidate those operations into its plant in
Hutchinson in central Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts will leave Hutchinson with about 5,250 employees,
including approximately 2,500 in Hutchinson, 1,050 in Sioux Falls,
1,510 in Eau Claire and 190 in Plymouth.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne M. Fortun, president and chief executive officer, said the
changes announced Tuesday along with other cost-cutting measures
will generate an estimated $110 million in annual savings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the moves, Fortun said the company does not expect to
return to profitability in the current fiscal year. It expects to
report a third quarter net loss of 35 to 45 cents per share,
excluding charges for severance costs and asset write-downs of 26
to 35 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson Technology made the announcement as it reported a net
loss of $13 million, or 53 cents per share, on net sales of $111
million, for the second quarter, which ended March 26. In the
second quarter of fiscal 1999, the company reported net earnings of
$13.7 million, or 54 cents per share, on net sales of $152 million.
</P>
<P>
   Fortun said sales for the third quarter are projected to dip to
$100 million to $105 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
