<HEADLINE> 4 Vie in Primary for Kerrey's Seat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- One of five candidates for the GOP
nomination for Democratic Sen. Bob Kerrey's seat dropped out of the
race Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Elliott Rustad, 66, was a distant second in the Republican
field behind state Attorney General Don Stenberg, according to a
poll conducted by his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''In order to win I would have to wage a (negative) campaign
that could divide the Republican party and that I'm not willing to
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rustad retired from his dermatology practice and sold his
Milford ranch before starting his campaign in November. Kerrey is
not seeking a third term.
</P>
<P>
   Rustad's decision narrows the field of candidates, but not by
much. Stenberg, Scottsbluff agribusinessman David Hergert,
Secretary of State Scott Moore and former state senator John DeCamp
are vying for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Ben Nelson is the likely Democratic nominee.
</P>
