<HEADLINE> Japan Banks To Merge  </HEADLINE>
By GINNY PARKER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd. and Mitsubishi
Trust and Banking Corp. agreed Wednesday to set up a joint holding
company, which would be the world's fifth-largest financial group.
</P>
<P>
   The two banks will form the holding company and integrate their
operations by April next year, officials said. The alliance would
have $837 billion in deposits and other assets.
</P>
<P>
   The firm would manage $433 billion in pension and other trusts
as it combines two BOT-Mitsubishi subsidiaries -- Nippon Trust Bank
and Tokyo Trust Bank -- with Mitsubishi Trust. The merger of the
three trust banks will be completed by October, 2001, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new holding company will be listed on both the Tokyo Stock
Exchange and the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The move will enable the banks involved to compete against other
planned megagroups in the financial industry.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese banks have been consolidating their operations to
recover from billions of dollars in bad loans made in the
speculative lending boom of the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest of these mergers is the Mizuho Financial Group,
which announced in August that it was creating an institution with
$1.3 trillion in assets by merging Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, Fuji Bank,
and the Industrial Bank of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Sanwa Bank, Tokai Bank and Asahi Bank also plan to
merge, creating the country's second-largest bank with $1 trillion
in assets.
</P>
<P>
   BOT-Mitsubishi and Mitsubishi Trust will initially continue
current operations under the joint holding company, to be named
Mitsubishi Tokyo Financial Group.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they will merge overlapping operations and
concentrate on their individual strengths, according to the Nihon
Keizai, Japan's leading business newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
