<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Gather To Protest in Brazil  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTO SEGURO, Brazil (AP) -- Hundreds of Indians held ceremonies
Tuesday to counter official celebrations of the 500th anniversary
of the arrival of Europeans -- an event many Indians call ''the
invasion.''
</P>
<P>
   On foot and by bus, in facepaint and feathers, Indians from
scores of tribes gathered at the Coroa Vermelha reservation, about
500 miles northeast of Rio de Janeiro, to demand that the
government speed up creation of Indian reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Ceremonies on Saturday will mark the anniversary of the
Portuguese arrival in Brazil in 1500. Explorer Pedro Alvarez Cabral
made his first landfall near Porto Seguro.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say up to 5 million Indians inhabited the country in
1500 compared with just 330,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   In coming days, the Indians will hold conferences on the
reservation just outside Porto Segura and build a monument to
Indians who died, which they hope to dedicate on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I say that these 500 years were a time of bitterness, of
anguish, of death,'' Pataxo chief Nailton Pataxo said in a
statement released by the Missionary Indigenous Council, linked to
Brazil's Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   ''From now on, we want to show that Indians are more
organized,'' the statement said. ''We will come out of this march
and this conference much more prepared to fight for the recovery
and demarcation of our lands.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest skirmish over land, two Pataxo Indians were
wounded by gunshots Tuesday in a clash with landowners who invaded
Indian land about 125 miles from Porto Seguro.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, around 200 students clashed with police in a
protest against the commemoration in Fortaleza, about 1,370 miles
northeast of Rio. The students had been stoning a clock set up for
the celebrations, then began pelting police who tried to break up
the protest.
</P>
<P>
   A student and five police officers were hurt, and ten students
were arrested, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions rose earlier this month when 200 police troopers
invaded the Coroa Vermelha reservation and bulldozed the 5-foot
concrete base of the Indians' memorial.
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando Henrique Cardoso met with Indian leaders in
Brasilia, the capital, and called the destruction of the monument
''absurd.'' Still, he canceled a scheduled visit to the reservation
and is to stay in town for the official commemoration.
</P>
<P>
   Since the monument was destroyed, the police presence has been
beefed up and roadblocks have been set up along key highways. Bahia
state Gov. Cesar Borges said he plans to put between 5,000 and
9,000 police in the area during the celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians could get support from the Landless Rural Workers
Movement, which has pledged to step up land invasions this week to
call attention to the need for agrarian reform. A group of movement
sympathizers is in Porto Seguro, although the government hopes to
move them out before Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
