<HEADLINE> Mavericks 112, Lakers 102  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MARSHALL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Michael Finley scored 25 points as the Dallas
Mavericks ended their 19-game losing streak to the Los Angeles
Lakers with a 112-102 victory Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Nash added 23 as Dallas beat the Lakers for the first time
since April 5, 1995. It was the Mavericks' eighth win in their last
nine.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' Shaquille O'Neal scored 38 points and had 20
rebounds, but hit just 8 of 19 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   In three previous meetings this season, Dallas coach Don Nelson
had his players foul O'Neal nearly every time he touched the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The ploy didn't work then as O'Neal averaged 30 points and 14
rebounds in three Lakers' wins.
</P>
<P>
   This time it did.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson held off employing ''Hack-a-Shaq'' until the final minute
of the third quarter, but the strategy keyed a run that put Dallas
in control.
</P>
<P>
   After Bradley knocked O'Neal to the floor with a hard foul,
6-foot-3, 185-pound guard Damon Jones came into the game with just
over a minute left. His sole purpose was to foul O'Neal, who
entered shooting 52 percent from the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   Twice Jones grabbed O'Neal around the waist away from the ball,
the second time coming before the ball even crossed midcourt.
O'Neal missed six straight free throws in the final 49 seconds of
the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas finished the quarter with a 6-0 run for a 80-75 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks went on 9-1 run to take a 101-88 lead with 3:45
left. Cedric Ceballos capped the run with a driving, left-handed
layup. Los Angeles got no closer than six the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos finished with 21 points, and Finley added five assists
and four rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' Kobe Bryant had 16 points and 14 rebounds, but made
just 7 of 20 shots.Notes: With 47 minutes played Michael Finley has 3,416 on the
season, breaking his own team record. The previous mark was 3,394
in 1997-98. ... Energetic new Mavericks owner Mark Cuban addressed
the crowd before and after the game, the team's final home game
this season. ... The Lakers had won their last eight games in
Dallas. ... The Lakers, the highest-drawing visiting team in the
league, drew a sellout of 18,190 Tuesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
