<HEADLINE> Packers RB To Attend Drug Course  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARKHAM, Ill. (AP) -- Green Bay Packers running back De'Mond
Parker appeared in court Tuesday on a marijuana possession charge,
and agreed to attend a court-approved drug course.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas O'Hara of Cook County Circuit Court continued the
case until July 26 when the court will get a report on whether
Parker successfully completed the program.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors often drop charges upon successful completion of the
course.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, 23, of Green Bay, Wis., was arrested April 1 after 7
grams of marijuana was found in an automobile in which he was
seated, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   They said Parker was parked on the street and loud music was
coming from the car. He also was holding a partially burnt
hand-rolled cigarette in his hand, which he dropped on the ground
when police asked him to leave the auto.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who played college football at the University of
Oklahoma, was with the Packers in 1999. He finished last season on
injured reserve with a knee injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
