<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate votes to change GOP presidential primary ballots  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Republican presidential candidates will have
an easier time campaigning in New York during the next primary if
legislation passed by the state Senate becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which passed the Senate Tuesday, would allow New
York Republicans to vote directly for candidates instead of
delegates, which is the current rule. Voters have called the
ballots confusing because they list the delegates' names first and
the candidates' names second, and in smaller print.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also open the election to more candidates because
it would allow any candidate on the ballot who raised at least
$5,000 in each of 20 states; is certified with the state Board of
Elections as being a nationally recognized and serious candidate;
or collected at least 5,000 supporting signatures from New York
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Under current primary rules, GOP candidates must collect
signatures from party members in any of the state's 31
congressional districts in which the candidates want to field
delegate slates.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a ballot access bill that approaches the presidential
primary in a very, very beneficial way,'' said Sen. Serphin
Maltese, a Republican from Queens who sponsored the bill. ''It's
kind of a warm and fuzzy approach to presidential politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders are confident the bill will become law, even
though it still needs Assembly approval and the signature of Gov.
George Pataki and had a hard time in the Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic leader of the Senate, Martin Connor, said certain
parts of the proposal, like a winner-take-all provision, could be
unconstitutional and violate the federal Voting Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   That provision means a candidate who captures a majority of the
vote will get all New York's delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're going to not get cleared by the Justice Department for
winner-take-all. But that's your problem,'' he said in Senate
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Hope, chairwoman of the state Democratic Party, said the
proposal is definitely an improvement but still has flaws,
especially the winner-take-all provision.
</P>
<P>
   ''That gives the bosses control over the final selection,'' she
said. ''Frankly, the deck is stacked in favor of the organizational
candidate anyway, but then they further stack the deck by saying
all they have to get is get 51 percent of the vote to take all the
delegates.''
</P>
<P>
   But many experts applauded the proposal, saying something needed
to be done to change the ballot laws, which caused state GOP
officials some embarrassment during the 2000 primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''New York is one of the worst states in the country in terms of
ballot access,'' said Rachel Leon, executive director of the state
chapter of Common Cause. ''So in general, we support any changes
that put elections back in the hands of voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, a Republican, originally proposed the bill.
He and State GOP Chairman William Powers led an unsuccessful effort
to use the state's complex ballot access rules to keep everyone but
Texas Gov. George W. Bush off the New York primary ballot this
year. Arizona Sen. John McCain began calling Pataki and Powers
''comrade'' and compared the New York ballot access rules to the
old Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge's order eventually opened up the ballot to
McCain and other GOP presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a feeling some of the lesser-known candidates had
trouble getting on the ballot,'' Maltese said. ''We want to make
sure that any candidate who really has an opportunity to be
president can run in New York state.''
</P>
<P>
   But Common Cause's Leon cautioned that changing the ballots just
to stymie the McCain backlash is the wrong thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're concerned that the Republicans and the governor are
reacting because of McCain's struggles,'' Leon said. ''We don't
want to see just his problem solved. There are a lot of candidates
out there whose problems won't be aired like McCain's were.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Allen, a spokesman for the state GOP, said he could not
comment on the bill because he hadn't seen it.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also requires all polling places in the state to be
open from 6 a.m. to 9 p.m. during the spring primary. Those hours
are now in force only in New York City, the suburban counties
surrounding the city and Erie County. Primary polls open at noon in
the rest of the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 2358 </TRAILER>
