<DOCNO> APW20000418.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton visits Adirondacks, criticizes Giulianienvironmental record  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG MOOSE, N.Y. (AP) -- In a pre-Earth Day environmental foray,
Hillary Rodham Clinton took her campaign into the heart of the
Adirondacks where she vowed to battle acid rain and criticized
Senate rival Rudolph Giuliani's environmental record.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said she would continue her environmental
offensive today with a stop on Long Island to discuss problems
facing Long Island Sound and the island's lobster industry.
</P>
<P>
   During her appearance Tuesday, Clinton also questioned the New
York City mayor's campaign payments of $1 million to conservative
direct-mail fund-raising guru Richard Viguerie. With Viguerie's
help, Giuliani has outraised Clinton in their Senate race, $19
million to $12 million, according to records made public Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think hiring Richard Viguerie, who does all of the
direct-mail for a lot of the most extreme and right-wing political,
public figures in our country is a disturbing development,'' she
told a news conference at the rustic Covewood Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Calling again for the mayor to release all his direct-mail,
fund-raising letters, Clinton said ''the people of New York deserve
to know what he is saying to try to raise money from people who
historically give money to Jerry Falwell or Ollie North or Jesse
Helms.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani campaign has repeatedly refused to make public its
fund-raising letters while the Clinton campaign has made its own
available as well as those of the mayor's it has been able to
obtain.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think that is the way most New Yorkers think,
regardless of party,'' Clinton said of the Giuliani letters. ''I
think most New Yorkers have a much more mainstream, practical view
about what the political process should produce.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, ever since the Viguerie connection became public,
Clinton has sought to use it to help her portray Giuliani as
someone who would work in the Senate with the conservative
Republicans who currently control Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady spoke at a news conference set up by the
Adirondack Council aimed at boosting attention for anti-acid rain
legislation that was sponsored by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. It
would sharply limit emissions from power plants in the Midwest --
considered a source of pollution that has contributed to the death
of Adirondack lakes and ponds.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she hoped Congress would pass Moynihan's
legislation as ''a going-away present to him.'' She is running for
the seat he is vacating at the end of the year and said she would
carry on his fight if Congress failed to pass his legislation this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Giuliani's environmental record, Clinton said she
would be on Long Island today to discuss the demise of the lobster
fishery there and planned to raise the issue of dumping into Long
Island Sound by New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said she was also ''worried about the loosening
of regulations that the city has done in the watershed that
protects the (upstate) reservoirs that supply the water to the
city.'' That is a theme that has been pressed by other critics of
the mayor in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss said the
mayor has a ''superb'' record on the environment and contended
Clinton has ''no environmental policy or record.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think she even knows where the watershed region is
located,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Glover Weiss also dismissed criticism of Viguerie by saying,
''when the Clintons get in trouble or need a scapegoat, they always
blame the vast right wing conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Who knows, maybe Mrs. Clinton will blame the right wing
conspiracy for killing the lobsters on Long Island Sound,'' Glover
Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's news conference was held on the shores of Big Moose
Lake, scene of Theodore Dreiser's ''An American Tragedy,'' a novel
based on a true story about the murder of a pregnant young women
who had been accompanied to the lake by her lover.
</P>
<P>
   While the reception at the lodge for Clinton was warm, thanks in
part to a roaring fire in the massive stone fireplace, the first
lady's electoral chances in the heavily Republican area seem
chillier.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have Democrats up here,'' said lodge owner and
Republican, Claude ''Major'' Bowes.
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Ellis assured the first lady that ''my wife, Jean, and
I are Republicans, but you have our votes.'' It turned out their
son had taught with the first lady at the University of Arkansas'
law school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-18-00 2359 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
